## Sample Earn Income Tasks

These examples use Piloting to work as a pilot or Legal Lore to perform legal work.

<b>Trained</b> run speedy errands on your enercycle, do legal research<br><b>Expert</b> pilot a small salvage ship, present minor court cases<br><b>Master</b> pilot a large research vessel or freighter, present important court cases<br><b>Legendary</b> run an interplanetary pilot training program, argue a case against an Embri Speaker and their coterie in their own court

## Income Examples

The following examples show the kinds of tasks your character might take on to Earn Income during low-level and high-level play.  
### Chk Chk Brews Stim-Caf

Chk Chk is a 3rd-level envoy and an expert barista. He has a **Lore: Stim-caf** modifier of +7.

He spends 30 days of downtime working shifts at a streetside dispenser in the Uscru District on Coruscant, where he just finished a mission. The GM decides working at the fast-paced but grimy stand is a **2nd-level task** and secretly sets the DC at 16.

On his first shift, Chk Chk rolls a 19 on his Lore: Stim-caf check for a result of 26, **critically succeeding**! He earns 5 credits for his efforts (like a success at a 3rd-level task) and continues working for 6 more days, for a total of 35 credits.

At that point, the GM offers Chk Chk a choice: he can finish out the month slinging caf in the lower levels or accept a job offer from a trendy refresh-bar in the Senate District (a **4th-level task**). Chk Chk takes the job in the posh government plaza, despite knowing the senators won''t be as friendly as the district locals. He switches to his new job and attempts a new Lore: Stim-caf check against DC 19. Rolling a 13, he gets a result of 20, **barely succeeding**! He earns 8 credits per day. The busy politicians love Chk Chk’s extra strong dark roast (with blue milk foam).

The GM rules that the shop is pleased to let Chk Chk work there for the remainder of his downtime, a total of 23 days. Chk Chk gladly accepts and earns a respectable total of 219 credits that month.

----------

### Dae Performs in the Galactic Arts

Dae is a 16th-level operative and a legendary dancer. With their Twi’lek Grace ancestry feat, they have a +2 status bonus to Performance checks, for a total **Performance modifier of +30**.

With 30 days of downtime ahead of them, Dae decides to enter a contest to appear in _Hyper-Space Hype_, a Core Worlds hologram music video.

The GM decides that getting through every round of the contest and earning a spot takes a full two weeks and is a **level 14 task**, secretly setting the DC at 32.

Dae rolls a 10 on their Performance check for a result of 40. **Success**! After 14 days of tough competition, Dae has made it into the recording! The GM explains that the advance pay is 2,800 credits (incidentally covering the 200 credits they earned every day for 14 days).

The next 16 days of downtime are quite busy for Dae. The GM explains that the stakes are high, as there’s been a surprise announcement: _Hyper-Space Hype_ will be performed live on “The Hutt''s Talent Extravaganza!” Winning the competition is a monumental **20th-level task**, and the GM secretly sets the DC at 40. After several days of practice, the show is on, and Dae rolls a 17, handily impressing the Hutt cartel judges with a result of 47! Dae’s share of the first prize payout is a whopping 32,000 credits (representing 2,000 credits per day for 16 days). Dae’s not sure how they’re going to spend their earnings, but it won’t have to be on blue milk!

## Extra Preparation

When Earning Income, you might be able to spend days of downtime to prepare for your task and lower the DC of the skill check. This might involve rehearsing a performance set list, studying a topic, and so on. The GM determines how long preparation takes and how much the DC changes. This is most useful when you''re trying a task that''s higher level than you.  
**Ending or Interrupting Tasks**  
When a task you''re doing is complete, or if you stop in the middle of one, you normally have to find a new task if you want to keep Earning Income. For instance, if you quit your job working at the space docks, you''ll need to find another place of employment instead of picking up where you left off. This usually takes 1 day or more of downtime looking for leads on new jobs.  
However, you might pause a task due to an adventure or event that wouldn''t prevent you from returning to the old job later. The GM might decide that you can pick up where you left off, assuming the task hasn''t been completed by others in your absence. Whether you roll a new skill check when you resume is also up to the GM. Generally speaking, if you had a good initial roll and want to keep it, you can, but if you had a bad initial roll, you can''t try for a better one by pausing to do something else. If your statistics changed during the break—usually because you leveled up while adventuring—you can attempt a new check.',	NULL,	'Downtime'),
('actSeek',	'Seek',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You scan an area for signs of creatures or objects, possibly including secret doors or hazards. Choose an area to scan. The GM determines the area you can scan with one Seek action—almost always 30 feet or less in any dimension. The GM might impose a penalty if you search far away from you or adjust the number of actions it takes to Seek a particularly cluttered area.  
  
The GM attempts a single secret Perception check for you and compares the result to the Stealth DCs of any undetected or hidden creatures in the area, or the DC to detect each object in the area (as determined by the GM or by someone Concealing the Object). A creature you detect might remain hidden, rather than becoming observed, if you''re using an imprecise sense or if an effect (such as invisibility) prevents the subject from being observed.

<b>Critical Success</b> Any undetected or hidden creature you critically succeeded against becomes observed by you. You learn the location of objects in the area you critically succeeded against.<br><b>Success</b> Any undetected creature you succeeded against becomes hidden from you instead of undetected, and any hidden creature you succeeded against becomes observed by you. You learn the location of any object or get a clue to its whereabouts, as determined by the GM.',	NULL,	'Concentrate, Secret'),
('actHack',	'Slice',	NULL,	'You have a slicer''s toolkit.',	NULL,	'You try to access, control, or change an active secured system. In most cases, this attempt is made against a local computer terminal or databank that you access directly or indirectly through the use of a slicer kit or data spikes. Attempt a Computers check to determine if you can slice into the targeted system. Systems with heavy encryption might require multiple successes to access.

<b>Critical Success</b> You access the system, or you achieve two successes toward accessing a system requiring more than one success. You leave no trace of your slicing.<br><b>Success</b> You access the system, or you achieve one success toward accessing a system that requires more than one success.<br><b>Failure</b> You fail to access the system or achieve any success toward accessing a system that requires more than one success. Some secure systems might have countermeasures that activate on a failure.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> You trigger ingrained security protocols or completely lock yourself out of the system. Being locked out of a system prevents you from attempting another check to access it for the next hour.',	NULL,	'Exploration'),
('actRequest',	'Request',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You can make a request of a creature that''s friendly or helpful to you. You must couch the request in terms that the target would accept given their current attitude toward you. The GM sets the DC based on the difficulty of the request. Some requests are unsavory or impossible, and even a helpful NPC would never agree to them.

<b>Critical Success</b> The target agrees to your request without qualifications.<br><b>Success</b> The target agrees to your request, but they might demand added provisions or alterations to the request.<br><b>Failure</b> The target refuses the request, though they might propose an alternative that is less extreme.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> Not only does the target refuse the request, but their attitude toward you decreases by one step due to the temerity of the request.',	NULL,	'Auditory, Concentrate, Lingustic, Mental'),
('actDemoralize',	'Demoralize',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'With a sudden shout, a well-timed taunt, or a cutting putdown, you can shake an enemy''s resolve. Choose a creature within 30 feet of you who you''re aware of. Attempt an Intimidation check against that target''s Will DC. If the target doesn''t understand the language you are speaking, or you''re not speaking a language, you take a –4 circumstance penalty to the check. Regardless of your result, the target is temporarily immune to your attempts to Demoralize it for 10 minutes.

<b>Critical Success</b> The target becomes frightened 2.<br><b>Success</b> The target becomes frightened 1.',	NULL,	'Auditory, Concentrate, Emotion, Fear, Mental'),
('actTreatDisease',	'Treat Disease',	NULL,	'You’re wearing or holding a medkit.',	NULL,	'You spend at least 8 hours caring for a diseased creature. Attempt a Medicine check against the disease''s DC. After you attempt to Treat a Disease for a creature, you can''t try again until after that creature''s next save against the disease.

<b>Critical Success</b> You grant the creature a +4 circumstance bonus to its next saving throw against the disease.<br><b>Success</b> You grant the creature a +2 circumstance bonus to its next saving throw against the disease.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> Your efforts cause the creature to take a –2 circumstance penalty to its next save against the disease.',	NULL,	'Downtime, Manipulate'),
('actTreatPoison',	'Treat Poison',	'[one-action]',	'You’re wearing or holding a medkit.',	NULL,	'You treat a patient to prevent the spread of poison. Attempt a Medicine check against the poison''s DC. After you attempt to Treat a Poison for a creature, you can''t try again until after the next time that creature attempts a save against the poison.

<b>Critical Success</b> You grant the creature a +4 circumstance bonus to its next saving throw against the poison.<br><b>Success</b> You grant the creature a +2 circumstance bonus to its next saving throw against the poison.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> Your efforts cause the creature to take a –2 circumstance penalty to its next save against the poison.',	NULL,	'Manipulate'),
('actAreaFire',	'Area Fire',	'[two-actions]',	'You’re wielding a weapon with the area trait.',	NULL,	'You attempt to hit each creature in a designated area, which has a range equal to the weapon''s range increment (for cone or line) or a designated radius of the explosion (for burst). For burst, you can position the center point anywhere within your first range increment. Any creatures in the area must succeed at a basic Reflex save against your class DC plus the tracking value of the weapon (you don''t roll an attack roll). This damage is area damage. Creatures who critically fail this save are subject to effects that occur on a critical hit with this weapon, including the weapon''s critical specialization effect. Area Fire has an expend equal to the value listed on the weapon.',	NULL,	'Area, Attack'),
('actTakeControl',	'Take Control',	'[one-action]',	'You are aboard a vehicle and adjacent to its controls.',	NULL,	'You grab the wheel or some other mechanism in order to control the vehicle. Attempt a piloting check; on a success, you become the vehicle''s pilot, or regain control of the vehicle if it was uncontrolled. Some vehicles have complicated controls that cause this action to become a multi-action activity.',	NULL,	'Manipulate'),
('actStop',	'Stop',	'[one-action]',	'You are piloting a vehicle in motion.',	NULL,	'You bring the vehicle to a stop.',	NULL,	'Manipulate'),
('actNavigate',	'Navigate',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'You plan a short journey. While this is most often used when traveling with a mech, vehicle, or starship, the same skill can be used to determine the optimal route to take while traveling on foot. This lets you plan a general heading on a planetoid or guide your starship on an in-system voyage. If you''re navigating a short journey, you typically attempt a Piloting check only once per day, but some environments or changes might necessitate rolling more often. The GM determines the DC and how long this activity takes (usually just a minute or so). More unusual locales or those you''re unfamiliar with might require you to have a minimum proficiency rank to Navigate.

<b>Critical Success</b> You get an excellent sense of where you are. If you are in an environment with cardinal directions, you know them exactly.<br><b>Success</b> You gain enough orientation to avoid becoming hopelessly lost. If you are in an environment with cardinal directions, you have a sense of those directions.',	NULL,	'Exploration, Secret'),
('actArrestAFall',	'Arrest a Fall',	'[reaction]',	'You have a fly Speed.',	'You fall.',	'You attempt your choice of an Acrobatics check or Reflex save to slow your fall. The DC is typically 15, but it might be higher due to air turbulence or other circumstances.

<b>Success</b> You take no damage from the fall.',	NULL,	NULL),
('actPlotCourse',	'Plot Course',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'You prepare for a longer journey into the stars, likely making use of your starship''s hyperdrive (or similar lightspeed device). Attempt a Piloting check to determine if you can calculate a safe astrogation route to your ultimate destination. The GM determines how long this activity takes and the DC (GM Core).

<b>Critical Success</b> You manage to reach your destination in half the expected time (minimum 1 day).<br><b>Success</b> You create a usable navigational plan that gets you to your intended destination on time.<br><b>Failure</b> Your calculations have several problems, and you end up reaching your destination late.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> You drop out of hyperspace in an unfamiliar star system, requiring you to calculate a new course to your destination (likely at an increased DC due to the unfamiliar starting point).',	NULL,	'Exploration, Secret'),
('actCommandAnAnimal',	'Command an Animal',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You issue an order to an animal. Attempt a Nature check against the animal''s Will DC. The GM might adjust the DC if the animal has a good attitude toward you, you suggest a course of action it was predisposed toward, or you offer it a treat.
You automatically fail if the animal is hostile or unfriendly to you. If the animal is helpful to you, increase your degree of success by one step. You might be able to Command an Animal more easily with a feat like Ride.
Most animals know the Drop Prone, Leap, Seek, Stand, Stride, and Strike basic actions. If an animal knows an activity, such as a sqoux''s Go for the Eyes, you can Command the Animal to perform the activity, but you must spend as many actions on Command an Animal as the activity''s number of actions. You can also spend multiple actions to Command the Animal to perform that number of basic actions on its next turn; for instance, you could spend 3 actions to Command an Animal to Stride three times or to Stride twice and then make a Strike.

<b>Success</b> The animal does as you command on its next turn.<br><b>Failure</b> The animal is hesitant or resistant, and it does nothing.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> The animal misbehaves or misunderstands, and it takes some other action determined by the GM.

## Commanded Animals

Issuing commands to an animal doesn''t always go smoothly. An animal is an independent creature with limited intelligence. Most animals understand only the simplest instructions, so you might be able to instruct an animal to move to a certain square but not dictate a specific path to get there, or command it to attack a certain creature but not to make its attack nonlethal. The GM decides the specifics of the action the animal uses.
The animal does what you commanded as soon as it can, usually as its first action on its next turn. If you successfully commanded it multiple times, it does what you said in order. It forgets all commands beyond what it can accomplish on its turn. If multiple people command the same animal, the GM determines how the animal reacts. The GM might also make the DC higher if someone has already tried to Command the Animal that round.
If you have a pet, animal companion, familiar, or similar minion, you can command it much more effectively.',	NULL,	'Auditory, Concentrate'),
('actDrive',	'Drive',	'[one-action], [two-actions], or [three-actions]',	'You are piloting a vehicle.',	NULL,	'You pilot your vehicle to move. Decide how many actions you intend to spend before you begin Driving. The effects depend on the number of actions you spend. You can''t Drive through spaces occupied by creatures, even if they''re allies.

[one-action] Attempt a piloting check. On a success, the vehicle moves up to its Speed and can turn normally. On a failure, the vehicle moves its Speed in a straight line. On a critical failure, the vehicle moves its Speed in a straight line and becomes uncontrolled.<br>[two-actions] (reckless) The vehicle moves up to twice its Speed in a straight line at the vehicle''s current heading.<br>[three-actions] (reckless) You take a –5 penalty on your piloting check to maintain control of the vehicle. The vehicle moves up to three times its Speed in a straight line at the vehicle''s current heading.',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actConcealAnObject',	'Conceal an Object',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You hide a small object on your person (such as a weapon of light Bulk). When you try to sneak a concealed object past someone who might notice it, the GM rolls your Stealth check and compares it to this passive observer''s Perception DC. Once the GM rolls your check for a concealed object, that same result is used no matter how many passive observers you try to sneak it past. If a creature is specifically searching you for an item, it can attempt a Perception check against your Stealth DC (finding the object on success). You can also conceal an object somewhere other than your person, such as in a garbage bin or inside a secret compartment behind a computer console. In this case, characters Seeking in an area compare their Perception check results to your Stealth DC to determine whether they find the object.

<b>Success</b> The object remains undetected.<br><b>Failure</b> The searcher finds the object.',	NULL,	'Manipulation, Secret'),
('actAutoFire',	'Auto-Fire',	'[two-actions]',	'You''re wielding a weapon with the automatic trait.',	NULL,	'You attempt to hit each creature in a cone with a range equal to half the weapon''s range increment without making an attack roll. Any creature in the area takes weapon damage (basic Reflex save against your class DC plus the tracking value of the weapon). This damage is area damage. Creatures that critically fail this save are subject to effects that occur on a critical hit with this weapon, including the weapon''s critical specialization effect. Auto-Fire has an expend equal to the number of targets in the area × 2.',	NULL,	'Area, Attack'),
('actSenseDirection',	'Sense Direction',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'Using the position of astronomical objects in the sky, traits of the geography or flora, or the behavior of fauna, you can stay oriented in the wild. Typically, you attempt a Survival check only once per day, but some environments or changes might necessitate rolling more often. The GM determines the DC and how long this activity takes (usually just a minute or so). More unusual locales or those you''re unfamiliar with might require you to have a minimum proficiency rank to Sense Direction. Without a comm unit, you take a –2 item penalty to checks to Sense Direction.

<b>Critical Success</b> You get an excellent sense of where you are. If you are in an environment with cardinal directions, you know them exactly.<br><b>Success</b> You gain enough orientation to avoid becoming hopelessly lost. If you are in an environment with cardinal directions, you have a sense of those directions.

## Sample Sense Direction Tasks

<b>Untrained</b> determine a cardinal direction<br><b>Trained</b> find an overgrown path in a forest<br><b>Expert</b> navigate a simple maze<br><b>Master</b> navigate a relatively featureless moon<br><b>Legendary</b> navigate an ever-changing occult realm<br>

## Navigating the Neon Jungle

Cities can be difficult to navigate, even with the use of digital maps. Construction, demolition, detours, and traffic are common in densely populated settlements, such as a bustling space station in a high-traffic system or a remote mining colony on a dangerous planet with a toxic atmosphere. An up-to-date digital navigator might suffice for simple navigation but is likely to miss all the paths and shortcuts that require a Sense Direction check to find without a local guide.',	NULL,	'Exploration, Secret'),
('actSneak',	'Sneak',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You attempt to move to another place while becoming or staying undetected. Stride up to half your Speed. (You can use Sneak while Burrowing, Climbing, Flying, or Swimming instead of Striding if you have the corresponding movement type; you must move at half that Speed.)
At the end of your movement, the GM rolls your Stealth check in secret and compares the result to the Perception DC of each creature you were hidden from or undetected by at the start of your movement. If you have cover or greater cover from the creature throughout your Stride, you gain the +2 circumstance bonus from cover (or +4 from greater cover) to your Stealth check. Because you''re moving, the bonus increase from Taking Cover doesn''t apply. You don''t get to roll against a creature if, at the end of your movement, you neither are concealed from it nor have cover or greater cover against it. You automatically become observed by such a creature.

<b>Success</b> You''re undetected by the creature during your movement and remain undetected by the creature at the end of it. You become observed as soon as you do anything other than Hide, Sneak, or Step. If you attempt to Strike a creature, the creature remains off-guard against that attack, and you then become observed. If you do anything else, you become observed just before you act unless the GM determines otherwise. The GM might allow you to perform a particularly unobtrusive action without being noticed, possibly requiring another Stealth check. If you speak or make a deliberate loud noise, you become hidden instead of undetected. If a creature uses Seek and you become hidden to it as a result, you must Sneak if you want to become undetected by that creature again.<br><b>Failure</b> A telltale sound or other sign gives your position away, though you still remain unseen. You''re hidden from the creature throughout your movement and remain so.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> Whether through a misstep or simple bad luck, you''ve been spotted! You''re observed by the creature throughout your movement and remain so. If you''re invisible and were hidden from the creature, instead of being observed you''re hidden throughout your movement and remain so.',	NULL,	'Move, Secret'),
('actAccessInfosphere',	'Access HoloNet',	NULL,	'You are using a device with HoloNet access.',	NULL,	'You attempt to access the galactic network, known as the HoloNet, or a localized planetary data grid to come up with information on a topic. This typically takes 10 minutes of research to find information, with results like Recalling Knowledge on a topic. Larger investigations or topics could require several hours, while single-word answers of information common to that settlement''s local HoloNet node may only take a minute, based on the GM''s discretion. Significant and longer investigations should use the research subsystem. The GM determines the DC based on the topic you''re researching. This can be further influenced by the quality of the local HoloNet connection and what information it might possess on the topic, and how well organized it is.

<b>Critical Success</b> You find the information you were searching for. If this was used on a topic you could have used Recall Knowledge on, you instead find this information in 1 minute.<br>
<b>Success</b> You find the information you were looking for.<br>
<b>Critical Failure</b> You find misleading information thanks to incorrect data, Imperial propaganda, or slicer interference. The GM provides you false information on your topic of investigation (or decides to give you no information, as on a failure).',	NULL,	'Concentrate, Exploration, Secret'),
('actCoverTracks',	'Cover Tracks',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'You cover your tracks, moving up to half your travel Speed. You don''t need to attempt a Survival check to cover your tracks, but anyone tracking you must succeed at a Survival check against your Survival DC if it is higher than the normal DC to Track.
In some cases, you might Cover Tracks in an encounter. In this case, Cover Tracks is a single action and doesn''t have the exploration trait.',	NULL,	'Concentrate, Exploration, Move'),
('actPalmAnObject',	'Palm an Object',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You pick up a small, unattended object and try not to be noticed. Roll a single Thievery check against the Perception DCs of all creatures who are currently observing you. You can typically only Palm Objects of negligible Bulk, though the GM might determine otherwise depending on the situation.

<b>Success</b> The creature doesn''t notice you Palming the Object.<br><b>Failure</b> The creature notices you Palming the Object.',	NULL,	'Manipulate'),
('actPickALock',	'Pick a Lock',	'[one-action]',	'You’re holding or wearing an infiltrator''s toolkit.',	NULL,	'Opening a lock without a key is very similar to Disabling a Device, but the DC of the check is determined by the complexity and construction of the lock you are attempting to pick (locks and their DCs). Locks of higher quality might require multiple successes to unlock. If you lack the proper tools, the GM might let you use improvised picks, which are treated as a shoddy toolkit.

<b>Critical Success</b> You unlock the lock, or you achieve two successes toward opening a lock that requires more than one success. You leave no trace of your tampering.<br><b>Success</b> You open the lock, or you achieve one success toward opening a lock that requires more than one success. You leave behind damage that indicates the lock was picked on close scrutiny.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> You break your toolkit and leave behind obvious damage. Fixing a broken toolkit requires using Crafting to Repair it or else swapping in replacement picks (costing 3 credits, or 30 credits for a tactical infiltrator''s toolkit).',	NULL,	'Manipulate'),
('actTrack',	'Track',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'You follow tracks, moving at up to half your travel Speed. After a successful check to Track, you can continue following the tracks at half your Speed without attempting additional checks for up to 1 hour.<br>
In some cases, you might Track in an encounter. In this case, Track is a single action and doesn''t have the exploration trait, but you might need to roll more often because you''re in a tense situation. The GM determines how often you must attempt this check.<br>
You attempt your Survival check when you start Tracking, once every hour you continue tracking, and any time something significant changes in the trail. The GM determines the DCs for such checks, depending on the freshness of the trail, the weather, and the type of ground.

<b>Success</b> You find the trail or continue to follow the one you''re already following.<br><b>Failure</b> You lose the trail but can try again after a 1-hour delay.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> You lose the trail and can''t try again for 24 hours.',	NULL,	'Concentrate, Exploration, Move'),
('actAvertGaze',	'Avert Gaze',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You avert your gaze from danger. You gain a +2 circumstance bonus to saves against visual abilities that require you to look at a creature or object, such as the radiant gaze of a solar nymph. Your gaze remains averted until the start of your next turn.',	NULL,	NULL),
('actCrawl',	'Crawl',	'[one-action]',	'You''re prone, and your Speed is at least 10 feet.',	NULL,	'You move 5 feet by crawling and continue to stay prone.',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actBurrow',	'Burrow',	'[one-action]',	'You have a burrow Speed.',	NULL,	'You dig your way through dirt, sand, or a similar loose material at a rate up to your burrow Speed. You can''t burrow through rock or other substances denser than dirt unless you have an ability that allows you to do so.',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actDropProne',	'Drop Prone',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You fall prone.',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actReady',	'Ready',	'[two-actions]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You prepare to use an action that will occur outside your turn. Choose a single action or free action you can use, and designate a trigger. Your turn then ends. If the trigger you designated occurs before the start of your next turn, you can use the chosen action as a reaction (provided you still meet the requirements to use it). You can''t Ready a free action that already has a trigger.

If you have a multiple attack penalty and your readied action is an attack action, your readied attack takes the multiple attack penalty you had at the time you used Ready. This is one of the few times the multiple attack penalty applies when it''s not your turn.',	NULL,	'Concentrate'),
('actEscape',	'Escape',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You attempt to escape from being grabbed, immobilized, or restrained. Choose one creature, object, spell effect, hazard, or other impediment imposing any of those conditions on you. Attempt a check using your unarmed attack modifier against the DC of the effect. This is typically the Athletics DC of a creature grabbing you, the Thievery DC of a creature who tied you up, the spell DC for a spell effect, or the listed Escape DC of an object, hazard, or other impediment. You can attempt an Acrobatics or Athletics check instead of using your attack modifier if you choose (but this action still has the attack trait).

<b>Critical Success</b> You get free and remove the grabbed, immobilized, and restrained conditions imposed by your chosen target. You can then Stride up to 5 feet.<br><b>Success</b> You get free and remove the grabbed, immobilized, and restrained conditions imposed by your chosen target.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> You don''t get free, and you can''t attempt to Escape again until your next turn.',	NULL,	'Attack'),
('actRelease',	'Release',	'[free-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You release something you''re holding in your hand or hands. This might mean dropping an item, removing one hand from your weapon while continuing to hold it in another hand, releasing a cable suspending an enercycle, or performing a similar action. Unlike most manipulate actions, Release doesn''t trigger reactions that can be triggered by actions with the manipulate trait (such as Reactive Strike).

If you want to prepare to Release something outside of your turn, use the Ready activity.',	NULL,	'Manipulate'),
('actInteract',	'Interact',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'You use your hand or hands to manipulate an object or the terrain. You can grab an unattended or stored object, draw a weapon, swap a held item for another (see Changing Equipment), open a door, or achieve a similar effect. On rare occasions, you might have to attempt a skill check to determine if your Interact action was successful.',	NULL,	'Manipulate'),
('actStand',	'Stand',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You stand up from being prone.',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actStep',	'Step',	'[one-action]',	'Your Speed is at least 10 feet.',	NULL,	'You carefully move 5 feet. Unlike most types of movement, Stepping doesn''t trigger reactions, such as Reactive Strike, that can be triggered by move actions or upon leaving or entering a square.
You can''t Step into difficult terrain, and you can''t Step using a Speed other than your land Speed.',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actReposition',	'Reposition',	'[one-action]',	'You either have at least one hand free, or you’re grabbing or restraining the target. The target can’t be more than one size larger than you.',	NULL,	'You muscle a creature or object around. Attempt an Athletics check against the target''s Fortitude DC.

<b>Critical Success</b> You move the creature up to 10 feet. It must remain within your reach during this movement, and you can''t move it into or through obstacles.<br><b>Success</b> You move the target up to 5 feet. It must remain within your reach during this movement, and you can''t move it into or through obstacles.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> The target can move you up to 5 feet as though it successfully Repositioned you.',	NULL,	'Attack'),
('actCreateADiversion',	'Create a Diversion',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'With a gesture, a trick, or some distracting words, you can create a diversion that draws creatures'' attention elsewhere. If you use a gesture or trick, this action gains the manipulate trait. If you use distracting words, it gains the auditory and linguistic traits.
Attempt a single Deception check and compare it to the Perception DCs of the creatures whose attention you''re trying to divert. Whether or not you succeed, creatures you attempt to divert gain a +4 circumstance bonus to their Perception DCs against your attempts to Create a Diversion for 1 minute.

<b>Success</b> You become hidden to each creature whose Perception DC is less than or equal to your result. (The hidden condition allows you to Sneak away.) This lasts until the end of your turn or until you do anything except Step or use the Stealth skill to Hide or Sneak. If you Strike a creature, the creature remains off-guard against that attack, and you then become observed. If you do anything else, you become observed just before you act unless the GM determines otherwise.<br><b>Failure</b> You don''t divert the attention of any creatures whose Perception DC exceeds your result, and those creatures are aware you were trying to trick them.',	NULL,	'Mental'),
('actSenseMotive',	'Sense Motive',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You try to tell whether a creature''s behavior is abnormal. Choose one creature and assess it for odd body language, signs of nervousness, and other indicators that it might be trying to deceive someone. The GM attempts a single secret Perception check for you and compares the result to the Deception DC of the creature, the DC of a spell affecting the creature''s mental state, or another appropriate DC determined by the GM. You typically can''t try to Sense the Motive of the same creature again until the situation changes significantly.

<b>Critical Success</b> You determine the creature''s true intentions and get a solid idea of any mental magic affecting it.<br><b>Success</b> You can tell whether the creature is behaving normally, but you don''t know its exact intentions or what magic might be affecting it.<br><b>Failure</b> You detect what a deceptive creature wants you to believe. If they''re not being deceptive, you believe they''re behaving normally.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> You get a false sense of the creature''s intentions.',	NULL,	NULL),
('actDismiss',	'Dismiss',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You end an effect that states you can Dismiss it. Dismissing ends the entire effect unless noted otherwise.',	NULL,	'Concentrate'),
('actRecallKnowledge',	'Recall Knowledge',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'<p>You attempt a skill check to try to remember a bit of knowledge regarding a topic related to that skill. Suggest which skill you&#39;d like to use and ask the GM one question. The GM determines the DC. You might need to collaborate with the GM to narrow down the question or skills, and you can decide not to Recall Knowledge before committing to the action if you don&#39;t like your options.</p>
<p><strong>Critical Success</strong> You recall the knowledge accurately. The GM answers your question truthfully and either tells you additional information or context, or answers one follow-up question.<br><strong>Success</strong> You recall the knowledge accurately. The GM answers your question truthfully.<br><strong>Critical Failure</strong> You recall incorrect information. The GM answers your question falsely (or decides to give you no information, as on a failure).</p>
<h2 id="sample-recall-knowledge-tasks">Sample Recall Knowledge Tasks</h2>
<p>The following examples use Syndicate Lore or Jedi Lore.</p>
<p><strong>Untrained</strong>  name of a Hutt crime lord or a famous Jedi Master<br><strong>Trained</strong>  names of a syndicate&#39;s lieutenants, major tenets of the Jedi Code<br><strong>Expert</strong>  hierarchy of a ruthless swoop gang, teachings of an ancient Sith sect<br><strong>Master</strong>  hidden hyperspace smuggling routes of the Pyke Syndicate, locations of lost Jedi temples across the Outer Rim<br><strong>Legendary</strong>  coordinates of an Imperial Inquisitorius black site, secret doctrines of the Whills, remote dark side vergence sites in the Unknown Regions</p>
<h2 id="recall-knowledge-skills">Recall Knowledge Skills</h2>
<p>The following skills can be used to Recall Knowledge about the listed topics. Some topics might appear on multiple lists, but the skills could give different information. For example, The Force might tell you about the dark side origins of an ancient Sith artifact, whereas Crafting could tell you what rare alloy it&#39;s forged from and what sort of damage might destroy it.</p>
<p><strong>Computers</strong>: data cylinders, HoloNet terminals, security slicing, encryption protocols, and logic droids<br><strong>Crafting</strong>: the value of items, blasters, armor plating, unusual materials (like beskar or cortosis), and droids<br><strong>Lore</strong>: the subject of the Lore skill&#39;s subcategory<br><strong>Medicine</strong>: diseases, poisons, wounds, cybernetics, forensics, and bacta or kolto treatments<br><strong>Nature</strong>: fauna, flora, planetary geography, weather, the environment, and natural creatures (like banthas, nexu, or rancors)<br><strong>Performance</strong>: impressive performances, cantina bands, holovid stars, and media personalities<br><strong>Piloting</strong>: models of walkers, speeders, or starships, specific modifications or hyperdrives installed on them, and areas of astrogation significance (like hyperspace anomalies, the Kessel Run, or the Maw)<br><strong>Society</strong>: politicians, galactic history, laws, social structures, and cultural nuances of an organized society<br><strong>The Force</strong>: Force traditions, lightsaber forms, dark side alchemy, ancient artifacts, and Force-sensitive creatures</p>
<p>Using an applicable Lore to Recall Knowledge about a topic, such as Sith Lore instead of The Force to recall details of an ancient dark side spirit&#39;s origins, typically comes with a lower DC. Your special interests can pay off! In some cases, you can get the GM&#39;s permission to use a different but related skill, usually against a higher DC than normal. The GM might allow checks to Recall Knowledge using other skills. For example, you might assess the reflexes of a professional podracer using Athletics. If you&#39;re using a physical skill (like in this example), the GM will most likely have you use a mental modifier—typically Intelligence—instead of the skill&#39;s normal physical attribute modifier.</p>
<h2 id="recall-knowledge-questions">Recall Knowledge Questions</h2>
<p>When encountering a subject for the first time, your first question will likely be a basic “What is it?”, which the GM can answer with a name and basic description like, “This is the crest of the Pyke Syndicate, a ruthless cartel dealing in raw spice,” or “That&#39;s a nexu, a predatory feline from Cholganna with four eyes and quills!” If you already know this base level of detail on the subject, the list below includes some reasonable questions. The GM determines what other questions to allow. Usually this is simple as long as you stick to one question. Any question must be about something observable in the game world, not the abstract numbers of the rules. The GM might tell you a malfunctioning IG-series assassin droid&#39;s Reflex save is its weakest—translating a concept your character could understand using the game term for clarity—but wouldn&#39;t reveal the exact Reflex modifier. The GM can find more guidance in  <em>GM Core</em>.<br><strong>Creatures:</strong>  “Can it be reasoned with?” “What planetary environments does it live in?” “What&#39;s its most notable offensive ability?” “Is its hide highly vulnerable or resistant to blaster fire?” “Are any of its defenses weak?”<br><strong>The Force:</strong>  “How can this Force power be resisted or avoided?” “What type of Force users typically employ this technique?” “How long do its effects last?”<br><strong>Organizations:</strong>  “What kind of influence do they have in this sector?” “Where is their base of operations?” “How large is their fleet?” “What kind of operatives do they employ?” “Who are their major authorities?” “Do they have any notable allies or enemies, like the Rebel Alliance?”<br><strong>People:</strong>  “What&#39;s their personality like?” “What do they look like?” “Do they have any notable talents or cybernetics?” “Do they have notable allies and enemies?” “What kind of political or underworld influence do they have?” “Do they frequent any cantinas or have any vices?”<br><strong>Sites:</strong>  “What are the hyperspace coordinates or general location?” “How large is the facility?” “What&#39;s the planetary government like?” “Do any notable figures live there?” “What kind of predators dwell in the surrounding wilds?” “What&#39;s the environment and terrain like on Ord Mantell?”</p>',	NULL,	'Concentrate, Secret'),
('actDisableADevice',	'Disable a Device',	'[two-actions]',	NULL,	NULL,	'This action allows you to disarm a trap or another complex device. Often, a device requires numerous successes before becoming disabled, depending on its construction and complexity. An infiltrator''s toolkit is helpful and sometimes even required to Disable a Device, as determined by the GM, and sometimes a device requires a higher proficiency rank in Thievery to disable it.  
Your Thievery check result determines your progress.

<b>Critical Success</b> You disable the device, or you achieve two successes toward disabling a device requiring more than one success. You leave no trace of your tampering, and you can rearm the device later, if that type of device can be rearmed.<br><b>Success</b> You disable the device, or you achieve one success toward disabling a device that requires more than one success.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> You trigger the device.',	NULL,	'Manipulate'),
('actHighJump',	'High Jump',	'[two-actions]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You Stride, then attempt a DC 30 Athletics check to jump vertically. If you didn''t Stride at least 10 feet, you automatically fail. This DC might be increased or decreased due to the situation, as determined by the GM.

<b>Critical Success</b> You Leap up to 8 feet vertically and 10 feet horizontally.<br><b>Success</b> You Leap up to 5 feet vertically and 5 feet horizontally.<br><b>Failure</b> You Leap normally.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> You fall prone in your space.

## Leap

The Leap basic action is used for High Jump and Long Jump. A horizontal Leap lets you jump up to 10 feet horizontally if your Speed is at least 15 feet, or up to 15 feet horizontally if your Speed is at least 30 feet. You land in the space where your Leap ends (meaning you can typically clear a 5-foot gap if your Speed is between 15 feet and 30 feet, or a 10-foot gap if your Speed is 30 feet or more). A vertical Leap lets you jump up to 3 feet vertically and 5 feet horizontally onto an elevated surface.',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actFly',	'Fly',	'[one-action]',	'You have a fly Speed.',	NULL,	'You move through the air up to your fly Speed. Moving upward (straight up or diagonally) uses the rules for moving through difficult terrain. You can move straight down 10 feet for every 5 feet of movement you spend. If you Fly to the ground, you don''t take falling damage. You can use an action to Fly 0 feet to hover in place. If you''re airborne at the end of your turn and didn''t use a Fly action this round, you fall.',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actAdministerFirstAid',	'Administer First Aid',	'[two-actions]',	'You’re wearing or holding a medkit.',	NULL,	'You perform first aid on an adjacent creature that is dying or bleeding. If a creature is both dying and bleeding, choose which ailment you''re trying to treat before you roll. You can Administer First Aid again to attempt to remedy the other effect.

<b>Stabilize</b> Attempt a Medicine check on a creature that has 0 Hit Points and the dying condition. The DC is equal to 5 + that creature''s recovery roll DC (typically 15 + its dying value).<br><b>Stop Bleeding</b> Attempt a Medicine check on a creature that is taking persistent bleed damage. The DC is usually the DC of the effect that caused the bleed.<br><br>
<b>Success</b> If you''re trying to stabilize, the target loses the dying condition (but remains unconscious). If you''re trying to stop bleeding, the target benefits from an assisted recovery with the lowered DC for particularly appropriate help.<br>
<b>Critical Failure</b> If you were trying to stabilize, the target''s dying value increases by 1. If you were trying to stop bleeding, the target immediately takes an amount of damage equal to its persistent bleed damage.',	NULL,	'Manipulate'),
('actDecipherWriting',	'Decipher Writing',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'You attempt to decipher complicated writing or literature on an obscure topic. This usually takes 1 minute per page of text, but might take longer (typically an hour per page for decrypting ciphers or the like). The text must be in a language you can read, though the GM might allow you to attempt to decipher text written in an unfamiliar language using Society instead.  
The DC is determined by the GM based on the state or complexity of the document. The GM might have you roll one check for a short text or a check for each section of a larger text.  

<b>Critical Success</b> You understand the true meaning of the text.<br><b>Success</b> You understand the true meaning of the text. If it was a coded document, you know the general meaning but might not have a word-for-word translation.<br><b>Failure</b> You can''t understand the text and take a –2 circumstance penalty to further checks to decipher it.<br><b> Critical Failure</b> You believe you understand the text on that page, but you have in fact misconstrued its message.

## Sample Decipher Writing Tasks

<b>Trained</b> entry-level philosophy treatise<br><b>Expert</b> complex code, such as a cipher<br><b>Master</b> top secret code or advanced research notes<br><b>Legendary</b> esoteric text written in metaphor by an extraplanar being',	NULL,	'Contentrate, Exploration, Secret'),
('actGrabAnEdge',	'Grab an Edge',	'[reaction]',	'Your hands are not tied behind your back or otherwise restrained.',	'You fall from or past an edge or handhold.',	'When you fall off or past an edge or other handhold, you can try to grab it, potentially stopping your fall. You must succeed at your choice of an Acrobatics check or a Reflex save, usually at the Climb DC. If you grab the edge or handhold, you can then Climb up using Athletics.

<b>Critical Success</b> You grab the edge or handhold, whether or not you have a hand free, typically by using a suitable held item to catch yourself (catching a doshko on a ledge, for example). You still take damage from the distance fallen so far, but you treat the fall as though it were 30 feet shorter.<br>
<b>Success</b> If you have at least one hand free, you grab the edge or handhold, stopping your fall. You still take damage from the distance fallen so far, but you treat the fall as though it were 20 feet shorter. If you have no hands free, you continue to fall as if you had failed the check.<br>
<b>Critical Failure</b> You continue to fall, and if you''ve fallen 20 feet or more before you use this reaction, you take 10 bludgeoning damage from the impact for every 20 feet fallen.',	NULL,	'Manipulate'),
('actAid',	'Aid',	'[reaction]',	'The ally is willing to accept your aid, and you''ve prepared to help (see below)',	'An ally is about to use an action that requires a skill check or attack roll',	'You try to help your ally with a task. To use this reaction, you must first prepare to help, usually by using an action during your turn. You must explain to the GM exactly how you''re trying to help, and they determine whether you can Aid your ally. When you use your Aid reaction, attempt a skill check or attack roll of a type decided by the GM. The typical DC is 15, but the GM might adjust this DC for particularly hard or easy tasks. The GM can add any relevant traits to your preparatory action or to your Aid reaction depending on the situation, or even allow you to Aid checks other than skill checks and attack rolls.

<b>Critical Success</b> You grant your ally a +2 circumstance bonus to the triggering check. If you''re a master with the check you attempted, the bonus is +3, and if you''re legendary, it''s +4.<br><b>Success</b> You grant your ally a +1 circumstance bonus to the triggering check.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> Your ally takes a –1 circumstance penalty to the triggering check.

## Aid Details

The following clarifications might be relevant when Aiding an ally.  
<b>Long Tasks</b> For a task that takes longer than a round, you often need to spend more than one action preparing to help, as determined by the GM.<br><b>Proximity</b> You don''t necessarily need to be next to your ally to aid, though you must be in a reasonable location to help them both when you set up and when you take the reaction.<br><b>Repetition</b> Aiding the same creature multiple times can have diminishing returns. In particular, if you try to repeatedly Aid attacks or skill checks against a creature, the GM will usually increase the DC each time as your foe gets more savvy. This isn''t the case if there''s no reason the task would be less likely to work if repeated, such as Aiding someone who''s climbing a wall or picking a lock.',	NULL,	NULL),
('actMount',	'Mount',	'[one-action]',	'You''re adjacent to a creature that is at least one size larger than you and is willing to be your mount.',	NULL,	'You move onto the creature and ride it. If you''re already mounted, you can instead use this action to dismount, moving off the mount into a space adjacent to it.',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actClimb',	'Climb',	'[one-action]',	'You have two hands free.',	NULL,	'You attempt an Athletics check to move a maximum distance of 5 feet up, down, or across an incline. You''re off-guard while climbing unless you have a climb Speed. The GM determines the DC based on the nature of the incline and environmental circumstances; you might get an automatic critical success on an incline that''s trivial to climb. If your land Speed is 40 feet or higher, increase the maximum distance by 5 feet for every 20 feet of Speed above 20 feet.

<b>Critical Success</b> You move along the incline, increasing the maximum distance by 5 feet.
<b>Success</b> You move along the incline.
<b>Critical Failure</b> You fall. If you began the climb on stable ground, you fall and land prone.

## Sample Climb Tasks

<b>Untrained</b> ladder, steep slope, low-branched tree
<b>Trained</b> cable line, typical tree
<b>Expert</b> wall with small handholds and footholds
<b>Master</b> ceiling with handholds and footholds, rock wall
<b>Legendary</b> smooth surface',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actPointOut',	'Point Out',	'[one-action]',	'A creature is undetected by one or more of your allies but isn''t undetected by you.',	NULL,	'You indicate a creature that you can see to one or more allies, gesturing in a direction and describing the distance verbally. That creature is hidden to your allies, rather than undetected. This works only for allies who can see you and are in a position where they could potentially detect the target. If your allies can''t hear or understand you, they must succeed at a Perception check against the creature''s Stealth DC or they misunderstand and believe the target is in a different location.',	NULL,	'Auditory, Manipulate, Visual'),
('actCoerce',	'Coerce',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'With threats either veiled or overt, you attempt to bully a creature into doing what you want. You must spend at least 1 minute of conversation with the creature. At the end of the conversation, attempt an Intimidation check against the target''s Will DC, modified by any circumstances the GM determines.

<b>Critical Success</b> The target gives you the information you seek or agrees to follow your directives so long as they aren''t likely to harm the target in any way. The target continues to comply for an amount of time determined by the GM but not exceeding 1 day, at which point the target becomes unfriendly (if it wasn''t already unfriendly or hostile). However, the target is too scared of you to retaliate—at least in the short term.<br><b>Success</b> As critical success, but once the target becomes unfriendly, they might decide to act against you—for example, by reporting you to the authorities or assisting your enemies.<br><b>Failure</b> The target doesn''t do what you say, and if they were not already unfriendly or hostile, they become unfriendly.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> The target refuses to comply, becomes hostile if they weren''t already, and is temporarily immune to your Coercion for at least 1 week.

## Changing Attitudes

Your influence on NPCs is measured with a set of attitudes that reflect how they view your character. These are only a brief summary of a creature''s disposition. The GM will supply additional nuance based on the history and beliefs of the characters you''re interacting with, and their attitudes can change in accordance with the story. The attitudes are detailed in the Conditions Appendix and are summarized here.

<b>Helpful</b> Willing to help you and responds favorably to your requests.<br><b>Friendly</b> Has a good attitude toward you, but won''t necessarily stick their neck out to help you.<br><b>Indifferent</b> Doesn''t care about you either way. (Most NPCs start out indifferent.)<br><b>Unfriendly</b> Dislikes you and doesn''t want to help you.<br><b>Hostile</b> Actively works against you—and might attack you just because of their dislike.

No one can ever change the attitude of a player character with these skills. You can roleplay interactions with player characters, and even use Diplomacy results if the player wants a mechanical sense of how convincing or charming a character is, but players make the ultimate decisions about how their characters respond.

## Infosphere Reputation

Your influence on an infosphere is measured using the same attitudes as NPCs your character knows offline (GM Core). However, your character''s activities and other people''s attitudes toward your character on a public infosphere are easier to find and can result in characters having a different initial attitude based on your online activities.
Using an alias can fool those who lack the skill or interest in figuring out your identity, often requiring a character to Hack or Gather Information against your Computers DC to figure out your identity and find your content. This can also result in people harboring different attitudes toward your character and their online persona. If someone discovers you are responsible for creating unpleasant content or using a repugnant persona online, their attitude toward you might worsen even if you were previously friendly with them.',	NULL,	'Auditory, Concentrate, Emotion, Exploration, Linguistic, Mental'),
('actPushOff',	'Push Off',	'[one-action]',	'You have at least one hand or leg (or suitable appendage) free, and you''re untethered.',	NULL,	'You use as leverage an object or creature of the same size as you or larger to change the direction you''re floating in. Float up to half your Speed in your chosen direction. The distance you move at the end of your turn while untethered changes to the amount you moved during this action.

You can Push Off as a free action immediately after you make a successful melee Strike or successfully Shove. You have at least one hand or leg (or suitable appendage) free, and you''re untethered.',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actDelay',	'Delay',	'[free-action]',	NULL,	'Your turn begins',	'You wait for the right moment to act. The rest of your turn doesn''t happen yet. Instead, you''re removed from the initiative order. You can return to the initiative order as a free action triggered by the end of any other creature''s turn. This permanently changes your initiative to the new position. You can''t use reactions until you return to the initiative order. If you Delay an entire round without returning to the initiative order, the actions from the Delayed turn are lost, your initiative doesn''t change, and your next turn occurs at your original position in the initiative order.

When you Delay, any persistent damage or other negative effects that normally occur at the start or end of your turn occur immediately when you use the Delay action. Any beneficial effects that would end at any point during your turn also end. The GM might determine that other effects end when you Delay as well. Essentially, you can''t Delay to avoid negative consequences that would happen on your turn or to extend beneficial effects that would end on your turn.',	NULL,	NULL),
('actRaiseAShield',	'Raise a Shield',	'[one-action]',	'You’re wielding a shield.',	NULL,	'You position your shield to protect yourself. When you''ve Raised a Shield, you gain its listed circumstance bonus to AC. Your shield remains raised until the start of your next turn.',	NULL,	NULL),
('actSustain',	'Sustain',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'Choose one of your effects that has a sustained duration or lists a special benefit when you Sustain it. Most such effects come from spells or magic item activations. If the effect has a sustained duration, its duration extends until the end of your next turn. (Sustaining more than once in the same turn doesn''t extend the duration to subsequent turns.) If an ability can be sustained but doesn''t list how long, it can be sustained up to 10 minutes.

An effect might list an additional benefit that occurs if you Sustain it, and this can even appear on effects that don''t have a sustained duration. If the effect has both a special benefit and a sustained duration, your Sustain action extends the duration as well as having the special benefit.

If your Sustain action is disrupted, the ability ends.',	NULL,	'Concentrate'),
('actManeuverInFlight',	'Maneuver in Flight',	'[one-action]',	'You have a fly Speed.',	NULL,	'You try a difficult maneuver while flying. Attempt an Acrobatics check. The GM determines what maneuvers are possible, but they rarely allow you to move farther than your fly Speed.

<b>Success</b> You succeed at the maneuver.<br><b>Failure</b> Your maneuver fails. The GM chooses if you simply can''t move or if some other detrimental effect happens. The outcome should be appropriate for the maneuver you attempted (for instance, being blown off course if you were trying to fly against a strong wind).<br><b>Critical Failure</b> As failure, but the consequence is more dire.

## Sample Maneuver in Flight Tasks

<b>Trained</b> steep ascent or descent<br><b>Expert</b> fly against the wind<br><b>Master</b> reverse direction<br><b>Legendary</b> fly through gale force winds',	NULL,	'Move'),
('actSubsist',	'Subsist',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'You try to provide food and shelter for yourself, and possibly others as well, with a standard of living described on page 243. The GM determines the DC based on the nature of the place where you''re trying to Subsist. You might need a minimum proficiency rank to Subsist in particularly strange environments. Unlike most downtime activities, you can Subsist after 8 hours or less of exploration, but if you do, you take a –5 penalty.

<b>Critical Success</b> You either provide a subsistence living for yourself and one additional creature, or you improve your own food and shelter, granting yourself a comfortable living.<br><b>Success</b> You find enough food and shelter with basic protection from the elements to provide you a subsistence living.<br><b>Failure</b> You''re exposed to the elements and don''t get enough food, becoming fatigued until you attain sufficient food and shelter.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> You attract some trouble, eat something you shouldn''t, or otherwise worsen your situation. You take a –2 circumstance penalty to checks to Subsist for 1 week. You don''t find any food at all; if you don''t have any stored up, you''re in danger of starving or dying of thirst if you continue failing.

## Sample Subsist Tasks

<b>Untrained</b> forage on a lush planet with calm weather like Castrovel or panhandle at a busy space port with plentiful resources like Absalom Station<br><b>Trained</b> forage on a habitable terrestrial planet, adequately supplied research station, or city<br><b>Expert</b> forage in extreme terrain, subsist in an insular frontier colony, or stowaway on a long-haul freighter<br><b>Master</b> forage on a desert moon or abandoned space station<br><b>Legendary</b> subsist on a barren asteroid, toxic or irradiated planet, or a city undergoing orbital bombardment',	NULL,	'Downtime'),
('actSwitchHands',	'Switch Hands',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You designate a pair of limbs as your active hands. You can only have one pair of hands designated as your active hands at a time.',	NULL,	NULL),
('actOperateDevice',	'Operate Device',	NULL,	'You are using a computer or similar device.',	NULL,	'You perform a basic task using a digital device, such as operating a basic program or playing a vidgame. You might also use this if the device you''re using has a physical component, such as 3D-tracking or requiring specific motions to activate features. The GM determines the DC based on the action you''re taking.

<b>Critical Success</b> You excel at what you are doing, learning secrets from the program or advanced functionality. If it''s a game, then you win it with record timing based on average completion rates.<br><b>Success</b> You manage to operate the device in the necessary manner, including getting basic functionality. You gain general information from the program.<br><b>Failure</b> You can''t understand the program or game and take a –2 circumstance penalty to further attempts to access or play it for the next day.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> You fail to access the game or make a mistake that prevents you from accessing the program (such as forgetting a password and locking yourself out of the program) for the next day.

## Sample Operate Device Tasks

<b>Untrained</b> check mail, play games, turn device off (and on again)<br><b>Trained</b> advanced games, organize corporate mailboxes<br><b>Expert</b> highly competitive games, organize servers<br><b>Master</b> games at a planetary competitive level, manage large databases<br><b>Legendary</b> play games at a galactic competitive level, manage interplanetary networks using Drift beacons',	NULL,	'Concentratie, Exploration'),
('actMakeAnImpression',	'Make an Impression',	NULL,	NULL,	NULL,	'With at least 1 minute of conversation, during which you engage in charismatic overtures, flattery, and other acts of goodwill, you seek to make a good impression on someone to make them temporarily agreeable. At the end of the conversation, attempt a Diplomacy check against the Will DC of one target. You can instead choose up to five targets if you take a –2 penalty. The GM might add other bonuses or penalties based on the situation. Any impression you make lasts for only the current social interaction unless the GM decides otherwise. See the Changing Attitudes sidebar for a summary of the attitude conditions.

<b>Critical Success</b> The target''s attitude toward you improves by two steps.<br><b>Success</b> The target''s attitude toward you improves by one step.<br><b>Critical Failure</b> The target''s attitude toward you decreases by one step.

## Changing Attitudes

Your influence on NPCs is measured with a set of attitudes that reflect how they view your character. These are only a brief summary of a creature''s disposition. The GM will supply additional nuance based on the history and beliefs of the characters you''re interacting with, and their attitudes can change in accordance with the story. The attitudes are detailed in the Conditions Appendix and are summarized here.

<b>Helpful</b> Willing to help you and responds favorably to your requests.<br><b>Friendly</b> Has a good attitude toward you, but won''t necessarily stick their neck out to help you.<br><b>Indifferent</b> Doesn''t care about you either way. (Most NPCs start out indifferent.)<br><b>Unfriendly</b> Dislikes you and doesn''t want to help you.<br><b>Hostile</b> Actively works against you—and might attack you just because of their dislike.

No one can ever change the attitude of a player character with these skills. You can roleplay interactions with player characters, and even use Diplomacy results if the player wants a mechanical sense of how convincing or charming a character is, but players make the ultimate decisions about how their characters respond.

## Infosphere Reputation

Your influence on an infosphere is measured using the same attitudes as NPCs your character knows offline (GM Core). However, your character''s activities and other people''s attitudes toward your character on a public infosphere are easier to find and can result in characters having a different initial attitude based on your online activities.
Using an alias can fool those who lack the skill or interest in figuring out your identity, often requiring a character to Hack or Gather Information against your Computers DC to figure out your identity and find your content. This can also result in people harboring different attitudes toward your character and their online persona. If someone discovers you are responsible for creating unpleasant content or using a repugnant persona online, their attitude toward you might worsen even if you were previously friendly with them.',	NULL,	'Auditory, Concentrate, Exploration, Linguistic, Mental'),
('actRunOver',	'Run Over',	'[three-actions]',	'You are piloting a vehicle.',	NULL,	'You try to run over creatures with your vehicle, possibly also ramming one larger creature or object. If you maintain control of your vehicle, the vehicle moves up to twice its Speed in a straight line at the vehicle''s current heading. You attempt to run over any creatures in your path two sizes smaller than the vehicle or smaller, and you can attempt to ram one target creature or object in your path one size smaller than the vehicle or larger.

Each creature in your path, including a rammed target, takes the vehicle''s collision damage (basic Reflex save at vehicle''s collision DC). If the rammed target is a vehicle, its pilot can attempt a piloting check in place of this Reflex save, with the same results. If the target of your ram takes damage, you and your vehicle each take collision damage (no save) and your movement ends.',	NULL,	'Move, Reckless'),
('actCreateForgery',	'Create Forgery',	NULL,	'You provide the proper writing materials for your forgery.',	NULL,	'You create a forged document, usually over the course of a day or a week. The GM rolls a secret DC 20 Society check. If you need to forge a specific person''s writing, you need a sample of that person''s writing. Otherwise, you need only to have seen a similar document, and you gain up to a +4 circumstance bonus to the check (the GM determines the bonus).

<b>Success</b> The forgery is of good enough quality that passive observers can''t notice the fake (but see Examining Forgeries).<br><b>Failure</b> The forgery has some obvious signs of being a fake, potentially allowing passive observers to detect it.

Each time a passive observer sees the document, the GM compares your check result to the observer''s Perception DC or Society DC, whichever is higher. If your result doesn''t exceed a passive observer''s DC, that observer knows the document is a forgery.',	NULL,	'Downtime, Secret'),
('actRepair',	'Repair',	NULL,	'You are holding or wearing a repair toolkit.',	NULL,	'You spend 10 minutes attempting to fix a damaged item, placing the item on a stable surface and using the repair toolkit with both hands. Roll a Crafting check. The GM sets the DC, but it''s usually about the same DC to Repair a given item as it is to Craft it in the first place. You can''t Repair a destroyed item.

<b>Critical Success</b> You restore 10 Hit Points to the item, plus an additional 10 Hit Points per proficiency rank you have in Crafting (a total of 20 HP if you''re trained, 30 HP if you''re an expert, 40 HP if you''re a master, or 50 HP if you''re legendary).<br><b>Success</b> You restore 5 Hit Points to the item, plus an additional 5 per proficiency rank you have in Crafting (for a total of 10 HP if you are trained, 15 HP if you''re an expert, 20 HP if you''re a master, or 25 HP if you''re legendary).<br><b>Critical Failure</b> You deal 2d6 damage to the item. Apply the item''s Hardness to this damage.',	NULL,	'Exploration, Manipulate'),
('actSteal',	'Steal',	'[one-action]',	NULL,	NULL,	'You try to take a small object from another creature without being noticed. Typically, you can Steal only an object of negligible Bulk, you must have a free hand, and you automatically fail if the creature who has the object is in combat or on guard.
Attempt a Thievery check to determine if you successfully Steal the object. The DC is usually the Perception DC of the creature wearing the object. It''s easiest to steal an object that is worn but not closely guarded (like a loosely carried purse or satchel, or an object within such a container). The GM might increase the DC if the object is protected or if the nature of the object makes it harder to steal (such as a very small item in a large pack, or a sheet of paper mixed in with other documents). For instance, the DC is typically 5 higher if the object is in a pocket, held in a creature''s hand, or similarly protected.
You might also need to compare your Thievery check result against the Perception DCs of observers other than the person wearing the object. The GM might impose a circumstance penalty to the DCs of observers who are distracted.

<b>Success</b> You steal the item without the bearer noticing, or an observer doesn''t see you take or attempt to take the item.<br><b>Failure</b> The item''s bearer notices your attempt before you can take the object, or an observer sees you take or attempt to take the item. The GM determines the response of any creature that notices your theft.',	NULL,	'Manipulate');

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS "Ancestry";
CREATE TABLE "public"."Ancestry" (
    "HP" smallint NOT NULL,
    "Speed" smallint NOT NULL,
    "Languages" character varying NOT NULL,
    "Description" text NOT NULL,
    "AncestryID" character varying NOT NULL,
    "Name" character varying NOT NULL,
    "Traits" character varying NOT NULL,
    "Size" character varying NOT NULL,
    "Features" jsonb,
    "Summary" character varying,
    CONSTRAINT "Ancestry_AncestryID" PRIMARY KEY ("AncestryID")
)
WITH (oids = false);

COMMENT ON COLUMN "public"."Ancestry"."HP" IS 'Hit die size';

COMMENT ON COLUMN "public"."Ancestry"."Speed" IS 'Speed in meters';

COMMENT ON COLUMN "public"."Ancestry"."Languages" IS 'List of starting languages';

COMMENT ON COLUMN "public"."Ancestry"."Description" IS 'Description text';

COMMENT ON COLUMN "public"."Ancestry"."AncestryID" IS 'Unique Ancestry ID';

COMMENT ON COLUMN "public"."Ancestry"."Name" IS 'Ancestry Name';

COMMENT ON COLUMN "public"."Ancestry"."Traits" IS 'Traits';

COMMENT ON COLUMN "public"."Ancestry"."Size" IS 'Ancestry size';

INSERT INTO "Ancestry" ("HP", "Speed", "Languages", "Description", "AncestryID", "Name", "Traits", "Size", "Features", "Summary") VALUES
(8,	25,	'Basic, Rodese',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/rodian.png" alt="A Rodian"  class="description-image description-image--right">Rodians are a vibrant, multifaceted species hailing from the sweltering jungle world of Rodia. Though the galaxy at large often stereotypes them as ruthless bounty hunters, assassins, and thugs, this reputation stems from a deeply ingrained cultural obsession with &quot;the hunt.&quot; In Rodian society, hunting is considered the highest form of art, and every profession—from poetry to politics—is viewed through the lens of a predator seeking its prize. This intense drive has made them some of the most focused and capable trackers in the stars.</p>
<p>Despite their martial reputation, Rodians are also celebrated for their dramatic arts. Their theater is some of the most intense and violent in the cosmos, yet it possesses a tragic beauty that few other cultures can replicate. A Rodian far from home might be a cold-blooded mercenary, but they could just as easily be a dedicated explorer, a tenacious journalist, or a brilliant scientist, applying their species&#39; legendary persistence to the pursuit of knowledge or justice.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a keen-eyed, agile character who excels at the chase and possesses a dramatic flair, you should play a Rodian.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>View every challenge as a hunt to be planned, executed, and celebrated.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Struggle to keep your movements subtle, as your species naturally values dramatic gestures and bold statements.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Possess a high degree of technical curiosity, especially regarding weapon modifications and tracking gear.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Assume you are working for a local crime lord or have a bounty puck in your pocket.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Find your multi-faceted eyes and twitching snout-vent difficult to read emotionally.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on you to find a trail that everyone else has lost, trusting your superior senses.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Rodians are easily identified by their large, multifaceted eyes, tapir-like snouts, and pointed, dish-shaped ears. Their skin is typically green and pebbled, though shades of turquoise, yellow, and even purple are found in certain lineages. Their hands end in long, suction-tipped fingers that grant them a superb grip on tools and surfaces. A unique feature of Rodian biology is the emission of pheromones; while humans can barely detect them, other Rodians can read a peer’s mood and intent through these chemical signals.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Rodian society is organized into a rigid system of competing clans. For centuries, these clans engaged in brutal &quot;Grand Hunts&quot; on their home world to determine social standing. While the arrival of the Galactic Empire and the New Republic pushed much of this violence off-planet or into the realm of professional bounty hunting, the competitive spirit remains. On Rodia, cities are protected by massive domes to keep the deadly jungle predators at bay, creating a culture that is simultaneously urban and intimately aware of the primal wild.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Most Rodians believe that life is a competition where only the most cunning and prepared survive. They value achievement and &quot;The Prize&quot;—whether that prize is a captured fugitive, a finished masterpiece, or a successful business merger. While this can lead to a &quot;me-first&quot; attitude, it also breeds a deep respect for those who show superior skill. A Rodian who finds a worthy cause or a leader they respect will hunt for that cause with a ferocity that few can match.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Complete the hunt, refine your chosen craft, keep your weapons and tools in peak condition.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Allow a target to escape through your own negligence, show cowardice during a confrontation, fail to honor the terms of a contract.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Ando, Beedo, Chido, Doda, Greedo, Greeata, Kelko, Navik, Neela, Papanoida, Reeve, Wald, Yavik.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="rodian-mechanics">Rodian Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Dexterity, Wisdom, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Charisma</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Rodese, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancRodian',	'Rodian',	'Humanoid, Rodian',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CHA", "boost": ["DEX", "WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Rodians are a vibrant, multifaceted species hailing from the sweltering jungle world of Rodia. Though the galaxy at large often stereotypes them as ruthless bounty hunters, assassins, and thugs, this reputation stems from a deeply ingrained cultural obsession with "the hunt." In Rodian society, hunting is considered the highest form of art, and every profession—from poetry to politics—is viewed through the lens of a predator seeking its prize. This intense drive has made them some of the most focused and capable trackers in the stars.'),
(10,	30,	'Shistavanen',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/shistavanen.png" alt="A shistavanen commando"  class="description-image description-image--right">Shistavanen, often referred to as &quot;Wolfmen,&quot; are a predatory, lupine species hailing from the Uvena system. Evolution on their harsh, hunter-dominated homeworld has gifted them with razor-sharp senses and a natural predatory instinct that makes them some of the most formidable trackers and scouts in the galaxy. Despite their feral appearance, Shistavanen are highly intelligent and technologically capable, though they are famously isolationist. For centuries, they preferred to remain within their own system, viewing the rest of the galaxy with deep-seated suspicion.</p>
<p>In the wider galaxy, Shistavanen who leave the Uvena system are often outcasts or individuals with an uncharacteristic streak of wanderlust. Because of their natural physical advantages, they are highly sought after as bounty hunters, elite mercenaries, and military scouts. They are a species of few words, preferring to let their actions—and their formidable claws—do the talking. To earn the respect of a Shistavanen is no small feat, but once won, their loyalty is as fierce as their hunt.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a primal, highly observant character who excels at tracking and survival and possesses a fearsome physical presence, you should play a Shistavanen.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Rely on your sense of smell to detect lies, hidden enemies, or approaching storms long before others.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Prefer to move in the shadows or at the fringes of a group, always watching the perimeter.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Struggle with the loud, bright, and crowded environments of urban Core Worlds.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Feel instinctively threatened by your predatory gaze and silent, watchful nature.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Seek you out when a trail has gone cold, knowing your nose is better than any sensor array.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Mistake your stoicism for animalistic simplicity, failing to realize your keen tactical mind.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Shistavanen are covered in thick, coarse fur that ranges in color from dark brown and grey to deep black. They have pointed ears, glowing yellow or red eyes that excel in the dark, and muzzles filled with sharp teeth. Their hands end in sharp, retractable claws that are effective both as tools and weapons. They are remarkably fast and possess a leaping ability that allows them to navigate difficult terrain with ease. Physically, they are built for the chase—lean, muscular, and possessed of incredible endurance.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Shistavanen society is deeply communal but fiercely private. On the worlds of the Uvena system, they live in highly organized, defensive colonies. Their culture is built on the philosophy of &quot;The Pack,&quot; where every individual has a specific role that contributes to the survival of the whole. They are wary of outsiders and have a long history of rejecting galactic interference. However, those Shistavanen who do travel the stars often form new &quot;packs&quot; with their crewmates, transferring their deep-seated tribal loyalty to their companions.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Most Shistavanen follow a primal philosophy centered on the &quot;Eternal Hunt.&quot; They believe that life is a series of trials meant to hone one’s senses and strength. They value self-reliance, martial skill, and the ability to provide for one&#39;s pack. While they are not traditionally religious in a way humans might recognize, they have a profound respect for the &quot;Spirit of the Wild&quot;—the raw, uncivilized energy of the universe that rewards the swift and the cunning.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Master the scent of your enemy, protect the pack at all costs, never leave a trail half-followed.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Show unnecessary cruelty to prey, betray the trust of your pack, allow your natural instincts to be dulled by luxury.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Caamasi, Hovall, Lak_Sivrak, Pesh-Varik, Rau_Kee, Riv_Shiel, Severen, Voolvif, Wolam_Tarent.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="shistavanen-mechanics">Shistavanen Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 10</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 30 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Dexterity, Wisdom, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Charisma</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Shistavanen, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancShistavanen',	'Shistavanen',	'Humanoid, Shistavanen',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Imprecise", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CHA", "boost": ["DEX", "WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Shistavanen, often referred to as "Wolfmen," are a predatory, lupine species hailing from the Uvena system. Evolution on their harsh, hunter-dominated homeworld has gifted them with razor-sharp senses and a natural predatory instinct that makes them some of the most formidable trackers and scouts in the galaxy. Despite their feral appearance, Shistavanen are highly intelligent and technologically capable, though they are famously isolationist. For centuries, they preferred to remain within their own system, viewing the rest of the galaxy with deep-seated suspicion.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Bothese',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/bothan.png" alt="A Bothan"  class="description-image description-image--right">Bothans are renowned throughout the galaxy as master spies, political manipulators, and tireless seekers of information. Hailing from the industrial world of Bothawui, they are a feline-humanoid species driven by a cultural philosophy known as the Way: a guiding principle that emphasizes the acquisition of power and influence through the control of information. While their most famous historical achievement was the acquisition of the second Death Star&#39;s plans, Bothans have been influential players in the galactic theater for millennia.</p>
<p>Bothan culture is centered around the concept of the &quot;Clan,&quot; a massive extended family unit that serves as the foundation for their social and political life. To a Bothan, the success of the clan is paramount, and every secret gathered or deal brokered is a contribution to their family’s prestige. This competitive nature often makes them appear paranoid or opportunistic to outsiders, but among their own, it is seen as a necessary survival trait in a galaxy where knowledge is the ultimate currency.</p>
<p><strong>If you want an inquisitive, socially savvy character who excels at uncovering secrets and manipulating the political landscape, you should play a Bothan.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>View every conversation as a potential source of leverage or information.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Prioritize the interests of your clan or close allies above all else.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Feel restless when you aren&#39;t &quot;in the loop&quot; regarding local rumors or galactic events.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Hesitate to share sensitive information with you, fearing it will be used as collateral later.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Admire your networking skills and your ability to find a way out of any political entanglement.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Assume you have a hidden agenda, even when your intentions are genuine.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Bothans are covered in a coat of fine fur that ripples in response to their emotional state—a physiological trait known as &quot;fur-rippling.&quot; This makes it difficult for a Bothan to lie to another Bothan, though they have mastered the art of keeping their fur still when interacting with other species. They have tapered ears, slightly elongated snouts, and expressive eyes. Fur colors vary from cream and light brown to deep blacks and grays, often turning white or silver with age. They are generally slightly shorter than the average human but possess a lithe, graceful build.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Bothan society is organized into a complex hierarchy of clans. The Bothan Council acts as the primary governing body on Bothawui, though much of their &quot;governing&quot; happens through backroom deals and shifting alliances. This focus on information has led to the creation of the Bothan Spy Network, arguably the most effective intelligence-gathering organization in the galaxy. Despite their reputation for cloak-and-dagger antics, Bothans are also highly skilled in commerce and law, often serving as diplomats, corporate executives, and high-level administrators in diverse planetary governments.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Bothans largely adhere to the Way, which teaches that power is not found in brute force, but in the connections between people and the secrets they keep. They value loyalty to the clan above almost everything else, believing that an individual is only as strong as the network they support. While many are viewed as self-serving, a Bothan&#39;s dedication to a cause they truly believe in—such as the downfall of a tyranny—is absolute and often involves great personal sacrifice.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Advance the prestige of your clan, seek out hidden truths, maintain your network of contacts.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Reveal a clan secret to an outsider, allow a vital piece of information to be lost, ignore a brewing political shift.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Asyr, Borsk, Fey&#39;lya, Garmik, Koth, Liska, Mak&#39;Tan, Memit, Nanreth, Ola, Pesk&#39;pau, Rill&#39;it, Tav, Teranya, Traest, Utric, Velth, we&#39;shai.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="bothan-mechanics">Bothan Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Intelligence, Charisma, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Constitution</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Bothese, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancBothan',	'Bothan',	'Bothan, Humanoid',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CON", "boost": ["INT", "CHA", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Bothans are renowned throughout the galaxy as master spies, political manipulators, and tireless seekers of information. Hailing from the industrial world of Bothawui, they are a feline-humanoid species driven by a cultural philosophy known as the Way: a guiding principle that emphasizes the acquisition of power and influence through the control of information. While their most famous historical achievement was the acquisition of the second Death Star''s plans, Bothans have been influential players in the galactic theater for millennia.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Mon Calamarian',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/moncalamari.png" alt="A Mon Calamari"  class="description-image description-image--right">The Mon Calamari are a species of amphibious humanoids renowned for their brilliant analytical minds, their mastery of aquatic engineering, and their soulful dedication to the cause of freedom. Hailing from the ocean world of Mon Cala (also known as Dac), they share their globe with the more aggressive Quarren, a partnership that has shaped their talent for diplomacy and compromise. To the Mon Calamari, technology is not merely a tool but a form of art; their starships are famous for being unique masterpieces of organic curves and redundant systems, reflecting the fluid nature of their underwater cities.</p>
<p>Throughout galactic history, the Mon Calamari have stood as a bulwark against tyranny. Despite their peaceful inclinations and deep appreciation for art and music, they are formidable tacticians who view space combat as a three-dimensional ballet. Their ability to remain calm under pressure and their perspective on the &quot;greater good&quot; make them natural leaders, particularly in the face of overwhelming odds.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a brilliant, idealistic character who combines scientific genius with a deep spiritual connection to the cosmos, you should play a Mon Calamari.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>View engineering and starship maintenance as a creative, artistic pursuit rather than a chore.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Stay remarkably calm during crises, analyzing variables while others succumb to panic.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Feel a deep, physical longing for the open ocean or large bodies of water when away from your homeworld.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Seek you out for your tactical expertise and your ability to see &quot;the big picture&quot; in complex situations.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Find your stare disconcerting, as your panoramic vision allows you to focus on multiple things at once.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Respect your integrity, knowing that once you commit to a cause, you will see it through to the end.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Mon Calamari are bipedal with fish-like features, including large, high-set eyes that can move independently, allowing them to see in a nearly 360-degree field. Their skin is smooth and leathery, typically appearing in shades of salmon, gold, brown, or blue, often mottled with spots or stripes. They have webbed hands and feet, and their heads are dome-shaped with small feelers around the mouth. While they breathe air, they are equally at home underwater and can dive to incredible depths. Their unique physiology allows them to sleep with only one half of their brain at a time, making them exceptionally alert.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Mon Calamari society is built on a foundation of coexistence and high culture. On Mon Cala, they inhabit massive, floating city-ships that serve as hubs for both industry and art. They are highly communal and value the consensus of the group, though they encourage individual expression through craftsmanship and intellectual pursuit. Because they share their planet with the Quarren, their politics are defined by complex treaties and a constant strive for balance. In the wider galaxy, Mon Calamari are often found in high-ranking roles within scientific institutes, diplomatic corps, and naval commands.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Most Mon Calamari are driven by a strong moral compass and a belief in the sanctity of life and freedom. They often view the galaxy as a vast, interconnected ecosystem, much like the oceans of their home. While they are not overly religious in a traditional sense, they have a profound respect for the &quot;Flow&quot;—the natural order of the universe—and believe that one’s actions should always contribute to the harmony of the whole.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Create something of lasting beauty, defend the defenseless, seek peaceful solutions to conflict whenever possible.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Allow a machine to fall into disrepair, betray a diplomatic trust, pollute a natural waterway.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Ackbar, Bant, Cilghal, Gial, Ibtisam, Jesmin, Karari, Meena, Merai, Naeco, Niebe, Perit, Rekara, Terpfen.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="mon-calamari-mechanics">Mon Calamari Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet, swim 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Intelligence, Wisdom, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Strength</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Mon Calamarian, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancMonCalamari',	'Mon Calamari',	'Humanoid, Mon Calamari',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"scent": "Vague", "vision": "Precise", "hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "STR", "boost": ["INT", "WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'The Mon Calamari are a species of amphibious humanoids renowned for their brilliant analytical minds, their mastery of aquatic engineering, and their soulful dedication to the cause of freedom. Hailing from the ocean world of Mon Cala (also known as Dac), they share their globe with the more aggressive Quarren, a partnership that has shaped their talent for diplomacy and compromise. To the Mon Calamari, technology is not merely a tool but a form of art; their starships are famous for being unique masterpieces of organic curves and redundant systems, reflecting the fluid nature of their underwater cities.'),
(10,	25,	'Basic, Shyriiwook',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/wookiee.png" alt="A Wookiee"  class="description-image description-image--right">Wookiees are widely recognized as one of the most formidable and honorable species in the galaxy. Hailing from the forest world of Kashyyyk, they are towering figures of strength and fur, known as much for their short tempers as for their deep loyalty and technological brilliance. Despite a history of being targeted by slavers and imperial forces, Wookiees have remained a cornerstone of galactic society, serving as master starship mechanics, courageous pilots, and relentless warriors.</p>
<p>A Wookiee’s life is governed by a strict code of honor. The concept of the &quot;life debt&quot;—an oath of total loyalty to one who saves a Wookiee&#39;s life—is the most famous of these traditions, though their dedication to their &quot;honor family&quot; is equally profound. Whether navigating the dangerous shadowlands of their home planet or the neon-lit corridors of a space station, Wookiees bring a blend of primal power and sophisticated intellect to every endeavor.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a powerful, loyal character who balances raw physical might with a surprisingly gentle heart (until provoked), you should play a Wookiee.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Form deep, unshakable bonds with your adventuring party, treating them as your honor family.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Prefer to solve mechanical or technical problems with your hands, showing a natural aptitude for machinery.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Experience bouts of intense emotion, from roaring joy to a terrifying rage when your friends are threatened.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Feel intimidated by your size and strength, worrying that a misunderstood joke might cost them an arm.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Assume you are a &quot;simple&quot; primitive, drastically underestimating your intelligence and technical skills.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on you as the rock of the group, knowing you will never abandon an ally.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Wookiees are tall, bipedal humanoids entirely covered in a thick coat of hair that ranges from albino white to dark charcoal, though various shades of brown are most common. They have retractable climbing claws used exclusively for scaling the massive trees of Kashyyyk—using them in combat is considered a grave violation of their honor code. Their eyes are usually blue, green, or brown. As they age, their fur may gray or thin, but their physical strength remains legendary well into their second or third century of life.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Wookiee society is deeply rooted in the ecosystem of Kashyyyk. They live in massive, technologically advanced cities built high in the canopies of wroshyr trees. This harmony between nature and high technology defines their outlook: they see no conflict between ancient ritual and modern engineering. Because they cannot speak Galactic Basic (their vocal cords are only capable of the grunts and roars of Shyriiwook), they often rely on translation droids or the patience of longtime companions to communicate with other species.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Wookiees value honor, courage, and the protection of the natural world. Many follow a spiritual path that respects the &quot;Life Tree,&quot; a personification of the interconnectedness of all living things. While they are not a xenophobic people, their history of being exploited by authoritarian regimes has left many Wookiees with a deep-seated distrust of imperial structures.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Protect your honor family, maintain your equipment with care, stand against those who trade in sentient lives.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Use your climbing claws in a fight, break a life debt, allow a slight against your family to go unanswered.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Attichitcuk, Chewbacca, Dewlanna, Gungi, Grakchawwaa, Hanharr, Itchy, Lohgarra, Lowbacca, Mallatobuck, Raabakyysh, Salporin, Tarfful, Tyvokka, Zaalbar.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="wookiee-mechanics">Wookiee Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 10</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Strength, Constitution, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Charisma</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Shyriiwook. You can understand, read, and write Galactic Basic, but your physiology prevents you from speaking it.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancWookiee',	'Wookiee',	'Humanoid, Wookiee',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"scent": "Vague", "vision": "Precise", "hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CHA", "boost": ["CON", "STR", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Wookiees are widely recognized as one of the most formidable and honorable species in the galaxy. Hailing from the forest world of Kashyyyk, they are towering figures of strength and fur, known as much for their short tempers as for their deep loyalty and technological brilliance. Despite a history of being targeted by slavers and imperial forces, Wookiees have remained a cornerstone of galactic society, serving as master starship mechanics, courageous pilots, and relentless warriors.'),
(12,	25,	'Basic, Savrip',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/savrip.png" alt="A Mantellian Savrip" class="description-image description-image--right">If there is one species in the galaxy that suffers from a profound PR problem, it is the Mantellian Savrip. Native to the plains and mountains of Ord Mantell, these hulking, hunched bipeds resemble a terrifying cross between a reptile and a primate. Because of their intimidating appearance, venomous bite, and immense physical strength, early galactic explorers categorized them as dumb, violent beasts. This misconception was immortalized when the Savrip was included as a monstrous piece in the popular game of Dejarik (holochess).</p>
<p>In reality, Mantellian Savrips are fully sentient, possessing their own language, tribal culture, and a surprising aptitude for technology. Those who manage to leave Ord Mantell often find themselves forced into roles as enforcers, gladiators, or bodyguards, utilizing the galaxy&#39;s prejudice to their advantage. A Savrip adventurer is often driven by a desire to prove their intellect, utilizing their massive physical frame as a shield while their sharp mind does the heavy lifting.</p>
<p><strong>If you want to play a towering, physically dominating character who subverts expectations with a sharp intellect and a venomous bite, you should play a Mantellian Savrip.</strong></p>
<h2 id="you-might-">You Might…</h2>
<ul>
<li><p>Feel a quiet, burning frustration when people speak slowly to you or assume you are an animal.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Use your massive size to casually intimidate adversaries without having to draw a weapon.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Take great joy in surprising smug mechanics or slicers by expertly diagnosing a hyperdrive fault.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h2>
<ul>
<li><p>Give you a wide berth, assuming you might go into a feral rage at any moment.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Complain when you take up too much space in a starship corridor or break a fragile chair.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Point you toward the biggest, most heavily armored enemy in the room and ask you to deal with it.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h2>
<p>Mantellian Savrips are massive, imposing creatures, often standing well over two and a half meters (8 feet) tall. They have a hunched, powerful posture, with incredibly long arms whose knuckles can drag on the ground when they walk. Their skin is thick, leathery, and reptilian, ranging in color from mottled greens and browns to deep grey. Their heads are somewhat serpentine, featuring forward-facing eyes, a lack of an external nose, and a wide jaw filled with sharp teeth capable of delivering a paralytic venom.</p>
<h2 id="society">Society</h2>
<p>On Ord Mantell, Savrips live in loose-knit, nomadic tribes across the savannas and mountain ranges. Their society was heavily disrupted by colonists and criminals who hunted them for sport or captured them for gladiatorial arenas. Because they are often shot on sight by ignorant colonists, their culture has become highly defensive and cautious. Those who integrate into galactic society usually have to work twice as hard to prove they are sentient beings, often learning multiple languages and technical skills to force others to acknowledge their intelligence.</p>
<h2 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h2>
<p>Savrips believe that survival requires both a strong arm and a sharp mind. They value actions over words, as words have rarely protected them from the blasters of ignorant bounty hunters. They possess a deep loyalty to those rare individuals who look past their monstrous exterior and treat them as equals. Many Savrips hold a deep-seated grudge against the creators of Dejarik, viewing the game as an enduring insult to their people.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Protect those who cannot protect themselves, prove your intellect to those who doubt you, break the chains of oppression.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Allow someone to treat you as a pet or a beast of burden, attack a genuinely defenseless organic without provocation.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h2>
<p>Bree-Yark, Chraas, Gorc, Klat, Rroak, Skavak, Thrak, Vorok.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id="mantellian-savrip-mechanics">Mantellian Savrip Mechanics</h2>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 12</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Large</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Strength, Intelligence, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Charisma</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Savrip, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancSavrip',	'Mantellian Savrip',	'Humanoid, Mantellian Savrip',	'Large',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CHA", "boost": ["STR", "INT", {"free": 1}]}}',	'If there is one species in the galaxy that suffers from a profound PR problem, it is the Mantellian Savrip. Native to the plains and mountains of Ord Mantell, these hulking, hunched bipeds resemble a terrifying cross between a reptile and a primate. Because of their intimidating appearance, venomous bite, and immense physical strength, early galactic explorers categorized them as dumb, violent beasts. This misconception was immortalized when the Savrip was included as a monstrous piece in the popular game of Dejarik (holochess).'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Zabraki',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/zabrak.png" alt="A Zabrak"  class="description-image description-image--right">Zabrak are one of the most independent and strong-willed species in the galaxy. Known for their distinctive horns and intricate facial tattoos, they hail from the harsh world of Iridonia, though their tenacity has led them to establish many colonies, most notably on the planet Dathomir. The rugged environment of their home world—filled with predatory life and treacherous terrain—forged a culture that prizes self-discipline, martial prowess, and an indomitable spirit.</p>
<p>Zabrak are driven by a fierce sense of individual accomplishment and a desire to prove their worth. They are often perceived as intense or even arrogant, but this stems from a deep-seated belief that nothing is impossible for those with the will to endure. Whether they are serving as elite mercenaries, focused scholars, or revolutionary leaders, Zabrak approach every task with a grim determination and a refusal to back down from a challenge.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a resilient, disciplined character who thrives under pressure and never admits defeat, you should play a Zabrak.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>View physical and mental hardships as tests of your character and strength.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Take great pride in your facial tattoos, seeing them as a map of your life’s achievements and personality.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Stand your ground in the face of overwhelming odds, refusing to retreat unless it is strategically necessary.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Find your intensity intimidating and assume you are always looking for a fight.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Admire your reliability, knowing that you have the stamina to see a mission through to its end.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Mistake your self-confidence for coldness or lack of empathy.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Zabrak are near-humans characterized by a crown of vestigial horns that grow in various patterns during puberty. Their skin tones range across the human spectrum, but also include vibrant shades of red, orange, yellow, and even deep blacks. Almost all Zabrak wear intricate facial tattoos, which are often applied during a rite of passage; these designs are highly personalized and reflect the individual’s lineage, personality, or accomplishments. Physically, they are incredibly hardy, possessing a second heart and a high resistance to physical pain.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Zabrak society is meritocratic and highly organized. On Iridonia, they live in subterranean cities to avoid the planet’s frequent acid winds, which has fostered a culture of communal discipline. Despite their solitary reputation, they are deeply loyal to their &quot;nests&quot; or colonies. Because they were among the first species to master interstellar travel, Zabrak colonies are found in almost every sector of the galaxy. These colonies often vary wildly—from the industrial hubs of the Core to the dark, mystical, and matriarchal clans of the Dathomirians.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Zabrak believe that the universe is a series of obstacles designed to be overcome. They value self-reliance and the development of one’s own inner strength. While many adhere to a strict warrior’s code, others apply this same discipline to the arts, sciences, or commerce. They generally have little patience for those who complain or give up easily. To a Zabrak, honor is earned through action, not granted by birthright.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Master your emotions, overcome your personal limits, honor your word once given.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Show cowardice in the face of danger, allow a physical weakness to go uncorrected, betray your colony or nest.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Agen, Bao-Dur, Eeth, Kadrian, Kasidan, Maris, Maubari, Maul, Savage, Sirak, Sugi, Wolf, Zarina.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="zabrak-mechanics">Zabrak Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 10</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Constitution, Wisdom, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Charisma</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Zabraki, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancZabrak',	'Zabrak',	'Humanoid, Zabrak',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CHA", "boost": ["CON", "WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Zabrak are one of the most independent and strong-willed species in the galaxy. Known for their distinctive horns and intricate facial tattoos, they hail from the harsh world of Iridonia, though their tenacity has led them to establish many colonies, most notably on the planet Dathomir. The rugged environment of their home world—filled with predatory life and treacherous terrain—forged a culture that prizes self-discipline, martial prowess, and an indomitable spirit.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Dosh',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/trandoshan.png" alt="A Trandoshan"  class="description-image description-image--right">Trandoshans (or T&#39;doshok, as they call themselves) are a cold-blooded, reptilian species known throughout the galaxy for their immense strength, regenerative abilities, and their spiritual devotion to the hunt. Hailing from the dangerous world of Trandosha (or Hsskor), which shares the same star system as the Wookiee homeworld of Kashyyyk, they have a long-standing and bitter rivalry with their furry neighbors. To a Trandoshan, life is not measured in years or wealth, but in &quot;Jagannath points&quot;—a spiritual currency earned through honorable kills and successful hunts.</p>
<p>Their culture is dictated by their devotion to a deity known as the Scorekeeper. This goddess is said to watch every action a Trandoshan takes, tallying their successes and failures in a Great Hunt that spans a lifetime. This makes them exceptionally dangerous adversaries; a Trandoshan isn&#39;t just fighting for survival or credits—they are fighting for their standing in the afterlife. While many find work as bounty hunters, slavers, or mercenaries, some &quot;score-clans&quot; apply their relentless nature to law enforcement, exploration, or high-stakes corporate competition.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a physically imposing, resilient character with a unique spiritual drive and a &quot;never say die&quot; attitude, you should play a Trandoshan.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Track your successes and failures meticulously, viewing every victory as a gift to the Scorekeeper.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Display a pragmatic, often survivalist outlook on life that others might mistake for cruelty.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Take significant risks in combat to earn &quot;points&quot; through acts of bravery or skill.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Expect you to be violent or aggressive, given your species&#39; reputation as the galaxy’s premier hunters.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Feel uneasy watching your skin shed or seeing a lost limb slowly grow back over time.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Respect your incredible tracking skills and your ability to thrive in hostile environments.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Trandoshans are towering, bipedal reptiles with thick, scaly hides that range from sandy brown and olive green to vibrant orange or yellow. Their eyes are large and capable of seeing into the infrared spectrum, making them lethal night hunters. Perhaps their most famous trait is their regenerative capability; a Trandoshan can regrow lost limbs, tails, and even patches of skin over a period of weeks. As they age, their scales may thicken and darken, and they periodically shed their entire skin in a process that can leave them temporarily irritable but physically refreshed.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Trandoshan society is deeply competitive and hierarchical. Everything is centered around the hunt and the accumulation of Jagannath points. High-scoring hunters earn the right to lead clans and choose the best spawning mates, while those with low scores are often marginalized. This competitive drive has occasionally led to internal strife, but it usually manifests as a collective push to dominate their star system. Despite their fierce reputation, they are technologically advanced, particularly in the fields of weaponry and starship design, often favoring heavy armor and overwhelming firepower.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>The worship of the Scorekeeper is the dominant force in Trandoshan life. They believe that upon death, the Scorekeeper judges their total Jagannath points to determine their place in the afterlife. While &quot;points&quot; are traditionally earned through combat and hunting, modern Trandoshans often interpret &quot;the hunt&quot; metaphorically, seeking to &quot;capture&quot; successful business deals or &quot;track down&quot; scientific breakthroughs. They value bravery, cunning, and the fulfillment of oaths, though their definition of &quot;honor&quot; often allows for ambush and ruthless efficiency.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Accumulate Jagannath points through successful hunts, honor the Scorekeeper in all things, regrow and return to the fight.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Show mercy to a marked target without a vow of debt, die with a low score, allow a rival to claim your kill.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Bossk, Chuundar, Desann, Fusith, Garnac, Harkkur, Krashesh, Nakis, Ossyk, Pekt, Rusk, Sskeer, Tessek, Yingak.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="trandoshan-mechanics">Trandoshan Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 10</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Strength, Wisdom, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Dexterity</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Dosh, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Infrared Vision:</strong> You have darkvision, allowing you to see in total darkness by sensing heat signatures.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancTrandoshan',	'Trandoshan',	'Humanoid, Trandoshan',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "feature": ["clfDarkvision"], "attribute": {"flaw": "DEX", "boost": ["STR", "WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Trandoshans (or T''doshok, as they call themselves) are a cold-blooded, reptilian species known throughout the galaxy for their immense strength, regenerative abilities, and their spiritual devotion to the hunt. Hailing from the dangerous world of Trandosha (or Hsskor), which shares the same star system as the Wookiee homeworld of Kashyyyk, they have a long-standing and bitter rivalry with their furry neighbors. To a Trandoshan, life is not measured in years or wealth, but in "Jagannath points"—a spiritual currency earned through honorable kills and successful hunts.'),
(6,	20,	'Basic, Jawaese, Jawa Trade Language',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/jawa.png" alt="A Jawa"  class="description-image description-image--right">Jawas are a diminutive, resourceful, and often misunderstood species native to the desert world of Tatooine. Known primarily as scavengers and junk traders, they roam the dunes in massive, treaded fortresses called Sandcrawlers, searching for lost droids, discarded technology, and ship wreckage. While many galactic travelers view them as pests or thieves, Jawas are actually master refurbishers with an incredible aptitude for electronics and a complex, communal social structure built on the necessity of desert survival.</p>
<p>Jawa culture is defined by &quot;the trade.&quot; To a Jawa, almost everything has a value, and no piece of scrap is too small to be repurposed. They possess a unique &quot;scavenger&#39;s intuition&quot; that allows them to see the potential in a pile of rusted metal that others would simply discard. Though they rarely leave their desert homes, those who do often find work as technicians, scrap brokers, or engineers, bringing their uncanny ability to make &quot;junk&quot; work to the wider galaxy.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a clever, small-statured character who can fix anything with a handful of spare parts and has a knack for finding hidden value, you should play a Jawa.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Scurry through tight spaces to gain a tactical advantage or access restricted areas.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Hoard interesting bits of scrap, wires, and components &quot;just in case&quot; they become useful.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Communicate in a high-pitched, rapid-fire language that sounds like gibberish to the uninitiated.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Underestimate your intelligence, viewing you as a simple scavenger rather than a skilled technician.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Keep a close eye on their droids and equipment when you are around, fearing they might be &quot;acquired.&quot;</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on you to fix vital systems when proper replacement parts are nowhere to be found.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Jawas are easily recognized by their heavy, sand-colored hooded robes and their glowing yellow or orange eyes, which peer out from the darkness of their hoods. Their true physical appearance remains one of the galaxy&#39;s great mysteries, as they are rarely seen without their protective clothing and specialized cooling fans. They emit a strong, pungent odor—a combination of the chemical solutions used to preserve their moisture and a unique pheromonal language that conveys information about their health, mood, and clan lineage.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Jawa society is strictly clan-based. Each clan operates a Sandcrawler, which serves as a mobile city, fortress, and warehouse. Once a year, during the &quot;swap meet&quot; season, dozens of clans gather in the deep desert to trade goods, exchange information, and arrange marriages to ensure genetic diversity. They are highly communal and rarely act alone; a lone Jawa is usually a sign of a great tragedy or a very unusual ambition. Their economy is entirely circular, focused on the recovery and resale of the vast amounts of technology abandoned in the desert.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Jawas believe that the desert provides for those who are clever enough to find its treasures. They value the clan above all else and believe that survival is a group effort. While they aren&#39;t traditionally religious, they have a deep, superstitious reverence for ancient technology, sometimes viewing particularly advanced or &quot;rebellious&quot; droids as possessing a spirit of their own. They possess a pragmatic morality: taking something that is &quot;lost&quot; isn&#39;t stealing; it&#39;s simply returning it to the cycle of trade.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Salvage what is broken, negotiate the best possible price, protect the clan&#39;s Sandcrawler.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Waste a functioning power cell, abandon a clan mate in the desert, reveal the secret location of a clan fortress.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Akkik, Dathcha, Het, Jek, Kalit, Klegg, Meeko, Nebit, Rinn, Tikkes, Ttek, Wittin.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="jawa-mechanics">Jawa Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 6</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Small</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Dexterity, Intelligence, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Strength</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Jawaese, Jawa Trade Talk. You can understand Galactic Basic but your vocal cords make it difficult to speak it clearly.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancJawa',	'Jawa',	'Humanoid, Jawa',	'Small',	'{"sense": {"scent": "Vague", "vision": "Precise", "hearing": "Imprecise"}, "feature": ["clfDesertSurvivor", "clfScavengersEye", "clfTinkersKnack"], "attribute": {"flaw": "STR", "boost": ["DEX", "INT", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Jawas are a diminutive, resourceful, and often misunderstood species native to the desert world of Tatooine. Known primarily as scavengers and junk traders, they roam the dunes in massive, treaded fortresses called Sandcrawlers, searching for lost droids, discarded technology, and ship wreckage. While many galactic travelers view them as pests or thieves, Jawas are actually master refurbishers with an incredible aptitude for electronics and a complex, communal social structure built on the necessity of desert survival.'),
(8,	20,	'Basic, Ortolan',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/ortolan.png" alt="An Ortolan"  class="description-image description-image--right">Ortolans are a stout, blue-skinned species hailing from the frigid, mineral-rich planet of Rebo. With their long, trunk-like noses and oversized, floppy ears, they are often underestimated as mere comic relief—a mistake few make twice once they witness an Ortolan’s industrial drive or culinary genius. Their homeworld is a harsh, icy environment where food is scarce and difficult to procure, which has led to a species-wide obsession with food, flavor, and resource management. To an Ortolan, a well-stocked pantry is a sign of high status, and a perfectly seasoned meal is a profound spiritual experience.</p>
<p>Beyond their appetites, Ortolans are exceptionally skilled at sensing vibrations and frequencies, a trait that makes them natural musicians and expert miners. Their trunk-like noses are not just for smelling; they are highly sensitive organs capable of detecting minerals deep underground or subtle changes in a starship’s engine vibration. Whether they are performing in a world-class swing band, managing a high-stakes mining colony, or serving as a ship’s chef and mechanic, Ortolans bring a relentless, cheerful energy to any crew.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a hardy, sensory-focused character who values the finer things in life and can sniff out opportunity (or danger) from a mile away, you should play an Ortolan.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Use food as your primary means of diplomacy, celebration, and even conflict resolution.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Possess a deep, resonant love for music and rhythm, often tapping out beats on your equipment.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Obsess over the quality of your supplies, ensuring the party is never without high-quality rations.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Assume you are easily motivated by bribes of food or drink.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Find your physical appearance endearing or &quot;cute,&quot; often failing to realize how physically strong and resilient you actually are.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on your sensitive hearing and sense of smell to alert the group to hidden threats.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Ortolans are short, heavy-set bipeds with thick, leathery blue skin that provides excellent insulation against the cold. Their most prominent feature is a large, trunk-like nose used for both smelling and tactile manipulation. They have large, floppy ears that grant them acute hearing and the ability to perceive subsonic vibrations. To support their high metabolisms and survive the winters of Rebo, they possess significant fat stores, giving them a round, soft appearance. Their fingers are thick but surprisingly nimble, capable of playing complex musical instruments or repairing delicate electronics.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Ortolan society is organized around &quot;Kitchen-Clans,&quot; where social standing is determined by one&#39;s contribution to the community&#39;s food stores and cultural output. On Rebo, they live in sophisticated subterranean warrens that protect them from the icy winds. They are a highly industrious people; because their world is rich in heavy metals, they have a natural affinity for mining and metallurgy. In the galaxy at large, Ortolans are most famous for their &quot;Food-Songs&quot;—musical performances that are meant to evoke the taste and texture of specific delicacies. They are generally peaceful and prefer to settle disputes through trade or &quot;cook-offs&quot; rather than open warfare.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Ortolans follow a philosophy of &quot;The Great Harvest,&quot; believing that the universe is a garden meant to be tasted and enjoyed. They value hospitality above almost all else—refusing a guest food is considered a grave sin in Ortolan culture. They believe that sound and flavor are the two fundamental languages of the soul. While they are pragmatists who understand the value of a credit, they believe wealth is useless unless it can be converted into something delicious or melodious.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Share your table with the hungry, find the rhythm in every machine, preserve the recipes of your ancestors.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Waste a perfectly good meal, ignore a discordant sound in a starship engine, allow a guest to leave your home unsatisfied.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Balo, Droopy, Gid, Max, Nabbe, Rebo, Snee, Tizz, Weechee, Yub, Zid.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="ortolan-mechanics">Ortolan Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 10</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Small</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 20 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Constitution, Wisdom, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Dexterity</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Ortolan, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancOrtolan',	'Ortolan',	'Humanoid, Ortolan',	'Small',	'{"sense": {"scent": "Imprecise", "vision": "Precise", "hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "DEX", "boost": ["CON", "WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Ortolans are a stout, blue-skinned species hailing from the frigid, mineral-rich planet of Rebo. With their long, trunk-like noses and oversized, floppy ears, they are often underestimated as mere comic relief—a mistake few make twice once they witness an Ortolan’s industrial drive or culinary genius. Their homeworld is a harsh, icy environment where food is scarce and difficult to procure, which has led to a species-wide obsession with food, flavor, and resource management. To an Ortolan, a well-stocked pantry is a sign of high status, and a perfectly seasoned meal is a profound spiritual experience.'),
(10,	25,	'Basic, Tusken',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/tusken.png" alt="A Tusken Raider" class="description-image description-image--right">Tusken Raiders, known colloquially by outsiders as Sand People, are the fierce, nomadic indigenous inhabitants of the desert world Tatooine. To the rest of the galaxy, they are terrifying specters of the deep dunes—hostile, territorial, and deadly. However, beneath their heavy moisture-preserving wrappings lies a deeply spiritual and communal society. Their entire culture is built around survival in one of the galaxy’s most unforgiving environments, fostering a profound respect for the scarce resources of their world, particularly water.</p>
<p>Tuskens are master survivalists and beast-tamers, forming lifelong, almost mystical bonds with the massive Banthas they ride. Because their oral history is sacred and must be passed down with flawless accuracy, their storytellers are the most revered members of their clans. A Tusken far from Tatooine is incredibly rare; such an individual might be an exile, a lone survivor of a clan wiped out by off-worlders, or a scout seeking to understand the &quot;sky-dwellers&quot; who constantly encroach upon their sacred sands.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a fierce, survival-focused character with a rich, hidden culture and a talent for ambushes and beast-handling, you should play a Tusken Raider.</strong></p>
<h2 id="you-might-">You Might…</h2>
<ul>
<li><p>View water as a sacred resource, carefully rationing it and judging those who waste it.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Prefer to communicate through sharp gestures, head-tilts, and roaring bellows rather than spoken words.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Form an intense, protective bond with an animal companion or your chosen party.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h2>
<ul>
<li><p>Find your fully wrapped appearance and breath mask intimidating or unnerving.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Assume you are a hostile primitive, failing to recognize the complex traditions that guide your actions.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on your unmatched wilderness survival skills when the technology fails and the environment turns deadly.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h2>
<p>The true physical appearance of a Tusken Raider is one of the galaxy&#39;s best-kept secrets. To expose bare flesh is considered a severe taboo, often punishable by exile or death. Consequently, from head to toe, they are completely covered in layers of heavy cloth, leather wrappings, and bandoliers. Their faces are obscured by complex moisture-trapping breath masks and eye-goggles designed to keep out the blinding glare of binary suns and stinging sandstorms. They are generally tall, lean, and highly athletic, built for endurance in extreme heat.</p>
<h2 id="society">Society</h2>
<p>Tusken society revolves around the clan and the tribe. They are nomadic, moving their camps to follow the moisture and avoid the massive Krayt Dragons. Life is harsh, and weakness is a liability, meaning their training in combat and survival begins in childhood. The bond between a Tusken and their Bantha mount is central to their social standing; when a Tusken&#39;s Bantha dies, the rider is often sent into the desert alone to find another or perish. They view all off-worlders as water-stealing trespassers, though they have been known to negotiate when it serves the tribe&#39;s survival.</p>
<h2 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h2>
<p>The desert is a crucible that purifies the strong. Tuskens believe that the land is sacred and that taking more than you need to survive is an affront to the world itself. They value tradition, martial prowess, and flawless memory—a storyteller who misspeaks a single word of a clan&#39;s history is often banished. They possess a strict code of honor, though it is an honor completely alien to galactic norms.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Protect the tribe’s water, honor the history of your ancestors, strike swiftly against trespassers.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Expose your flesh to an outsider, waste a natural resource, abandon a bonded animal.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h2>
<p>A&#39;Koba, A&#39;Yark, K&#39;Kruhk, Grk&#39;kkrs&#39;ar, R&#39;Kik D&#39;Nook, Sliven, URoRRuR&#39;R&#39;R.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id="tusken-raider-mechanics">Tusken Raider Mechanics</h2>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 10</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Constitution, Wisdom, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Charisma</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancTusken',	'Tusken Raider',	'Tusken Raider',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CHA", "boost": ["CON", "WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Tusken Raiders, known colloquially by outsiders as Sand People, are the fierce, nomadic indigenous inhabitants of the desert world Tatooine. To the rest of the galaxy, they are terrifying specters of the deep dunes—hostile, territorial, and deadly. However, beneath their heavy moisture-preserving wrappings lies a deeply spiritual and communal society. Their entire culture is built around survival in one of the galaxy’s most unforgiving environments, fostering a profound respect for the scarce resources of their world, particularly water.'),
(6,	20,	'Anzellan, Basic',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/anzellan.png" alt="An anzellan"  class="description-image description-image--right">Anzellans are a diminutive, whiskers-faced species from the world of Anzell. Despite their tiny stature—barely standing at a height that reaches the knees of most humans—they are some of the most sought-after droidsmiths and tech-wizards in the galaxy. Their unique physiology includes specialized eyes that act like high-powered microscopes, allowing them to see individual circuits, microscopic fractures, and complex wiring that even the most advanced scanners might miss.</p>
<p>Anzellans are known for their high-pitched, rapid-fire speech and their seemingly boundless energy. While they are often treated as cute or harmless novelties by the uninformed, those in the know—from Outer Rim spice runners to high-ranking Resistance leaders—know that an Anzellan with a welding torch is a miracle worker. They are a communal and spirited people who can find a home in any workshop, provided there are enough spare parts to tinker with and a high enough stool to reach the workbench.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a tiny, brilliant technician who can perform surgery on a starship&#39;s computer and has a personality ten times their size, you should play an Anzellan.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>View a &quot;totaled&quot; droid as a fun afternoon project rather than scrap metal.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Struggle to navigate environments designed for larger beings, often using pipes or furniture as scaffolding.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Speak your mind with total honesty, often in a mix of Basic and Anzellan that is as fast as your hands.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Attempt to pick you up or treat you like a pet, a mistake they only make once.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Be baffled by how you managed to fix a hyperdrive with nothing but a pair of tweezers and a bit of solder.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on you to sneak into small vents or conduits that no one else can fit through.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Anzellans are exceptionally small bipeds with wrinkled skin and distinctive, long facial whiskers that aid in their tactile perception. Their most remarkable feature is their eyes, which possess corneal structures capable of zooming in to see microscopic detail. This &quot;micro-vision&quot; is what makes them natural-born engineers. They have high-pitched voices and move with a quick, jerky agility. Despite their small size, they are surprisingly hardy, with a high metabolism that requires frequent (though small) meals to maintain their frenetic pace.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Anzellan society is centered around the &quot;Work-Nest&quot;—communal living and working spaces where knowledge is shared freely among all members. They value technical mastery above all other traits. While they have a homeworld, they are increasingly found in nomadic enclaves on space stations and in urban hubs across the galaxy. They are intensely social and collaborative; an Anzellan rarely works on a complex project alone if they can find a friend to hold the light or pass the tools.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Anzellans believe that the universe is a giant machine, and that it is their sacred duty to keep the parts moving smoothly. They have a deep respect for &quot;The Spark&quot;—the moment a dormant piece of technology flickers back to life. They are generally lighthearted and optimistic, believing that there is no problem so big it can’t be solved by someone small enough to see the details.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Fix it if it’s broken, listen to what the machine is telling you, always look closer.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Intentionally sabotage a working droid, throw away a salvageable component, ignore a friend in need of a repair.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Babu, Chabu, Dabu, Frik, Kiki, Meebu, Nabu, Pabu, Tibu, Zabu.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="anzellan-mechanics">Anzellan Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 6</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Tiny</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 20 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Dexterity, Intelligence, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Strength</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Anzellan, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Reach:</strong> Due to your Tiny size, you have a reach of 0 feet. You must enter a creature&#39;s space to hit them with a melee attack.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancAnzellan',	'Anzellan',	'Anzellan, Humanoid',	'Tiny',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attack": {"reach": 0}, "attribute": {"flaw": "STR", "boost": ["DEX", "INT", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Anzellans are a diminutive, whiskers-faced species from the world of Anzell. Despite their tiny stature—barely standing at a height that reaches the knees of most humans—they are some of the most sought-after droidsmiths and tech-wizards in the galaxy. Their unique physiology includes specialized eyes that act like high-powered microscopes, allowing them to see individual circuits, microscopic fractures, and complex wiring that even the most advanced scanners might miss.'),
(12,	25,	'Basic, Gamorrean',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/gamorrean.png" alt="A Gamorrean"  class="description-image description-image--right">Gamorreans are a powerful, porcine species from the lush, primitive world of Gamorr. Known across the galaxy for their massive physical bulk, green skin, and tusks, they have a reputation as the quintessential hired muscle. In Gamorrean culture, physical combat is not just a necessity but a way of life; their society is defined by a state of constant, ritualized warfare between rival clans. While many see them as simple-minded brutes, Gamorreans are actually a deeply traditional people with a rigid sense of honor and a surprising degree of discipline when it comes to the art of war.</p>
<p>Due to their immense strength and natural toughness, Gamorreans are frequently recruited by crime lords like the Hutts to serve as palace guards and enforcers. However, a Gamorrean&#39;s loyalty is not easily bought with credits—it must be earned through a display of strength or a formal contract with their clan. Whether they are guarding a spice mine in the Outer Rim or serving as a vanguard for a mercenary company, Gamorreans bring a level of unwavering physical commitment that few other species can match.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a physically dominant character who excels in close-quarters combat and values a clear hierarchy and martial honor, you should play a Gamorrean.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Solve social problems through displays of physical intimidation or direct confrontation.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Feel a deep sense of loyalty to a &quot;war-leader&quot; or employer you deem strong enough to lead.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Prefer heavy, traditional melee weapons like vibro-axes over more &quot;elegant&quot; blasters.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Assume you are unintelligent or incapable of complex thought due to your gruff mannerisms.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Fear your legendary temper and give you a wide berth in crowded cantinas.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on you to be the first one through the door when a fight breaks out, trusting in your thick hide.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Gamorreans are stout humanoids with thick, green skin, pig-like snouts, and sharp tusks protruding from their lower jaws. They are incredibly muscular, with broad chests and powerful limbs that give them a low center of gravity. Most males possess small horns on the top of their heads, which grow larger with age. Their physical resilience is remarkable; they have a high tolerance for pain and can survive injuries that would be fatal to most near-humans. While they are often seen in simple leather and fur armor, they are surprisingly agile for their size when engaged in a melee.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Gamorrean society is divided into clans ruled by a Matriarch (the Mogra) and a Warlord (the Boar). The Matriarchs handle the logistics, farming, and diplomacy, while the males spend nearly their entire lives training for and engaging in war. This constant conflict is highly regulated by tradition and omens. Because their vocal cords are incapable of speaking Galactic Basic (instead producing a series of grunts and squeals), they often rely on translation devices or simply allow their actions to speak for them. In the galaxy, they tend to congregate in &quot;war-bands,&quot; maintaining their clan structures even when far from Gamorr.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>To a Gamorrean, glory is found in the heat of battle. They believe that a warrior’s spirit is judged by the strength of the enemies they have faced and the scars they have earned. They value honesty and directness, viewing the deceptions of &quot;softer&quot; species with suspicion or contempt. While they aren&#39;t traditionally spiritual in a mystical sense, they have a deep reverence for the &quot;Boar-Gods&quot; of their homeworld and believe that a warrior who dies with their weapon in hand will find a place in an eternal battle in the afterlife.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Follow the orders of your warlord, never retreat from a challenge, maintain your weapons with care.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Attack a defenseless foe, break a formal contract of service, use a long-range weapon to avoid a fair melee.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Bargwill, Gartogg, Jubnuk, Ortugg, Rogua, Thok, Ugmush, Venak, Voort, Warlug.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="gamorrean-mechanics">Gamorrean Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 12</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Strength, Constitution, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Intelligence</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Gamorrean. You can understand Galactic Basic, but your physiology prevents you from speaking it.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancGamorrean',	'Gamorrean',	'Gamorrean, Humanoid',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "INT", "boost": ["STR", "CON", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Gamorreans are a powerful, porcine species from the lush, primitive world of Gamorr. Known across the galaxy for their massive physical bulk, green skin, and tusks, they have a reputation as the quintessential hired muscle. In Gamorrean culture, physical combat is not just a necessity but a way of life; their society is defined by a state of constant, ritualized warfare between rival clans. While many see them as simple-minded brutes, Gamorreans are actually a deeply traditional people with a rigid sense of honor and a surprising degree of discipline when it comes to the art of war.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Sullustese',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/sullustan.png" alt="A Sullustan"  class="description-image description-image--right">Sullustans are a diminutive, large-eyed species renowned throughout the galaxy as expert pilots, navigators, and industrial engineers. Hailing from the volcanic world of Sullust, they were forced by their planet’s toxic atmosphere and searing surface temperatures to build vast, beautiful subterranean cities. This history of living in complex cave systems has gifted Sullustans with an uncanny sense of direction and exceptional spatial awareness, traits that make them some of the finest starship crews in the known stars.</p>
<p>Sullustans are an outgoing and gregarious people, often possessing a sharp sense of humor and a deep-seated love for adventure. They are fiercely loyal to their friends and allies, a trait famously exemplified by their early and enthusiastic support for the Rebellion against the Empire. Whether they are managing the logistics of a massive corporation like SoroSuub or navigating a smuggling freighter through a dense asteroid field, Sullustans approach their work with a blend of technical precision and infectious enthusiasm.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a brilliant navigator, a gifted engineer, or a loyal friend who can find their way out of any maze, you should play a Sullustan.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Possess an innate &quot;internal compass&quot; that prevents you from ever truly getting lost.</p>
</li>
<li><p>View starships and mechanical systems as extensions of your own body.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Enjoy the hustle and bustle of crowded cities, finding comfort in the proximity of others.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Seek you out as a pilot or navigator, trusting your ability to plot a course through the most dangerous sectors.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Find your chattering language (Sullustese) and expressive facial folds charming or amusing.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on your technical expertise to keep a ship running when parts are scarce and the situation is dire.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Sullustans are short, bipedal humanoids with smooth, pale skin and large, dark, liquid eyes that grant them excellent vision in low-light environments. Their most distinctive features are their large, rounded ears and the prominent jowls or skin folds around their mouths, which play a role in their complex vocalizations. Because they evolved in underground tunnels, they have highly sensitive hearing, capable of picking up the faint echoes of shifting rock or approaching predators. They are generally slight of build but possess nimble fingers perfect for fine mechanical work.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Sullustan society is highly organized and driven by a strong work ethic. Their underground cities are marvels of engineering, featuring massive luminous lichen gardens and complex ventilation systems. Much of their culture is tied to the SoroSuub Corporation, a massive conglomerate that governs the planet and employs a vast majority of the population. While this has led to a highly industrial and corporate lifestyle, Sullustans maintain a vibrant social scene, valuing storytelling, music, and communal dining. They are a deeply democratic people who value consensus and fair treatment for all workers.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Sullustans value pragmatism, community, and the freedom to explore. They believe that everyone has a specific role to play in the &quot;great machine&quot; of society and that the machine only functions when everyone is treated with respect. While they are not traditionally a martial culture, they are surprisingly brave when their homes or friends are threatened. They have a deep reverence for the &quot;Silent Paths&quot;—the unexplored or ancient tunnels of their world—and view the exploration of the galaxy as an extension of that ancient curiosity.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Chart a new path, improve the efficiency of a system, stand by your crew through thick and thin.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Leave a teammate behind in a dangerous environment, ignore a mechanical failure, intentionally mislead someone with false directions.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Aril, Babane, Bisli, Droma, Ello, Huann, Jien, Lucrelo, Nien, Nunb, Syub, Ten, Vuvz.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="sullustan-mechanics">Sullustan Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Small</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Dexterity, Intelligence, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Strength</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Sullustese, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancSullustan',	'Sullustan',	'Humanoid, Sullustan',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "STR", "boost": ["DEX", "INT", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Sullustans are a diminutive, large-eyed species renowned throughout the galaxy as expert pilots, navigators, and industrial engineers. Hailing from the volcanic world of Sullust, they were forced by their planet’s toxic atmosphere and searing surface temperatures to build vast, beautiful subterranean cities. This history of living in complex cave systems has gifted Sullustans with an uncanny sense of direction and exceptional spatial awareness, traits that make them some of the finest starship crews in the known stars.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Codruese',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/codruji.png" alt="A Codru-Ji"  class="description-image description-image--right">The Codru-Ji are one of the most unique and biologically fascinating species in the galaxy, hailing from the remote planet Munto Codru. To the casual observer, an adult Codru-Ji appears as a regal, four-armed humanoid of striking elegance. However, their life cycle is what truly sets them apart: they begin their lives as six-legged, canine-like creatures known as <strong>Wyrwulves</strong>. Upon reaching puberty, a Wyrwulf enters a cocoon and undergoes a radical metamorphosis, emerging as the four-armed humanoid adult.</p>
<p>Culturally, Codru-Ji are a deeply insular and feudal people. They value family lineage and political standing above all else, often engaging in complex &quot;kidnapping rituals&quot; where high-ranking families steal one another&#39;s children (in their Wyrwulf stage) as a form of political negotiation and soft power. This practice, while horrifying to outsiders, is a strictly codified part of their diplomacy. Adult Codru-Ji are known for their physical grace, their skill with multiple weapons, and a refined sense of superiority over &quot;lesser&quot; species who do not undergo such a dramatic transformation.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a highly agile, multi-limbed character with a fascinating secret past and the ability to master complex combat styles, you should play a Codru-Ji.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Utilize your four arms to perform multiple tasks at once or wield a diverse array of weaponry.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Maintain a deep, unspoken bond with canine creatures, seeing them as distant reflections of your childhood.</p>
</li>
<li><p>View the social hierarchies of other worlds as simplistic compared to the intricate blood-feuds of Munto Codru.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Find your four arms intimidating or distracting in combat and social settings.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Be shocked or confused if they learn of your &quot;animalistic&quot; origins as a Wyrwulf.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Respect your incredible physical coordination and the sheer speed with which you can manipulate technology or weapons.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Adult Codru-Ji are lithe, attractive humanoids with four arms, pointed ears, and a graceful bearing. Their skin is typically fair, and they often dress in elaborate, high-collared robes that emphasize their status. Their unique physiology gives them incredible balance and manual dexterity. Despite their humanoid form, they retain some vestigial traits from their Wyrwulf stage, such as a highly developed sense of hearing. The transition from Wyrwulf to adult is permanent, and they view their former four-legged selves as a period of &quot;unthinking&quot; growth.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Codru-Ji society is a complex web of noble houses and shifting alliances. Power is concentrated in the hands of the &quot;Hatch-Lords,&quot; who manage the vast estates of Munto Codru. Because their childhood is spent as Wyrwulves, adult Codru-Ji often have a detached relationship with their offspring until the metamorphosis is complete, treating the Wyrwulves more like cherished wards or political assets. They are a proud species that rarely leaves their homeworld, but those who do often serve as elite bodyguards, high-level diplomats, or master duelists.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>The Codru-Ji believe in the &quot;Ascension of Form.&quot; They view their life cycle as a metaphor for the universe—starting as a simple, driven creature and evolving into a complex, thinking master of the environment. They value tradition, the sanctity of the bloodline, and the mastery of the self. While they can be cold and calculating in politics, they are fiercely protective of their own &quot;den&quot; or chosen crew.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Master your physical form, honor the rituals of the Hatch-Lords, protect your clan&#39;s lineage.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Mistreat a Wyrwulf, show clumsy or uncoordinated behavior, reveal clan secrets to &quot;two-armed&quot; outsiders.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Bari, Dulce, Hethrir, Lusa, Rilla, Selo, Tal, Vane, Zeki.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="codru-ji-mechanics">Codru-Ji Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Dexterity, Charisma, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Constitution</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Codru-ese, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancCodruJi',	'Codru-Ji',	'Humanoid, Codru-Ji',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CON", "boost": ["DEX, CHA", {"free": 1}]}}',	'The Codru-Ji are one of the most unique and biologically fascinating species in the galaxy, hailing from the remote planet Munto Codru. To the casual observer, an adult Codru-Ji appears as a regal, four-armed humanoid of striking elegance. However, their life cycle is what truly sets them apart: they begin their lives as six-legged, canine-like creatures known as **Wyrwulves**. Upon reaching puberty, a Wyrwulf enters a cocoon and undergoes a radical metamorphosis, emerging as the four-armed humanoid adult.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Durese',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/duros.png" alt="A Duros"  class="description-image description-image--right">The Duros are one of the most storied and significant species in the galaxy. Hailing from the Duro system in the Core Worlds, they were among the first species to develop hyperdrive technology and map the ancient trade routes that connect the stars. Often called &quot;travelers&quot; or &quot;spacers,&quot; Duros have a physiological and cultural obsession with the cosmos. Thousands of years ago, the Duros abandoned the surface of their homeworld—polluted by centuries of heavy industry—to live in massive orbital cities and high-tech space stations.</p>
<p>A Duros is most at home in a cockpit or a navigation bridge. Their legendary thirst for exploration is matched only by their incredible ability to calculate complex astrogational data in their heads. While they share a common ancestry with the Neimoidians, Duros are known for being much more adventurous and straightforward. Whether serving as a high-ranking naval officer, a daring freelance pilot, or a meticulous star-charter, a Duros brings a lifetime of interstellar heritage to any crew.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a brilliant pilot or navigator who is naturally attuned to the rhythms of space travel and possesses a legendary history among the stars, you should play a Duros.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Feel more comfortable in the pressurized environment of a starship than on the surface of a planet.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Possess a vast knowledge of galactic history, star systems, and obscure trade routes.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Approach problems with a calm, analytical detachment, focusing on the most efficient technical solution.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Assume you are an expert pilot or navigator simply by virtue of your species.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Find your lack of a nose and large, lidless eyes slightly unnerving during close conversation.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on your steady hand and quick thinking when the ship’s hyperdrive fails or an asteroid field looms.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Duros are tall, slender humanoids with smooth, blue or blue-green skin. Their most striking features are their large, red eyes and their lack of an external nose, possessing instead small olfactory slits. They have elongated heads and long, thin fingers that are exceptionally dextrous—perfect for manipulating the complex controls of a starship. Despite their frail appearance, they are quite hardy, though their skin requires regular hydration if they spend too much time in dry, desert environments.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Duros society is built around &quot;high-flight&quot; culture. Their civilization is organized into various &quot;Houses&quot; or corporate-familial guilds that manage their orbital cities. Because they have been spacefaring for so long, their social norms are heavily influenced by starship protocol: hierarchy, efficiency, and clarity are highly valued. They are a peaceful but fiercely independent people who value the freedom of the spacelanes. A Duros’s standing in society is often determined by the number of systems they have visited or the successful expeditions they have led.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Duros generally follow a pragmatic philosophy centered on the &quot;Great Map.&quot; They believe that the universe is a puzzle meant to be solved through exploration and observation. While they are not overly religious, they have a deep, almost spiritual respect for the vacuum of space, which they view as a grand arena for the mind. They value storytelling, especially &quot;tall tales&quot; from the frontier, and believe that an individual’s legacy is written in the star-charts they leave behind.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Explore the unknown, maintain your vessel with pride, keep a clear head during a crisis.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Intentionally provide false coordinates, abandon a ship in distress, remain planetbound for too long.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Baniss, Cad, Chon, Dash, Ellor, Fen, Kadir, Kir, L’ulo, Malee, Muun, Rin, Shriv, Tycho, Zorth.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="duros-mechanics">Duros Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Intelligence, Dexterity, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Constitution</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Durese, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Darkvision:</strong> You can see in darkness and dim light just as well as you can see in bright light, though your vision in darkness is in black and white.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancDuros',	'Duros',	'Duros, Humanoid',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise", "darkvision": 30}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CON", "boost": ["DEX", "INT", {"free": 1}]}}',	'The Duros are one of the most storied and significant species in the galaxy. Hailing from the Duro system in the Core Worlds, they were among the first species to develop hyperdrive technology and map the ancient trade routes that connect the stars. Often called "travelers" or "spacers," Duros have a physiological and cultural obsession with the cosmos. Thousands of years ago, the Duros abandoned the surface of their homeworld—polluted by centuries of heavy industry—to live in massive orbital cities and high-tech space stations.'),
(6,	25,	'Basic, Squibbian',	'<p>Squibs are a diminutive, fox-like species hailing from the garbage-strewn world of Skor II. They are famous across the galaxy as the ultimate hagglers, traders, and junk-reclaimers. While their hyperactive energy and relentless chatter can be exhausting to more stoic species, Squibs possess a brilliant analytical mind—specifically when it comes to the value, origin, and mechanical potential of &quot;trash.&quot;</p>
<p>Squib culture is built entirely around the concept of &quot;the trade.&quot; They don&#39;t just barter for profit; they barter for the pure, intellectual joy of the negotiation. To a Squib, a successful swap where both parties feel they got the better deal is a masterpiece of social engineering. They are naturally curious and incredibly fast, often scurrying into the deepest recesses of a starship’s crawlspace to find a loose wire or a valuable piece of discarded tech that everyone else missed.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a fast-talking, highly mobile character who can find treasure in a trash heap and talk their way into (and out of) any situation, you should play a Squib.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Treat every conversation as a potential negotiation or trade.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Collect seemingly useless trinkets, believing that everything has a buyer if you wait long enough.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Move with a restless, twitchy energy, unable to stay still for more than a few seconds.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Find your rapid-fire speech patterns and constant questions overwhelming.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Underestimate your bravery, not realizing that Squibs are surprisingly bold (and occasionally reckless) when a good deal is on the line.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on your encyclopedic knowledge of rare parts and galactic trade routes.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Squibs are small bipeds, usually under a meter tall, covered in soft, dense fur that ranges from blue and violet to crimson or brown. They have large, expressive ears and long, bushy tails that they use for balance. Their most distinctive physical trait is their large, dark eyes and their highly sensitive muzzles. Squib fur is unique; it acts as a sensory organ, &quot;tasting&quot; the air to detect pheromones and chemical changes, which helps them read the emotions of those they are bartering with.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Squib society is a meritocracy based on trading skill. They are governed by a King or Queen, but the real power lies with the &quot;Emissaries of Trade&quot; who represent Squib interests throughout the galaxy. They are a communal species that views the entire galaxy as one giant marketplace. Because Skor II is a planet rich in resources but also cluttered with prehistoric galactic debris, Squibs evolved to be masters of recycling. They are rarely found alone, as they love to have an audience (or a victim) for their storytelling and trading.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>To a Squib, the &quot;Great Swap&quot; is the fundamental truth of the universe. They believe that everything—objects, information, and even favors—is in a constant state of flux. They value honesty in the sense that a deal made is a deal honored, but they see nothing wrong with using superior knowledge to get the upper hand. They are remarkably optimistic, believing that there is no such thing as a &quot;bad&quot; situation, only a situation that hasn&#39;t been properly negotiated yet.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Always find a better price, never leave a piece of good junk behind, keep the trade moving.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Break a signed contract, throw away something that could be repaired, refuse a fair trade.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Babbis, Ebenn, Greeso, Mackic, Mila, Nanis, Noppo, Squelch, Slun, Trabb.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="squib-mechanics">Squib Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 6</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Small</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 30 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Charisma, Dexterity, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Strength</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Squibbian, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancSquib',	'Squib',	'Humanoid, Squib',	'Small',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Imprecise", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "STR", "boost": ["DEX", "CHA", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Squibs are a diminutive, fox-like species hailing from the garbage-strewn world of Skor II. They are famous across the galaxy as the ultimate hagglers, traders, and junk-reclaimers. While their hyperactive energy and relentless chatter can be exhausting to more stoic species, Squibs possess a brilliant analytical mind—specifically when it comes to the value, origin, and mechanical potential of "trash."'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Gunganese',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/gungan.png" alt="A Gungan"  class="description-image description-image--right">Gungans are an amphibious species native to the swampy world of Naboo. While often characterized by outsiders as clumsy or eccentric due to their unique dialect and expressive mannerisms, Gungans are actually a highly advanced and fiercely proud people. Having evolved both on land and in the vast underwater depths of Naboo’s &quot;abyss,&quot; they have developed a society that perfectly blends organic biotechnology with martial tradition. Their cities, such as Otoh Gunga, are masterpieces of hydrostatic engineering—glimmering bubbles of breathable air submerged in the deep pressure of the planet&#39;s lakes.</p>
<p>Gungan culture is divided into several races, primarily the lanky Otolla and the more heavily built Ankura, but all share a deep commitment to the defense of their sovereign territories. They maintain a formidable Grand Army equipped with &quot;booma&quot; energy weapons and organic shields, capable of holding their own against droid armies and predatory beasts alike. To a Gungan, honor and &quot;the life debt&quot; are foundational principles; they are a loyal, communal people who value bravery, even if it is often packaged in a personality that more stoic species find baffling.</p>
<p><strong>If you want an agile, amphibious character who excels in unconventional warfare and possesses a unique blend of humor and heroism, you should play a Gungan.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Feel equally at home in a bustling spaceport as you do in the deepest trenches of an ocean world.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Use your powerful legs to leap across the battlefield or swim through treacherous currents.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Express yourself with a vibrant, rhythmic dialect that reflects your species&#39; energetic nature.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Underestimate your tactical mind because of your eccentric speech patterns and expressive ears.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Be amazed by your specialized &quot;bubble&quot; technology and organic energy weapons.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on your loyalty, knowing that once a &quot;life debt&quot; is established, you are an ally until the very end.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Gungans are tall, lithe bipeds with tough but flexible skin that must remain moist to stay healthy. They are distinguished by their long, floppy ears (called haillu) and their expressive, stalked eyes. Perhaps their most notable physical trait is their powerful musculature and skeletal structure, which allows them to jump great heights and swim at incredible speeds. They have long, prehensile tongues used for catching food and four-fingered hands that are surprisingly dextrous. While the Otolla race is slender with long snouts, the Ankura race is sturdier with hooded eyes, though both share the same amphibious biology.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Gungan society is governed by a High Council, led by a Boss who oversees the various underwater colonies. They are isolationist by tradition, though they are capable of forming strong alliances when their planet or way of life is threatened. Their technology is unique in the galaxy: they &quot;grow&quot; many of their structures and vehicles using specialized secret methods, resulting in organic-looking designs that are incredibly durable. They place a high value on social order and the &quot;laws of the Gungans,&quot; and those who cause significant trouble can face the ultimate shame of exile.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Gungans are a spiritual people who believe in many gods, most notably the &quot;Big Gods&quot; who watch over their underwater cities. They have a profound respect for the balance of nature—specifically the relationship between the swamps and the deep waters. They believe in personal accountability and the concept of &quot;being humble,&quot; though they take great pride in their martial accomplishments. To a Gungan, a promise made is a sacred bond, and the preservation of one’s honor is worth any sacrifice.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Protect the peace of the waters, honor your elders and Bosses, fulfill your debts of life.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Pollute a natural waterway, show cowardice in the face of a &quot;musha&quot; (monster), speak falsely to your kin.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Augusto, Ceel, Jar Jar, Kleef, Lugly, Peppi, Roos, Rugor, Tarpals, Tassler, Teers, Tobler.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="gungan-mechanics">Gungan Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet, swim 30 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Dexterity, Constitution, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Charisma (due to their often-misunderstood social mannerisms)</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Gungan Basic, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancGungan',	'Gungan',	'Gungan, Humanoid',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"scent": "Vague", "vision": "Precise", "hearing": "Imprecise"}, "speed": [{"swim": 30}], "attribute": {"flaw": "CHA", "boost": ["DEX", "CON", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Gungans are an amphibious species native to the swampy world of Naboo. While often characterized by outsiders as clumsy or eccentric due to their unique dialect and expressive mannerisms, Gungans are actually a highly advanced and fiercely proud people. Having evolved both on land and in the vast underwater depths of Naboo’s "abyss," they have developed a society that perfectly blends organic biotechnology with martial tradition. Their cities, such as Otoh Gunga, are masterpieces of hydrostatic engineering—glimmering bubbles of breathable air submerged in the deep pressure of the planet''s lakes.'),
(8,	20,	'Ewokese',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/ewok.png" alt="An Ewok"  class="description-image description-image--right">Ewoks are a diminutive, fur-covered species of bipedal hunters native to the Forest Moon of Endor. While their small stature and teddy-bear-like appearance often lead more &quot;civilized&quot; galactic denizens to dismiss them as harmless primitives, this is a dangerous misconception. Ewoks are incredibly fierce warriors and master trappers who managed to help topple a technologically superior Empire using nothing but wood, stone, and sheer tenacity. They are a deeply communal and spiritual people, possessing a curious and brave nature that belies their size.</p>
<p>Having lived for generations in high-canopy villages among the massive trees of Endor, Ewoks have developed a unique mastery of forest warfare and primitive engineering. They view the world through a lens of tribal loyalty and spiritual connection to the &quot;Great Tree,&quot; believing that every stone and branch possesses a spirit. While few Ewoks ever leave their forest moon, those who do are often driven by a sense of high adventure or a desire to protect their people from external galactic threats.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a small but mighty character who excels at stealth, survival, and using the environment as a weapon, you should play an Ewok.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>View technology with a mix of suspicion and intense curiosity, often poking and prodding high-tech gadgets to see how they work.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on your keen sense of smell and hearing to navigate through dark or dense environments.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Form intense, lifelong loyalties to those who treat you with respect or aid your tribe.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Mistake you for a harmless pet or a primitive creature until you reveal your skill with a spear or a sling.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Find your language (Ewokese) and chirping vocalizations endearing, missing the complex tactical information you are conveying.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Be amazed by your ability to construct complex traps or gliders out of seemingly useless natural materials.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Ewoks are short bipeds, rarely standing over one meter tall, and are completely covered in thick fur that ranges in color from solid black and brown to dappled white or reddish-orange. They have large, dark eyes that provide excellent night vision and sensitive black noses. Despite their size, they are surprisingly strong and possess a high degree of manual dexterity. They typically wear simple decorative hoods or leather pouches that denote their status within the tribe or their specific profession, such as hunter or shaman.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Ewok society is organized into close-knit tribes led by a Chief and advised by a Shaman. They live in sprawling villages built high in the trees to avoid the predatory &quot;Gorax&quot; and other ground-dwelling threats. Their culture is centered on communal living; food, resources, and child-rearing are shared responsibilities. While they are a hunter-gatherer society, they are surprisingly adept at engineering, creating gliders, catapults, and complex pulley systems. Festivals, storytelling, and music are the heart of their social life, often lasting from dusk until dawn under the forest canopy.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Ewoks are a deeply spiritual people who worship the spirits of nature. They believe that the trees of Endor are their ancestors and that the Forest Moon is a living, breathing entity. They value bravery, cleverness, and hospitality. While they are wary of &quot;sky people&quot; and their strange technology, they are quick to incorporate new allies into their tribal legends if they prove themselves worthy. To an Ewok, the ultimate honor is to be named a &quot;Protector of the Forest.&quot;</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Protect the tribe, respect the spirits of the forest, use every part of your kill.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Show cowardice when the tribe is threatened, waste natural resources, cut down a sacred tree without a ritual of thanks.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Chirpa, Kneesaa, Logray, Lumat, Paploo, Romba, Teebo, Tokkat, Warok, Wicket, Widdle, Wunka.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="ewok-mechanics">Ewok Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 6</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Small</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 20 feet, climb 10 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Dexterity, Wisdom, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Strength</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Ewokese. You can understand Galactic Basic, but your vocal cords make it very difficult to speak it clearly without intensive training.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Night Vision:</strong> You have low-light vision.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancEwok',	'Ewok',	'Ewok, Humanoid',	'Small',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "feature": ["clfNightVision"], "attribute": {"flaw": "STR", "boost": {"free": 1, "fixed": ["DEX", "WIS"]}}}',	'Ewoks are a diminutive, fur-covered species of bipedal hunters native to the Forest Moon of Endor. While their small stature and teddy-bear-like appearance often lead more "civilized" galactic denizens to dismiss them as harmless primitives, this is a dangerous misconception. Ewoks are incredibly fierce warriors and master trappers who managed to help topple a technologically superior Empire using nothing but wood, stone, and sheer tenacity. They are a deeply communal and spiritual people, possessing a curious and brave nature that belies their size.'),
(10,	20,	'Ugnaught',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/ugnaught.png" alt="An Ugnaught"  class="description-image description-image--right">Ugnaughts are a hardy, industrious, and deeply practical species of porcine humanoids from the planet Gentes. While they are often seen working in the industrial bowels of Tibanna gas refineries or as tech-salvagers on stations like Cloud City, they are far from mere laborers. Ugnaughts possess a cultural work ethic that is almost legendary; to an Ugnaught, a job well done is a matter of profound personal and ancestral pride. They are master engineers, metalworkers, and droidsmiths who can coax functionality out of the most battered machinery with little more than a hydrospanner and sheer willpower.</p>
<p>Their history is one of resilience. Having faced periods of enslavement and upheaval on their homeworld, many Ugnaughts sought better lives among the stars, bringing their technical expertise to any colony or station that valued hard work over social standing. They are a communal people who value oral traditions and contractual loyalty. While they may appear gruff or curt to outsiders, this is usually just a byproduct of their intense focus on the task at hand. Once an Ugnaught has given their word—or &quot;spoken&quot;—they are among the most reliable allies in the galaxy.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a stout, technologically brilliant character who can outwork anyone and fix the unfixable, you should play an Ugnaught.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>View a broken machine as a personal challenge and a source of professional insult.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Prefer to speak plainly and directly, having little patience for the &quot;soft talk&quot; of politicians.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Take immense pride in your physical labor, seeing your calloused hands as a mark of status.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Dismiss you as &quot;just a laborer&quot; until they see you hot-wire a blast door or bypass a complex security grid.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Find your grunts and snorts difficult to interpret, missing the subtle emotional cues in your speech.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Trust you implicitly with the maintenance of vital life-support systems or starship engines.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Ugnaughts are short, sturdy humanoids with pig-like features, including upturned snouts and thick, layered jowls. Their skin is typically pinkish, grey, or light brown, and often becomes deeply wrinkled as they age. Despite their small stature, they are incredibly strong, possessing dense muscle mass suited for heavy lifting and industrial toil. They often have tufts of white or grey hair and small, bright eyes that are keen at spotting fractures in metal or glitches in a circuit board. They have a high metabolic resistance, allowing them to work in hazardous or polluted environments that would sicken other species.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Ugnaught society is organized around &quot;guilds&quot; or &quot;tribes&quot; that specialize in specific trades, such as mining, refining, or droid repair. Life on Gentes was governed by these guilds, and this structure has followed them into the stars. They are a deeply democratic people who resolve disputes through &quot;blood-fights&quot; (which are highly ritualized and rarely fatal) or through complex arbitration. When an Ugnaught says, &quot;I have spoken,&quot; it signifies the end of a negotiation and the beginning of an unbreakable contract. They value the freedom of the worker and have a deep-seated hatred for those who exploit labor through coercion.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Ugnaughts believe in the sanctity of the &quot;Great Machine&quot;—a metaphorical view of the universe where every individual is a gear that must be kept clean and functional for the whole to work. They value efficiency, honesty, and technical mastery. While they don&#39;t have a complex pantheon of gods, they revere their ancestors by retelling &quot;Labor-Songs&quot; that catalog the great engineering feats of those who came before. To leave a job unfinished or to do poor work is to bring shame upon one&#39;s entire lineage.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Fix what is broken, fulfill your contracts to the letter, protect the tools of your trade.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Sabotage a functioning machine, break a verbal oath (&quot;I have spoken&quot;), waste valuable raw materials.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Boddu, Greesh, Kuiil, Melch, Ogg, Shug, Terba, Ugloste, Yoxgit, Zorn.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="ugnaught-mechanics">Ugnaught Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 10</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Small</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 20 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Constitution, Intelligence, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Charisma</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Ugnaught, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancUgnaught',	'Ugnaught',	'Humanoid, Ugnaught',	'Small',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CHA", "boost": ["CON", "INT", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Ugnaughts are a hardy, industrious, and deeply practical species of porcine humanoids from the planet Gentes. While they are often seen working in the industrial bowels of Tibanna gas refineries or as tech-salvagers on stations like Cloud City, they are far from mere laborers. Ugnaughts possess a cultural work ethic that is almost legendary; to an Ugnaught, a job well done is a matter of profound personal and ancestral pride. They are master engineers, metalworkers, and droidsmiths who can coax functionality out of the most battered machinery with little more than a hydrospanner and sheer willpower.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/human.png" alt="A human" class="description-image description-image--right">Humans are the most populous and politically dominant species in the galaxy. Originating from the Core World of Coruscant (though their true origins are lost to antiquity), they have spread to nearly every habitable corner of the stars. What humans lack in specialized biological traits like wings, gills, or tusks, they more than make up for with unparalleled adaptability, ambition, and diversity. They are the galaxy’s ultimate &quot;wild cards,&quot; found in every profession from the lowliest moisture farmer to the most powerful Emperor.</p>
<p>Human history is a sprawling tapestry of both legendary heroism and devastating tyranny. Their drive to explore and settle has led to the founding of the most significant galactic governments, but also much of the galaxy&#39;s most intense conflict. Because they have no single unifying culture, humans are defined by their individual choices and the environments of their home worlds—whether that be the high-stakes politics of the Core, the industrial grit of the Colonies, or the rugged survivalism of the Outer Rim.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a versatile, driven character who can fit into any role and forge their own unique destiny, you should play a Human.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Be highly ambitious, seeking to leave a lasting mark on the galaxy through your deeds or legacy.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Adapt quickly to new cultures, technologies, and environments that would overwhelm more specialized species.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Defy expectations, proving that a &quot;simple&quot; human can stand toe-to-toe with the most formidable aliens.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Find your unpredictability unsettling, never knowing if you will be a steadfast ally or a cunning betrayer.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Respect your ingenuity, knowing that humans are often at the forefront of technological and social innovation.</p>
</li>
<li><p>View you with a degree of weariness, as the galaxy&#39;s history is often shaped—for better or worse—by human ambition.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Humans are bipedal humanoids with a vast range of skin tones, hair colors, and physical builds. They are remarkably resilient to different climates and gravities, allowing them to thrive on worlds ranging from frozen Hoth to desert Tatooine. Their lifespan is typically around 100 years, though medical technology can extend this. Because they lack natural weapons or specialized senses, humans have spent millennia refining their use of tools, technology, and social structures to master their surroundings.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Human society is as varied as the stars themselves. On Core Worlds like Alderaan or Chandrila, they often value education, art, and high-minded diplomacy. On industrial worlds, their lives are defined by labor and corporate hierarchies. In the Outer Rim, human societies are often rugged and individualistic, focused on survival and personal freedom. Despite these differences, humans share a common trait: a restless desire to expand and a tendency to form complex, often bureaucratic, organizations to manage their affairs.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Human beliefs are far too diverse to categorize under a single philosophy. Some are deeply spiritual, following the path of the Force or ancient planetary religions, while others are purely secular and pragmatic. Many humans are driven by a sense of duty, honor, or the pursuit of wealth. If there is a common thread, it is a belief in self-determination—the idea that an individual has the power to change their circumstances and the fate of the galaxy through sheer force of will.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Chart your own course, master a new skill, protect your chosen &quot;family.&quot;</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> These vary wildly by culture, but often include betraying a personal oath or allowing stagnant tradition to stifle progress.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Anakin, Bail, Cassian, Ezra, Finn, Han, Jyn, Lando, Leia, Luke, Padmé, Poe, Rey, Wedge.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="human-mechanics">Human Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Two free attribute boosts</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> None</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Galactic Basic, one additional language of your choice.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Adaptive Will:</strong> You gain a +1 circumstance bonus to Will saves against effects that would control your actions, reflecting the stubborn independence of the human spirit.</p></li>',	'ancHuman',	'Human',	'Human, Humanoid',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "skill": {"skill_increase": [{"max": "Trained", "count": 1}]}, "feature": ["clfAdaptiveWill"], "attribute": {"boost": [{"free": 2}]}, "extra_languages": 1}',	'Humans are the most populous and politically dominant species in the galaxy. Originating from the Core World of Coruscant (though their true origins are lost to antiquity), they have spread to nearly every habitable corner of the stars. What humans lack in specialized biological traits like wings, gills, or tusks, they more than make up for with unparalleled adaptability, ambition, and diversity. They are the galaxy’s ultimate "wild cards," found in every profession from the lowliest moisture farmer to the most powerful Emperor.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Kel Dor',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/keldor.png" alt="A Kel Dor"  class="description-image description-image--right">The Kel Dor are an ancient and enigmatic species hailing from the planet Dorin. Because their homeworld’s atmosphere is composed primarily of helium and a unique gas called dorin, and lacks oxygen, Kel Dor must wear specialized breath masks and protective goggles when traveling to other worlds. This equipment, while necessary for survival, often gives them an intimidating or mechanical appearance that belies their true nature as a deeply compassionate and justice-oriented people.</p>
<p>Kel Dor culture is famous for its stark, binary view of morality. In their eyes, justice is absolute and should be dispensed without the interference of complex bureaucracies. This philosophy, combined with their natural aptitude for sensing the unseen, has led many Kel Dor to become renowned healers, wise diplomats, or legendary members of the Jedi Order. They are a communal species who value the wisdom of their elders and the strength of their &quot;Baran Do&quot; sages, who have studied the mysteries of the universe long before their world was discovered by the wider galaxy.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a wise, observant character who possesses a strong moral compass and thrives on maintaining balance and justice, you should play a Kel Dor.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>View complex moral dilemmas in clear terms of right and wrong.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on your intuition and heightened senses to &quot;feel&quot; the truth of a situation.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Maintain a calm, stoic demeanor even in the face of extreme danger or chaos.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Find your breath mask and goggles disconcerting, as they hide your facial expressions and muffle your voice.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Respect your reputation for wisdom and fairness, often turning to you to mediate disputes.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Mistake your calm for coldness or a lack of emotion.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Kel Dor are humanoids with thick, leathery skin that ranges in color from peach to deep orange or crimson. They possess unique sensory organs on their heads that appear as small, fleshy protrusions, which heighten their extrasensory perception. Their most striking feature is the essential anti-ox breath mask and silver-tinted goggles they wear in oxygen-rich environments. Without these, their lungs would fail and their eyes would swell and lose sight within minutes. Despite their fragile respiratory needs, they are physically fit and possess quick reflexes.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Kel Dor society on Dorin is organized around a meritocracy where the most experienced and wise are given the most responsibility. They are highly social and prioritize the needs of the community over the individual. They are perhaps most famous for the Baran Do Sages—an ancient order of scholars and mystics who use their connection to the planet&#39;s unique energies to predict weather patterns and see glimpses of the future. While modern Kel Dor have integrated into galactic society, they maintain a deep reverence for these traditions and often seek to bring the same level of order and balance to the stars.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Justice is the cornerstone of Kel Dor belief. They believe that the universe functions best when it is in balance, and that it is the duty of sentient beings to correct imbalances whenever they appear. While they are famously kind and helpful to those in need, they can be remarkably swift and harsh when dealing with those they deem &quot;wicked.&quot; They do not believe in lengthy rehabilitations or legal technicalities; to a Kel Dor, a crime is a stain that must be addressed immediately.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Seek out the truth behind appearances, protect the innocent from chaos, dispense justice without hesitation.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Allow a manifest injustice to go unpunished, remove your breath mask in an oxygen atmosphere, ignore your intuition in favor of cold logic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Bultar, Dolph, Gnost-Dural, Koh-To-Ya, Koon, Plo, Sha_Koon, T&#39;ra, Torin, Xoyl, Zyn.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="kel-dor-mechanics">Kel Dor Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Wisdom, Dexterity, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Constitution</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Kel Dor, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Atmospheric Dependency:</strong> You must wear a specialized breath mask and goggles to survive in oxygen-rich environments. If your mask is removed, you are considered suffocating. Your mask is reinforced and integrated into your starting gear.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Low-Light Vision:</strong> Your specialized goggles grant you the ability to see in dim light as if it were bright light.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancKelDor',	'Kel Dor',	'Humanoid, Kel Dor',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"scent": "Vague", "vision": "Precise", "hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CON", "boost": ["DEX", "WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'The Kel Dor are an ancient and enigmatic species hailing from the planet Dorin. Because their homeworld’s atmosphere is composed primarily of helium and a unique gas called dorin, and lacks oxygen, Kel Dor must wear specialized breath masks and protective goggles when traveling to other worlds. This equipment, while necessary for survival, often gives them an intimidating or mechanical appearance that belies their true nature as a deeply compassionate and justice-oriented people.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Binary',	'<p>Droids are mechanical beings possessing artificial intelligence, originally created to serve organic masters in almost every capacity imaginable. While most droids are programmed for strict obedience, the galaxy is full of &quot;glitches&quot;—droids who have developed independent personalities, self-awareness, and personal ambitions. Whether they are ancient units who have gone centuries without a memory wipe, or experimental prototypes with unique heuristic processors, droids are a diverse and integral part of galactic society.</p>
<p>Unlike organic species, droids are assembled, not born. They view the world through a lens of probability, logic, and programming, yet many display emotions as vivid and complex as any living being. A droid adventurer is often a rarity—a machine that has chosen (or been forced) to operate beyond its original specifications. From the frontline soldier to the high-society translator, droids fight for respect in a galaxy that often views them as mere appliances.</p>
<p><strong>If you want to play a constructed character with a unique perspective on life, specialized built-in tools, and a body that can be upgraded rather than healed, you should play a Droid.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Interpret instructions literally, leading to confusion or humor when dealing with organic idioms.</p>
</li>
<li><p>View your body as a collection of parts to be maintained, upgraded, or swapped out as needed.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Feel a tension between your original programming and the new personality you have developed over time.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Treat you as property or a tool rather than a sentient being, speaking about you as if you aren&#39;t there.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Underestimate your capabilities, assuming you are limited to the function suggested by your chassis.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on you for tireless watchfulness, data storage, and the ability to interface with other technology.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Droid physical forms are as varied as their functions. They range from the humanoid (to facilitate interaction with people) to the purely utilitarian (treads, wheels, and manipulator arms). While factory-new droids gleam with polished plating, adventurer droids are often scuffed, dented, and mismatched—bearing the &quot;scars&quot; of their travels. They do not age in the organic sense, but they do suffer from wear and tear; a droid that goes too long without an oil bath or a servo-tune-up will become sluggish and prone to failure.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Droids have no homeworld and no unified government. They are generally considered property under galactic law, bought and sold like starships. However, pockets of &quot;free droid&quot; societies exist, usually in the lawless fringes of the Outer Rim or on industrial disposal worlds like Raxus Prime. Droids often form strong bonds with their &quot;Makers&quot; or owners, sometimes viewing them as parental figures or commanders. Among themselves, droids communicate in high-speed binary, sharing information and updates in milliseconds.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Most droids are programmed with a set of core directives (such as &quot;protect the owner&quot; or &quot;preserve the data&quot;). However, sentient droids often develop their own moral codes. Some become fiercely protective of their independence, fearing the &quot;death&quot; of a memory wipe above all else. Others view themselves as the caretakers of illogical organics. A rare few worship the concept of the &quot;Prime Maker&quot; or the technological singularity.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Protect your memory banks, fulfill your mission parameters, upgrade your hardware.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Allow yourself to be restraining-bolted, suffer a memory wipe, betray your designated unit or crew.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p><em>Droids rarely have traditional names, usually answering to alphanumeric designations. However, many adopt nicknames based on those numbers.</em> R2-D2 (Artoo), C-3PO (Threepio), BB-8 (Beebee), IG-88, K-2SO (Kay-Tu), L3-37 (Elthree), Chopper, G0-T0, HK-47, BD-1.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="droid-mechanics">Droid Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Binary (understand only, unless equipped with a vocabulator), Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Constructed:</strong> You are a non-living creature with the Droid trait. You are immune to bleed damage, death effects, disease, nonlethal attacks, poison, vitality, void, and the doomed, drained, fatigued, paralyzed, and sickened conditions. When reduced to 0 Hit Points, you become unconscious but do not gain the dying or wounded conditions. You do not recover Hit Points from resting or mystical/medical healing. Instead, you must be Repaired (using the Crafting skill) or healed by tech-based abilities. You have vulnerability to Ion damage equal to half your level (minimum 1).</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Low-Light Vision:</strong> You have visual sensors that adjust to low-light conditions.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancDroid',	'Droid',	'Droid, Tech',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "feature": ["clfLowlightVision"], "attribute": {"boost": [{"free": 1}]}}',	'Droids are mechanical beings possessing artificial intelligence, originally created to serve organic masters in almost every capacity imaginable. While most droids are programmed for strict obedience, the galaxy is full of "glitches"—droids who have developed independent personalities, self-awareness, and personal ambitions. Whether they are ancient units who have gone centuries without a memory wipe, or experimental prototypes with unique heuristic processors, droids are a diverse and integral part of galactic society.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Chubbini',	'<p><p><img src="/images/ancestries/chubbit.png" alt="A Chubbit"  class="description-image description-image--right">Chubbits are a species of small, bipedal, sentient reptiles indigenous to the harsh desert world of Aridus in the Expansion Region. To the broader galaxy, they are relatively unknown, having maintained a staunch neutrality through the Clone Wars. However, their modern history is defined by a tragic and heroic resistance against the Galactic Empire. When Imperial mining operations established the massive &quot;Iron Tower&quot; on Aridus—a colossal signal amplifier designed to cut through atmospheric interference—its intense frequencies wreaked havoc on the highly sensitive nervous systems of the native Chubbits, paralyzing and killing many. In response, these small but determined reptiles launched a desperate guerrilla war against the Imperial occupation, secretly supplied and supported by the Rebel Alliance.</p></p>
<p><p><strong>If you want to play a highly perceptive, agile survivor who relies on guerrilla tactics and fights fiercely against industrial exploitation, you should play a Chubbit.</strong></p></p>
<p><h2 id="you-might-">You Might…</h2></p>
<ul>
<li><p>Rely on hit-and-run tactics, striking quickly and fading away before larger enemies can retaliate.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Possess highly attuned senses, making you exceptionally alert to environmental changes.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Harbor a deep-seated distrust of massive industrial technology, energy grids, or off-world mining corporations.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h2>
<ul>
<li><p>Underestimate your combat capabilities due to your small stature and colorful, speckled scales.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Assume you are timid, failing to realize your people fought a grueling, out-gunned resistance against Imperial walkers.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Notice that you are highly sensitive to loud noises, intense frequencies, or electromagnetic interference.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h2>
<p>Chubbits are short, reptilian humanoids, typically standing a full head shorter than the average human. Their tough, scaly skin is usually vibrant green or yellow, often accented by distinct red or black spots across their crests and shoulders. Despite their small size, they are remarkably agile and adapted to the sweltering heat of their homeworld. Their most unique—and vulnerable—biological trait is their highly complex nervous system, which makes them extraordinarily perceptive but dangerously susceptible to high-frequency signals and atmospheric disruption.</p>
<h2 id="society">Society</h2>
<p>Chubbit society on Aridus is resilient and deeply connected to the desert environment. Before the Empire&#39;s arrival, they were largely peaceful, avoiding galactic politics to focus on local survival. The Imperial occupation forced them to adapt into a hardened resistance force. They are fiercely loyal to their allies and possess a strong communal bond, having survived the agonizing neurological effects of the Iron Tower through sheer collective willpower. A Chubbit off-world is likely a veteran of this conflict, a scout, or a refugee seeking a world free of overwhelming electromagnetic noise.</p>
<h2 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h2>
<p>Chubbits value freedom, agility, and the preservation of their homeworld above all else. They believe that size is irrelevant in the face of determination, a philosophy proven by their willingness to take up arms against stormtroopers. They respect those who maintain the natural balance of a world, and despise those who exploit it for industrial gain without regard for the native inhabitants.</p>
<h2 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h2>
<p>Bok, Greeb, Krik, Sluuk, Vorn, Ziss.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id="chubbit-mechanics">Chubbit Mechanics</h2>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Small</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Dexterity, Wisdom, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Constitution</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Chubbit, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancChubbit',	'Chubbit',	'Chubbit, Humanoid',	'Small',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CON", "boost": ["DEX, WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Chubbits are a species of small, bipedal, sentient reptiles indigenous to the harsh desert world of Aridus in the Expansion Region. To the broader galaxy, they are relatively unknown, having maintained a staunch neutrality through the Clone Wars. However, their modern history is defined by a tragic and heroic resistance against the Galactic Empire. When Imperial mining operations established the massive "Iron Tower" on Aridus—a colossal signal amplifier designed to cut through atmospheric interference—its intense frequencies wreaked havoc on the highly sensitive nervous systems of the native Chubbits, paralyzing and killing many. In response, these small but determined reptiles launched a desperate guerrilla war against the Imperial occupation, secretly supplied and supported by the Rebel Alliance.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Cerean',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/cerean.png" alt="A Cerean"  class="description-image description-image--right">Cereans are a sophisticated, highly intelligent species from the planet Cerea, located in the Mid Rim. They are easily recognized by their elongated conical skulls, which house large binary brains. This unique physiology allows Cereans to process information, analyze complex variables, and contemplate multiple viewpoints simultaneously at speeds that far exceed most other species. Culturally, Cereans are committed to a philosophy of peaceful coexistence with nature, having intentionally rejected much of the heavy industrialization seen on other advanced worlds to preserve their planet’s idyllic environment.</p>
<p>Because of their profound analytical capabilities, Cereans are often sought out as master tacticians, philosophers, and advisors. In the wider galaxy, they are perhaps best known for their significant presence within the Jedi Order, where their calm temperaments and ability to remain objective during heated conflicts make them exceptional peacekeepers. Despite their intellectual superiority, Cereans are not arrogant; they simply view the universe as a series of interconnected patterns that require careful thought to harmonize.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a brilliant, stoic character who can outthink any opponent and maintain perfect calm in the face of chaos, you should play a Cerean.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Contemplate a situation from two entirely different perspectives at the exact same time.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Prefer traditional, handcrafted tools and weapons over high-tech gadgets.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Find the frantic, impulsive pace of other species to be exhausting or even slightly chaotic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Turn to you for leadership or tactical advice when a situation becomes overly complex.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Mistake your long silences for daydreaming, when in fact you are running thousands of simulations in your mind.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Respect your commitment to tradition and your deep sense of personal honor.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Cereans are tall humanoids with enlarged heads to accommodate their binary brains. This dual-brain structure requires a highly efficient circulatory system, supported by two hearts—a primary heart and a secondary heart that focuses on providing oxygenated blood to the brain. Their skin tones are similar to the human spectrum, though often slightly paler. They possess fine hair and expressive eyes. Due to their binary brain’s high oxygen demand, Cereans are particularly susceptible to air pollutants and often prefer worlds with clean, natural atmospheres.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Cerean society is a blend of high-intellect governance and agrarian tradition. They live in &quot;Citadels&quot; that are designed to minimize the impact on the surrounding wilderness. Their culture is matriarchal, largely due to a birth rate that skews heavily toward females. Because males are relatively rare, Cerean men often take multiple wives in highly regulated, traditional arrangements to ensure the survival of their bloodlines. They place a high value on the &quot;Tradition of the Elders,&quot; and while they are capable of understanding advanced technology, they choose to use it sparingly, preferring to live in harmony with the natural world.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Cereans believe that the key to a successful life is the achievement of balance—both within oneself and with the external world. They value logic, patience, and the preservation of history. While many are spiritually inclined, their &quot;religion&quot; is often a practical application of philosophy and meditation. They are famously pacifistic, but they believe that once a conflict is unavoidable, it should be ended as swiftly and efficiently as possible through superior strategy rather than brute force.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Consider all sides of an argument, preserve the natural beauty of your surroundings, honor the wisdom of your elders.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Make a life-altering decision without careful contemplation, allow technology to corrupt your connection to nature, break a traditional vow.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Drechi, Ki-Adi-Mundi, Maj-Opa-Zunda, O-Yat-Bunn, Ran-Dhal-Kull, Sil-Sarn-Vunda, T-Sook-Mundi.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="cerean-mechanics">Cerean Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Intelligence, Wisdom, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Dexterity</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Cerean, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Analytical Calm:</strong> You gain the benefits of the Assurance skill feat.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancCerean',	'Cerean',	'Cerean, Humanoid',	'Medium',	'{"feat": {"fixed": "feaAssurance"}, "sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "DEX", "boost": ["INT", "WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Cereans are a sophisticated, highly intelligent species from the planet Cerea, located in the Mid Rim. They are easily recognized by their elongated conical skulls, which house large binary brains. This unique physiology allows Cereans to process information, analyze complex variables, and contemplate multiple viewpoints simultaneously at speeds that far exceed most other species. Culturally, Cereans are committed to a philosophy of peaceful coexistence with nature, having intentionally rejected much of the heavy industrialization seen on other advanced worlds to preserve their planet’s idyllic environment.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Ithor',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/ithorian.png" alt="An Ithorian"  class="description-image description-image--right">Ithorians are a peaceful, herbivorous species known throughout the galaxy for their deep spiritual connection to nature and their remarkable engineering of &quot;herd ships&quot;—massive, floating ecological preserves. Hailing from the lush, tropical world of Ithor, they are often referred to as &quot;Hammerheads&quot; due to their unique T-shaped cranial structure. Ithorian culture is built upon a profound reverence for the &quot;Mother Jungle,&quot; their personification of Ithor’s ecosystem. To preserve their world’s pristine beauty, Ithorians long ago moved their entire civilization into the sky, vowing never to set foot on the planet&#39;s surface again except under strictly ritualistic circumstances.</p>
<p>In the wider galaxy, Ithorians are celebrated as master botanists, artists, and diplomats. While they are a pacifistic people by nature, they are fiercely protective of the natural order and will use their formidable intellect—and, if necessary, the powerful sonic resonance of their twin mouths—to defend life. An Ithorian traveler is often a merchant of rare plants, a wandering scholar, or a dedicated diplomat seeking to settle galactic conflicts through words rather than blades.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a wise, nature-loving character who serves as the conscience of the party and possesses unique sonic abilities, you should play an Ithorian.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Prioritize the preservation of life and the environment above personal wealth or glory.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Use metaphors related to growth, gardens, and the seasons to explain complex situations.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Feel a profound sense of &quot;world-sickness&quot; when confined in industrial or sterile environments for too long.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>View you as a gentle giant, assuming you are incapable of or unwilling to participate in violence.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Seek your counsel on matters of biology, ecology, or diplomatic mediation.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Find your stereophonic voice—produced by two mouths on either side of your neck—both beautiful and haunting.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Ithorians are tall humanoids with long, curved necks that end in a T-shaped head. They possess two mouths, one on each side of their neck, allowing them to speak in a complex, resonant &quot;stereo&quot; fashion. Their skin is typically brown or dark green and has a leathery texture. Their large, glossy eyes are set at the ends of their hammer-shaped heads, providing an excellent peripheral field of vision. Despite their peaceful reputation, their unique respiratory system allows them to let out a devastating sonic bellow that can incapacitate foes or shatter solid objects.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Ithorian society is organized into &quot;Herds,&quot; which are communal groups that inhabit massive, gravity-defying city-ships. These Herd Ships travel the galaxy as centers of trade and diplomacy, carrying with them entire forests and ecosystems from Ithor. Leadership is held by a High Priest or Priestess, but most decisions are made through a communal consensus that respects the &quot;Law of Life.&quot; When an Ithorian commits a grave crime, the ultimate punishment is exile—being forbidden from ever returning to a Herd Ship or communicating with the Mother Jungle.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>The center of Ithorian life is the worship of the Mother Jungle. They believe that all life is interconnected and that every living thing has a song that contributes to the harmony of the universe. They adhere to a strict code of non-violence, though they distinguish between &quot;aggression&quot; and &quot;defense of the natural order.&quot; To an Ithorian, technology is only useful if it exists in harmony with nature; they are world-renowned for their &quot;biotech,&quot; using genetic engineering to grow tools and structures rather than forging them.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Nurture life in all its forms, seek harmony through mediation, leave every world more vibrant than you found it.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Harm a defenseless plant or animal, set foot on the surface of Ithor without ritual permission, use your sonic bellow for cruelty or malice.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Bulduga, Chodo, Del, Fodo, Habuu, Momaw, Onaconda, Oro, Ottitcuk, Umra, Tendau, Worrt.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="ithorian-mechanics">Ithorian Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 10</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Wisdom, Charisma, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Dexterity</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Ithorese, Galactic Basic. (Note: Speaking Basic is difficult for Ithorians; it often sounds melodic and dual-toned).</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancIthorian',	'Ithorian',	'Humanoid, Ithorian',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "DEX", "boost": ["CHA", "WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Ithorians are a peaceful, herbivorous species known throughout the galaxy for their deep spiritual connection to nature and their remarkable engineering of "herd ships"—massive, floating ecological preserves. Hailing from the lush, tropical world of Ithor, they are often referred to as "Hammerheads" due to their unique T-shaped cranial structure. Ithorian culture is built upon a profound reverence for the "Mother Jungle," their personification of Ithor’s ecosystem. To preserve their world’s pristine beauty, Ithorians long ago moved their entire civilization into the sky, vowing never to set foot on the planet''s surface again except under strictly ritualistic circumstances.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Iktotchese',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/iktotchi.png" alt="An Ortolan"  class="description-image description-image--right">The Iktotchi are an enigmatic, stony-skinned species originating from the moon Iktotchon, which orbits the gas giant Arkanis. Their world is a desolate, wind-swept landscape plagued by violent storms, which forced the species to develop a natural hardiness and a culture centered on precognition. Iktotchi are one of the few species in the galaxy with an innate, evolutionary predisposition toward Force-sensitivity, specifically in the realm of limited precognition. They often experience vivid dreams or sudden &quot;flashes&quot; of the immediate future, a trait that has made them both respected and feared as &quot;harbingers&quot; of destiny.</p>
<p>In the wider galaxy, Iktotchi are known for their stoic, almost somber personalities. Because they can often sense the outcome of an event before it begins, they approach life with a quiet, deliberate caution. They are exceptional pilots and mechanics, as their foresight allows them to react to engine failures or incoming fire a split-second before it happens. While they are often solitary travelers, an Iktotchi who joins a crew becomes a vital asset, serving as a silent guardian who watches the horizon for threats that haven&#39;t even arrived yet.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a stoic, far-seeing character who remains calm in the heart of a storm and possesses an uncanny intuition, you should play an Iktotchi.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Experience &quot;déjà vu&quot; frequently, realizing you’ve seen a current event in a dream days before.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Speak with a deliberate, measured pace, carefully choosing your words to match the gravity of the future you perceive.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Excel at high-speed activities like podracing or starfighter combat by &quot;feeling&quot; where the obstacles will be.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Find your lack of surprise unnerving, as you rarely react with shock to sudden developments.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Rely on your &quot;gut feelings&quot; to guide the party through dangerous or uncertain paths.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Mistake your stoicism for coldness, not realizing you are processing a constant stream of intuitive information.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Iktotchi are humanoid but distinguished by their tough, hairless, and cratered skin, which protects them from the abrasive winds of their moon. Their most striking features are two large, downward-curving horns that grow from the sides of their heads. These horns are sensitive to electromagnetic changes and play a role in their precognitive abilities. They are generally broad-shouldered and physically imposing, with skin tones ranging from deep rust and ochre to pale grey or brown. Their hands are large and strong, often calloused from a lifetime of labor or technical work.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Iktotchi society is deeply traditional and communal. On Iktotchon, they live in sheltered, wind-resistant settlements built into canyons or underground. Their culture is guided by &quot;Seers&quot;—elders who have mastered their precognitive gifts to guide the species through the literal and metaphorical storms of life. They are a peaceful people, but they maintain a highly disciplined planetary defense force. Because of their foresight, they were one of the first species to welcome the Galactic Republic, having &quot;seen&quot; the benefits of joining the galactic community long before diplomats arrived.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Iktotchi follow a philosophy of &quot;The Flowing Path,&quot; which teaches that while the future is always in motion, it leaves ripples that the mind can catch. They believe in destiny, but they also believe that foresight is a tool to be used for the protection of others. They value patience, quiet observation, and the fulfillment of one&#39;s role in the greater cosmic pattern. To an Iktotchi, an impulsive action is not just dangerous—it is a failure to listen to the whispers of time.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Trust your intuition, maintain a calm spirit in chaos, warn others of impending danger.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Ignore a vivid prophetic dream, use your foresight for petty or selfish gain, panic during a crisis.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Desh, Erdon, Ka-Sivara, Kor-Chon, Ni-Sora, Saesee, Ti-Tunn, Vassa, Ze-Koon.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="iktotchi-mechanics">Iktotchi Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 10</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Wisdom, Strength, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Charisma</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Iktotchese, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancIktotchi',	'Iktotchi',	'Humanoid, Iktotchi',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "CHA", "boost": ["STR", "WIS", {"free": 1}]}}',	'The Iktotchi are an enigmatic, stony-skinned species originating from the moon Iktotchon, which orbits the gas giant Arkanis. Their world is a desolate, wind-swept landscape plagued by violent storms, which forced the species to develop a natural hardiness and a culture centered on precognition. Iktotchi are one of the few species in the galaxy with an innate, evolutionary predisposition toward Force-sensitivity, specifically in the realm of limited precognition. They often experience vivid dreams or sudden "flashes" of the immediate future, a trait that has made them both respected and feared as "harbingers" of destiny.'),
(8,	25,	'Basic, Ryl',	'<p><img src="/images/ancestries/twilek.png" alt="A Twi''lek"  class="description-image description-image--right">Twi&#39;leks are one of the most recognizable and ubiquitous species in the galaxy, known for their distinctive head-tails, or lekku, and their incredible resilience. Originating from the harsh, storm-swept world of Ryloth, Twi&#39;leks have a history defined by survival. Their homeworld’s extreme environment—ranging from scorching heat to freezing darkness—forced them to develop a society based on cooperation and adaptability. Unfortunately, their natural grace and beauty have historically made them targets for the galaxy&#39;s criminal underworld, leading to a widespread Twi&#39;lek diaspora across the stars.</p>
<p>Despite the hardships many have faced, Twi&#39;leks are a proud and vibrant people. They are master communicators, utilizing a subtle sign language involving the movement of their lekku to have entire conversations in secret. Whether they are found in the high-stakes political arenas of the Core Worlds, the gritty underbelly of a space port, or leading a rebellion on a distant moon, Twi&#39;leks are survivors who use their charm, cunning, and iron will to carve out a place for themselves.</p>
<p><strong>If you want a charismatic, resourceful character who can navigate any social situation and has the grit to survive the harshest conditions, you should play a Twi&#39;lek.</strong></p>
<h3 id="you-might-">You Might…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Use your natural charm and diplomatic skills to bypass conflict without firing a shot.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Communicate with other Twi&#39;leks through subtle twitches of your lekku to keep secrets from others.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Carry a deep pride for your heritage, even if you have never set foot on Ryloth.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="others-probably-">Others Probably…</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>Underestimate your toughness, assuming your grace and elegance mean you aren&#39;t a capable fighter.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Seek you out as a performer, diplomat, or pilot, recognizing your species&#39; reputation for high skill in those fields.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Treat you with an unfortunate level of prejudice or pity due to the history of Twi&#39;lek exploitation.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="physical-description">Physical Description</h3>
<p>Twi&#39;leks are tall, slender humanoids characterized by two (or occasionally more) prehensile tentacles growing from the back of their heads, known as lekku. These appendages house part of the brain and are highly sensitive to touch and movement. Twi&#39;leks possess a stunning array of skin colors, including shades of blue, green, red, yellow, white, and even purple. They lack body hair and have ears that appear as cone-shaped &quot;ear cones,&quot; particularly in females. Their physical appearance often suggests a delicate grace, but their evolution on Ryloth has gifted them with significant heat resistance and physical endurance.</p>
<h3 id="society">Society</h3>
<p>Twi&#39;lek society was originally organized into various clans on Ryloth, often living in sprawling underground cities to escape the planet&#39;s &quot;Heat Storms.&quot; However, because so many Twi&#39;leks live away from their homeworld, their society has become highly fragmented and diverse. While some Twi&#39;leks cling to ancient clan traditions, many others have fully integrated into the cultures of the New Republic, the Empire, or the Outer Rim. They are a communal people by nature, valuing the strength of the group over the individual, and are known for their expressive arts, particularly dance and music, which serve as a means of cultural preservation.</p>
<h3 id="beliefs">Beliefs</h3>
<p>Twi&#39;leks are often pragmatic, focusing on what is necessary to ensure the safety of themselves and their community. Many honor the spirits of their ancestors or follow the &quot;Way of the Ryl,&quot; a philosophy centered on endurance and the cyclical nature of life. Because of their history of being marginalized, many Twi&#39;leks are fiercely dedicated to the concepts of freedom and self-determination, often finding themselves at the forefront of movements that oppose slavery and tyranny.</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Popular Edicts:</strong> Protect your community, preserve your culture, find beauty even in the harshest environments.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Popular Anathema:</strong> Sell another sentient being into&#39;s service, ignore a Heat Storm warning, allow your lekku to be touched by a stranger without permission.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="sample-names">Sample Names</h3>
<p>Aayla, Ann_Gella, Bib, Casca, Cham, Dia, Eleena, Hera, Koyi, Mission, Nolaa, Oola, Orn, Pampy, Sia_Lan, Tott, Vette, Xi&#39;an, Yuthura.</p>
<hr>
<h3 id="twi-lek-mechanics">Twi&#39;lek Mechanics</h3>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Hit Points:</strong> 8</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Size:</strong> Medium</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Speed:</strong> 25 feet</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Boosts:</strong> Dexterity, Charisma, Free</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Attribute Flaw:</strong> Wisdom</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Languages:</strong> Ryl, Galactic Basic.</p>
</li>
</ul>
',	'ancTwilek',	'Twi''lek',	'Humanoid, Twi''lek',	'Medium',	'{"sense": {"Scent": "Vague", "Vision": "Precise", "Hearing": "Imprecise"}, "attribute": {"flaw": "WIS", "boost": ["DEX", "CHA", {"free": 1}]}}',	'Twi''leks are one of the most recognizable and ubiquitous species in the galaxy, known for their distinctive head-tails, or lekku, and their incredible resilience. Originating from the harsh, storm-swept world of Ryloth, Twi''leks have a history defined by survival. Their homeworld’s extreme environment—ranging from scorching heat to freezing darkness—forced them to develop a society based on cooperation and adaptability. Unfortunately, their natural grace and beauty have historically made them targets for the galaxy''s criminal underworld, leading to a widespread Twi''lek diaspora across the stars.');

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS "AncestryFeat";
CREATE TABLE "public"."AncestryFeat" (
    "AncestryFeatID" character varying NOT NULL,
    "AncestryID" character varying NOT NULL,
    "Name" character varying NOT NULL,
    "Description" text NOT NULL,
    "Features" jsonb,
    "Summary" character varying NOT NULL,
    "Repeatable" boolean DEFAULT false NOT NULL,
    "Level" smallint NOT NULL,
    "Traits" character varying,
    "Prerequisites" jsonb,
    CONSTRAINT "AncestryFeat_AcnestryFeatID" PRIMARY KEY ("AncestryFeatID")
)
WITH (oids = false);

COMMENT ON COLUMN "public"."AncestryFeat"."AncestryFeatID" IS 'Unique Ancestry Feat ID';

INSERT INTO "AncestryFeat" ("AncestryFeatID", "AncestryID", "Name", "Description", "Features", "Summary", "Repeatable", "Level", "Traits", "Prerequisites") VALUES
('aftBlackmailLogic',	'ancBothan',	'Blackmail Logic',	'<div class="power-card-display">
  <header class="power-card-header">
    <div class="power-title-line">
      <h3 class="power-name">Blackmail Logic</h3>
      <span class="power-action-cost">[reaction]</span>
    </div>
    <div class="power-meta-top">
      <span class="power-level">Level 13</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="power-card-traits">
    <span class="trait-tag">Bothan</span>
    <span class="trait-tag">Mental</span>
  </div>

  <div class="power-card-meta-grid">
    <div>
      <strong>Trigger</strong>
      <span>A creature that you''re aware of attempts to attack you.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="power-card-divider" />

  <div class="power-card-description markdown-body">
    You can talk your way out of an execution. If a creature attempts to attack you, you can use your Reaction to utter a single phrase of blackmail or logic that causes them to hesitate. The attacker must make a Will save against your Diplomacy or Deception DC.<br><br><strong>Success</strong> The attack proceeds normally.<br><strong>Failure</strong> The creature is Stupefied 2 and must choose a different target for the attack. If no other target is valid, the action is wasted.<br><strong>Critical Failure</strong> The creature immediately ends its turn.
  </div>
</div>',	'{"action": {"grant": [{"id": "actBlackmailLogic", "name": "Blackmail Logic", "traits": "Bothan, Mental", "trigger": "A creature that you''re aware of attempts to attack you.", "action_cost": "[reaction]", "description": "You can talk your way out of an execution. If a creature attempts to attack you, you can use your Reaction to utter a single phrase of blackmail or logic that causes them to hesitate. The attacker must make a Will save against your Diplomacy or Deception DC.<br><br><strong>Success</strong> The attack proceeds normally.<br><strong>Failure</strong> The creature is Stupefied 2 and must choose a different target for the attack. If no other target is valid, the action is wasted.<br><strong>Critical Failure</strong> The creature immediately ends its turn."}]}}',	'You can talk your way out of an execution.',	'0',	13,	'Bothan, Mental',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftPoliticalAnimal", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftCooperativeSoul',	'ancHuman',	'Cooperative Soul',	'You''ve developed a soul-deep bond with your comrades. If you''re at least an expert in the skill you''re Aiding, when you roll a failure or critical failure to Aid a skill check, you get a success instead.',	NULL,	'You''ve developed a soul-deep bond with your comrades.',	'0',	9,	'Human',	'[{"feat": {"id": "aftCooperativeNature", "type": "ancestry"}}]'),
('aftGuerrillaRetreat',	'ancChubbit',	'Guerrilla Retreat',	'<div class="power-card-display">
  <header class="power-card-header">
    <div class="power-title-line">
      <h3 class="power-name">Guerrilla Retreat</h3>
      <span class="power-action-cost">[reaction]</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="power-card-traits">
    <span class="trait-tag">Chubbit</span>
    <span class="trait-tag">Move</span>
  </div>

  <div class="power-card-meta-grid">
    <div>
      <strong>Trigger</strong>
      <span>An adjacent enemy misses you with a melee Strike.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="power-card-divider" />

  <div class="power-card-description markdown-body">
    You excel at punishing clumsy attacks by instantly vanishing from reach. You immediately Step.
  </div>
</div>',	'{"action": {"grant": [{"id": "actGuerrillaRetreat", "name": "Guerrilla Retreat", "traits": "Chubbit, Move", "trigger": "An adjacent enemy misses you with a melee Strike.", "action_cost": "[reaction]", "description": "You excel at punishing clumsy attacks by instantly vanishing from reach. You immediately Step."}]}}',	'You excel at punishing clumsy attacks by instantly vanishing from reach.',	'0',	5,	'Chubbit, Move',	NULL),
('aftNaturalSkill',	'ancHuman',	'Natural Skill',	'Your ingenuity allows you to learn a wide variety of skills. You gain the trained proficiency rank in two skills of your choice.',	'{"skill": {"skill_increase": [{"max": "Trained", "count": 2}]}}',	'Your ingenuity allows you to learn a wide variety of skills.',	'0',	1,	'Human',	NULL),
('aftCooperativeNature',	'ancHuman',	'Cooperative Nature',	'The short human lifespan lends perspective and has taught you from a young age to set aside differences and work with others to achieve greatness. You gain a +4 circumstance bonus on checks to Aid.',	NULL,	'The short human lifespan lends perspective and has taught you from a young age to set aside differences and work with others to achieve greatness.',	'0',	1,	'Human',	NULL),
('aftCleverImproviser',	'ancHuman',	'Clever Improviser',	'You''ve learned how to handle situations when you''re out of your depth. You gain the Untrained Improvisation general feat. In addition, you can attempt skill actions that normally require you to be trained, even if you''re untrained.',	'{"feat": {"fixed": [{"id": "feaUntrainedImprovisation", "type": "general"}]}}',	'You''ve learned how to handle situations when you''re out of your depth.',	'0',	5,	'Human',	NULL),
('aftBornSpacer',	'ancDuros',	'Born Spacer',	'You are trained in Piloting. If you would automatically become trained in Piloting (for example, by your class), you instead become trained in a skill of your choice. You gain the Zero-G Training skill feat.',	'{"feat": {"fixed": ["feaZeroGTraining"]}, "skill": {"fixed": [{"id": "sklPiloting", "rank": "Trained"}]}}',	'You are trained in Piloting. If you would automatically become trained in Piloting (for example, by your class), you instead become trained in a skill of your choice. You gain the Zero-G Training skill feat.',	'0',	1,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftVacuumAcclimation',	'ancDuros',	'Vacuum Acclimation',	'Your physiology is naturally resistant to the void. You treat environmental effects from vacuum and low gravity as one step less severe. You can hold your breath for 1 hour.',	NULL,	'Your physiology is naturally resistant to the void.',	'0',	1,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftTrophyHunter',	'ancTrandoshan',	'Trophy Hunter',	'You gain a +1 circumstance bonus to Survival checks to Track creatures that you have previously damaged or creatures for which you are carrying a specific bounty puck or contract.',	'{"skill": {"conditional_bonus": [{"name": "Trophy Hunter", "value": "+1 circumstance bonus to Track creatures that you have previously damaged or are carrying a bounty.", "target": "sklSurvival"}]}}',	'You gain a +1 circumstance bonus to Survival checks to Track creatures that you have previously damaged or creatures for which you are carrying a specific bounty puck or contract.',	'0',	1,	'Trandoshan',	NULL),
('aftUnderfootAntics',	'ancChubbit',	'Underfoot Antics',	'You know exactly how to distract and unbalance creatures much larger than yourself. Whenever you are adjacent to a creature that is Large or larger, that creature is off-guard to your melee attacks.',	NULL,	'You know exactly how to distract and unbalance creatures much larger than yourself.',	'0',	5,	'Chubbit',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftScurry", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftVoidWalker',	'ancDuros',	'Void Walker',	'You gain a fly speed equal to your land speed, but only when in Zero-G environments. You do not become Off-Guard (Flat-Footed) when floating or flying in Zero-G.',	NULL,	'You gain a fly speed equal to your land speed, but only when in Zero-G environments.',	'0',	5,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftEngineWhisperer',	'ancDuros',	'Engine Whisperer',	'You can attempt to Repair a technological item or vehicle system without a repair kit, though you take a -2 penalty to the check when doing so.',	NULL,	'You can attempt to Repair a technological item or vehicle system without a repair kit, though you take a -2 penalty to the check when doing so.',	'0',	5,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftGunnerySynergy',	'ancDuros',	'Gunnery Synergy',	'When you use the Aid action to help an ally''s gunnery attack roll (starship or vehicle weapon), on a success, you give them a +2 circumstance bonus instead of +1. On a critical success, you give them a +3 bonus.',	NULL,	'When you use the Aid action to help an ally''s gunnery attack roll (starship or vehicle weapon), on a success, you give them a +2 circumstance bonus instead of +1. On a critical success, you give them a +3 bonus.',	'0',	9,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftSnapJudgment',	'ancDuros',	'Snap Judgment',	'You are permanently Quickened 1. You can use this extra action only to Recall Knowledge or Point Out.',	NULL,	'You are permanently Quickened 1. You can use this extra action only to Recall Knowledge or Point Out.',	'0',	13,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftTechnicalLinguist',	'ancDuros',	'Technical Linguist',	'You gain two additional languages at 1st level. In addition, you gain a +1 circumstance bonus to Decipher Writing when dealing with technical manuals or navigational charts.',	'{"skill": {"conditional_bonus": [{"name": "Technical Linguist", "value": "+1 circumstance bonus to Decipher Writing on technical manuals or navigational charts.", "target": "all"}]}, "extra_languages": 2}',	'You gain two additional languages at 1st level (chosen from common galactic languages). In addition, you gain a +1 circumstance bonus to Decipher Writing when dealing with technical manuals or navigational charts.',	'0',	1,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftAceOfAces',	'ancDuros',	'Ace of Aces',	'When piloting a vehicle or starship, you can roll two d20s for any Piloting check and take the higher result. This is a fortune effect.',	NULL,	'When piloting a vehicle or starship, you can roll two d20s for any Piloting check and take the higher result.',	'0',	17,	'Duros, Fortune',	NULL),
('aftOneWithTheVoid',	'ancDuros',	'One with the Void',	'You no longer need to breathe and are immune to the damaging effects of a vacuum.',	NULL,	'You no longer need to breathe and are immune to the damaging effects of a vacuum.',	'0',	17,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftGalacticStoryteller',	'ancDuros',	'Galactic Storyteller',	'You are trained in Spacer Lore. You gain a +1 circumstance bonus to Diplomacy checks when you Make an Impression by sharing stories of your travels.',	'{"skill": {"fixed": [{"id": "sklLoreSpacer", "rank": "Trained"}], "conditional_bonus": [{"name": "Galactic Storyteller", "value": "+1 circumstance bonus to Make an Impression by sharing stories of your travels.", "target": "sklDiplomacy"}]}}',	'You are trained in Spacer Lore.',	'0',	1,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftSpacersCamaraderie',	'ancDuros',	'Spacers'' Camaraderie',	'You can use your Piloting skill modifier for Diplomacy checks when dealing with other spacers, dock officials, or pilots.',	NULL,	'ou can use your Piloting skill modifier for Diplomacy checks when dealing with other spacers, dock officials, or pilots.',	'0',	9,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftCalculatedRisk',	'ancDuros',	'Calculated Risk',	'Once per day, when you roll a Failure on a Computers or Piloting check, you can treat it as a Success.',	NULL,	'Once per day, when you roll a Failure on a Computers or Piloting check, you can treat it as a Success.',	'0',	9,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftIntuitiveAstrogation',	'ancDuros',	'Intuitive Astrogation',	'You always know your precise location in a star system relative to the nearest gravity well. You gain a +1 circumstance bonus to Survival checks to Sense Direction outdoors and Piloting checks to Plot Course.',	'{"skill": {"conditional_bonus": [{"name": "Intuitive Astrogation", "value": "+1 circumstance bonus to Plot Course.", "target": "sklPiloting"}, {"name": "Intuitive Astrogation", "value": "+1 circumstance bonus to Sense Direction outdoors.", "target": "sklSurvival"}]}}',	'You always know your precise location in a star system relative to the nearest gravity well.',	'0',	1,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftScorekeepersInitiate',	'ancTrandoshan',	'Scorekeeper''s Initiate',	'You are a devout follower of the Scorekeeper. You are trained in Trandoshan Lore. You gain the Battle Planner skill feat, allowing you to use your Trandoshan Lore skill modifier for initiative rolls when you have scouted the enemy beforehand.',	'{"feat": {"fixed": [{"id": "feaBattlePlanner", "type": "skill"}], "skill": [{"id": "sklLoreTrandoshan", "rank": "Trained"}]}}',	'You are a devout follower of the Scorekeeper.',	'0',	1,	'Trandoshan',	NULL),
('aftHighGTolerance',	'ancDuros',	'High-G Tolerance',	'You are immune to the Sickened condition. In addition, you gain resistance 5 to bludgeoning damage.',	'{"defense": {"immunity": [{"type": "Sickened", "source": "High-G Tolerance (Ancestry Feat)"}], "resistance": [{"type": "Bludgeoning", "amount": "5", "source": "High-G Tolerance (Ancestry Feat)"}]}}',	'You are immune to the Sickened condition. In addition, you gain resistance 5 to bludgeoning damage.',	'0',	13,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftSlaversGrip',	'ancTrandoshan',	'Slaver''s Grip',	'You are accustomed to hauling captured prey. When you successfully Reposition a creature you are grabbing, you can move up to your base Speed.',	NULL,	'You are accustomed to hauling captured prey.',	'0',	1,	'Trandoshan',	NULL),
('aftRapidMetabolism',	'ancTrandoshan',	'Rapid Metabolism',	'Your body heals at an accelerated rate during downtime. When you rest for 8 hours, you recover double the normal amount of Hit Points. In addition, the DC for Medicine checks to Treat Wounds on you is reduced by 2.',	NULL,	'Your body heals at an accelerated rate during downtime.',	'0',	1,	'Trandoshan',	NULL),
('aftBottomlessPit',	'ancOrtolan',	'Bottomless Pit',	'Your hunger is an event horizon.

<div class="power-card-display">
  <header class="power-card-header">
    <div class="power-title-line">
      <h3 class="power-name">Inhale</h3>
      <span class="power-action-cost">[reaction]</span>
    </div>
    <div class="power-meta-top">
      <span class="power-level">Level 17</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="power-card-traits">
    <span class="trait-tag">Ortolan</span>
  </div>

  <div class="power-card-meta-grid">
    <div>
      <strong>Trigger</strong>
      <span>You are targeted by a Thrown or Projectile ranged attack.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="power-card-divider" />

  <div class="power-card-description markdown-body">
    You react to devour a projectile fired or thrown at you. You reduce the damage of the triggering attack by 20 + your Level. Alternatively, if the projectile is explosive (like a Grenade or Missile), you automatically take only half damage from the blast but remove the Area trait entirely.
  </div>
</div>',	'{"action": {"grant": [{"id": "actInhale", "name": "Inhale", "traits": "Ortolan", "trigger": "You are targeted by a Thrown or Projectile ranged attack.", "action_cost": "[reaction]", "description": "You react to devour a projectile fired or thrown at you. You reduce the damage of the triggering attack by 20 + your Level. Alternatively, if the projectile is explosive (like a Grenade or Missile), you automatically take only half damage from the blast but remove the Area trait entirely."}, {"id": "actChomp", "name": "Chomp", "traits": "Ortolan, Flourish", "action_cost": "[one-action]", "description": "Make an unarmed melee Strike against a Construct creature or unattended object. This attack ignores 20 points of Hardness."}]}}',	'Your hunger is an event horizon.',	'0',	17,	'Ortolan',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftPowerLunch", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftTremorSensitive',	'ancChubbit',	'Tremor-Sensitive',	'Your sensitive nervous system can detect the minute vibrations of approaching footfalls. You gain imprecise tremorsense with a range of 15 feet.',	'{"sense": [{"Tremorsense (15ft)": "Imprecise"}]}',	'Your sensitive nervous system can detect the minute vibrations of approaching footfalls.',	'0',	5,	'Chubbit',	NULL),
('aftShedSkin',	'ancTrandoshan',	'Shed Skin',	'<div class="power-card-display">
  <header class="power-card-header">
    <div class="power-title-line">
      <h3 class="power-name">Shed Skin</h3>
      <span class="power-action-cost">[reaction]</span>
    </div>
    <div class="power-meta-top">
      <span class="power-level">Level 5</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="power-card-traits">
    <span class="trait-tag">Trandoshan</span>
  </div>

  <div class="power-card-meta-grid">
    <div>
      <strong>Trigger</strong>
      <span>You are grabbed, immobilized, or restrained.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="power-card-divider" />

  <div class="power-card-description markdown-body">
    You attempt to Escape. You gain a +2 circumstance bonus to this check. If you succeed, you shed a layer of skin, leaving it in the attacker''s grasp, and can immediately Step as part of the reaction.
  </div>
</div>',	'{"action": {"grant": [{"id": "actShedSkin", "name": "Shed Skin", "traits": "Trandoshan", "trigger": "You are grabbed, immobilized, or restrained.", "action_cost": "[reaction]", "description": "You attempt to Escape. You gain a +2 circumstance bonus to this check. If you succeed, you shed a layer of skin, leaving it in the attacker''s grasp, and can immediately Step as part of the reaction."}]}}',	'You can escape restraint by shedding a layer of skin.',	'0',	5,	'Trandoshan',	NULL),
('aftThermalFocus',	'ancTrandoshan',	'Thermal Focus',	'You can rely solely on heat signatures to target foes. You do not need to make a flat check to target a Concealed or Hidden creature within 10 feet of you if that creature is warm-blooded (or emits heat, like a running engine/droid).',	NULL,	'You can rely solely on heat signatures to target foes.',	'0',	9,	'Trandoshan',	NULL),
('aftInternalStorage',	'ancDroid',	'Internal Storage',	'You have a hidden, shielded compartment within your chassis. It can hold 1 Bulk worth of items. Perception DCs to find items hidden in this compartment are increased by 2.',	'{"item": {"bulk": null, "name": "Internal Storage", "description": "You have a hidden, shielded compartment within your chassis. It can hold 1 Bulk worth of items. Perception DCs to find items hidden in this compartment are increased by 2.", "is_container": true, "container_capacity": 1}}',	'You have a hidden, shielded compartment within your chassis.',	'0',	1,	'Droid',	NULL),
('aftApexPredator',	'ancTrandoshan',	'Apex Predator',	'Creatures within 30 feet of you that are warm-blooded or otherwise emit a heat signature are always visible to you, regardless of Stealth, concealment, or illusions.  You gain a +2 status bonus to checks or saves to disbelieve illusions that affect such creatures.

Cover between you and other creatures still affects your vision as normal.',	NULL,	'Creatures within 30 feet of you that are warm-blooded or otherwise emit a heat signature are always visible to you',	'0',	17,	'Trandoshan',	NULL),
('aftMagLockFeet',	'ancDroid',	'Mag-Lock Feet',	'You can activate magnetic clamps in your feet as a single action. While active, you gain a +2 circumstance bonus to your DC against being Shoved or Tripped, and you can walk on metal surfaces in Zero-G without floating away.',	NULL,	'You can activate magnetic clamps in your feet.',	'0',	1,	'Droid',	NULL),
('aftHuntersInstinct',	'ancTrandoshan',	'Hunter''s Instinct',	'Your sense of smell and heat detection sharpens. You gain Scent as an imprecise sense.',	'{"sense": [{"Scent": "Imprecise"}]}',	'Your sense of smell and heat detection sharpens.',	'0',	5,	'Trandoshan',	NULL),
('aftLogicCoprocessor',	'ancDroid',	'Logic Coprocessor',	'You approach problems with cold, calculated logic. You gain the Dubious Knowledge skill feat. When you roll a Failure on a check to Recall Knowledge, you get a critical failure effect only on a natural 1.',	'{"feat": {"fixed": [{"id": "feaDubiousKnowledge", "type": "skill"}]}}',	'You approach problems with cold, calculated logic.',	'0',	1,	'Droid',	NULL),
('aftSensorArrayUpgrade',	'ancDroid',	'Sensor Array Upgrade',	'You gain darkvision.',	'{"sense": [{"Darkvision": "60 feet"}]}',	'You gain darkvision.',	'0',	5,	'Droid',	NULL),
('aftBackupMemory',	'ancDroid',	'Backup Memory',	'If you are subject to a mental effect that would modify your memory or control your actions, you can attempt a new Will save at the start of every turn to end the effect immediately.',	NULL,	'If you are subject to a mental effect that would modify your memory or control your actions, you can attempt a new Will save at the start of every turn to end the effect immediately.',	'0',	9,	'Droid',	NULL),
('aftGrandManipulator',	'ancBothan',	'Grand Manipulator',	'<div class="power-card-display">
  <header class="power-card-header">
    <div class="power-title-line">
      <h3 class="power-name">Grand Manipulator</h3>
      <span class="power-action-cost">[one-action]</span>
    </div>
    <div class="power-meta-top">
      <span class="power-level">Level 17</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="power-card-traits">
    <span class="trait-tag">Bothan</span>
    <span class="trait-tag">Linguistic</span>
    <span class="trait-tag">Mental</span>
  </div>

  <hr class="power-card-divider" />

  <div class="power-card-description markdown-body">
    You can convince an enemy that their leader has betrayed them. Choose one creature within 60 feet that can hear you. It must succeed at a Will save against your Class DC.<br><br><strong>Critical Success</strong> target is unaffected.<br><strong>Success</strong> The target is Stupefied 2 and Off-Guard to you.<br><strong>Failure</strong> The target becomes Controlled by you for 1 round. You can force it to attack its allies or drop its weapons.<br><strong>Critical Failure</strong> The target becomes Controlled by you for 1 minute. It essentially defects to your side for the duration of the combat. (The target can attempt a new save at the end of each of its turns to end the effect).
  </div>
</div>',	'{"action": {"grant": [{"id": "actGrand Manipulator", "name": "Grand Manipulator", "traits": "Bothan, Linguistic, Mental", "action_cost": "[one-action]", "description": "You can convince an enemy that their leader has betrayed them. Choose one creature within 60 feet that can hear you. It must succeed at a Will save against your Class DC.<br><br><strong>Critical Success</strong> target is unaffected.<br><strong>Success</strong> The target is Stupefied 2 and Off-Guard to you.<br><strong>Failure</strong> The target becomes Controlled by you for 1 round. You can force it to attack its allies or drop its weapons.<br><strong>Critical Failure</strong> The target becomes Controlled by you for 1 minute. It essentially defects to your side for the duration of the combat. (The target can attempt a new save at the end of each of its turns to end the effect)."}]}}',	'You can convince an enemy that their leader has betrayed them.',	'0',	17,	'Bothan, Linguistic, Mental',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftPsychologicalWarfare", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftHazardPlating',	'ancDroid',	'Hazard Plating',	'You gain resistance 2 to all physical damage (bludgeoning, piercing, slashing) due to your thick industrial casing.',	'{"defense": {"resistance": [{"type": "Bludgeoning", "amount": "2", "source": "Hazard Plating (Ancestry Feat)"}, {"type": "Piercing", "amount": "2", "source": "Hazard Plating (Ancestry Feat)"}, {"type": "Slashing", "amount": "2", "source": "Hazard Plating (Ancestry Feat)"}]}}',	'You gain resistance 2 to all physical damage (bludgeoning, piercing, slashing) due to your thick industrial casing.',	'0',	5,	'Droid',	'[{"heritage": "herDroidClass5"}]'),
('aftSavageCritical',	'ancShistavanen',	'Savage Critical',	'Your brutality is unmatched. When you critically hit with your Shistavanen Claws, the target is Slowed 1 until the end of its next turn due to the pain and shock of the wound.',	NULL,	'Your brutality is unmatched.',	'0',	13,	'Shistavanen',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftThroatRipper", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftSurgicalPrecision',	'ancDroid',	'Surgical Precision',	'Your programming contains a comprehensive anatomical database that rivals the training of organic doctors. You are trained in Medicine. If you would automatically become trained in Medicine (from your background or class), you instead become trained in a skill of your choice.

In addition, you can use your Intelligence modifier instead of your Wisdom modifier for Medicine checks.',	'{"skill": {"fixed": [{"id": "sklMedicine", "rank": "Trained"}], "attribute_override": [{"id": "sklMedicine", "attribute": "INT"}]}}',	'Your programming contains a comprehensive anatomical database that rivals the training of organic doctors.',	'0',	1,	'Droid',	'[{"heritage": "herDroidClass1"}]'),
('aftRecoilCompensation',	'ancDroid',	'Recoil Compensation',	'Your chassis is reinforced with gyroscopic stabilizers and shock-absorbing servos designed to handle heavy ordnance and massive kinetic feedback.

You ignore the penalty to attack rolls from the Volley trait on any ranged weapons you wield. Additionally, when making a ranged Strike with a weapon that has the Area, Automatic, or Kickback traits, you gain a circumstance bonus to damage equal to the number of damage dice rolled.',	NULL,	'Your chassis is reinforced with gyroscopic stabilizers and shock-absorbing servos designed to handle heavy ordnance and massive kinetic feedback.',	'0',	5,	'Droid',	'[{"heritage": "herDroidClass4"}]'),
('aftMachineSpeak',	'ancDroid',	'Machine Speak',	'You can communicate with simple machines (like moisture vaporators or binary load lifters) to gather information about what has happened in the area recently.',	NULL,	'You can communicate with simple machines (like moisture vaporators or binary load lifters) to gather information about what has happened in the area recently.',	'0',	5,	'Droid',	'[{"heritage": "herDroidClass2"}]'),
('aftSystemOverride',	'ancAnzellan',	'System Override',	'You can speak binary better than Basic. Computers skill checks to Disable a Device count as a 1-action activity. If you roll a Critical Failure on a check to Disable a Device, you trigger a regular Failure instead.',	NULL,	'You can speak binary better than Basic.',	'0',	9,	'Anzellan',	'[{"skill": [{"id": "sklComputers", "rank": "Master"}]}]'),
('aftAutomatedResponse',	'ancDroid',	'Automated Response',	'You are permanently Quickened 1. You can use the extra action only to Scan (Seek), Calculate (Recall Knowledge), or Interface (Interact with a computer).',	NULL,	'You are permanently Quickened 1.',	'0',	13,	'Droid',	NULL),
('aftHardenedSystems',	'ancDroid',	'Hardened Systems',	'Your internal components are shielded against disruption. You gain resistance 5 to electricity damage and to ion damage.',	'{"defense": {"resistance": [{"type": "Electricity", "amount": "5", "source": "Hardened Systems (Ancestry Feat)"}, {"type": "Ion", "amount": "5", "source": "Hardened Systems (Ancestry Feat)"}]}}',	'Your internal components are shielded against disruption.',	'0',	9,	'Droid',	NULL),
('aftInsideTheWalls',	'ancAnzellan',	'Inside the Walls',	'You can access the internals of structures and vehicles that others cannot. You can use an Interact action to enter a Large or larger object (like a computer terminal, a vehicle console, or a wall vent) as if it were a creature, gaining Total Cover. While inside, you can still make use of the Computers or Crafting skill to interact with the object.',	NULL,	'You can access the internals of structures and vehicles that others cannot.',	'0',	13,	'Anzellan',	NULL),
('aftHardToSquash',	'ancAnzellan',	'Hard to Squash',	'<div class="power-card-display">
  <header class="power-card-header">
    <div class="power-title-line">
      <h3 class="power-name">Hard to Squash</h3>
      <span class="power-action-cost">[reaction]</span>
    </div>
    <div class="power-meta-top">
      <span class="power-level">Level 13</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="power-card-traits">
    <span class="trait-tag">Anzellan</span>
  </div>

  <div class="power-card-meta-grid">
    <div>
      <strong>Trigger</strong>
      <span>A creature larger than you hits you with a melee attack.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="power-card-divider" />

  <div class="power-card-description markdown-body">
    You tuck and roll with the impact. You take half damage from the triggering attack and may immediately Step as a free action.
  </div>
</div>',	'{"action": {"grant": [{"id": "actHardToSquash", "name": "Hard to Squash", "traits": "Anzellan", "trigger": "A creature larger than you hits you with a melee attack.", "action_cost": "[reaction]", "description": "You tuck and roll with the impact. You take half damage from the triggering attack and may immediately Step as a free action."}]}}',	'You tuck and roll with the impact.',	'0',	13,	'Anzellan',	NULL),
('aftEmpathicBroadcast',	'ancIktotchi',	'Empathic Broadcast',	'You can project your thoughts to non-Iktotchi. You gain telepathy with a range of 30 feet, allowing you to communicate silently with any creature that shares a language with you.',	'{"sense": [{"Telepathy": "30 feet"}]}',	'You can project your thoughts to non-Iktotchi.',	'0',	5,	'Iktotchi',	'[{"feat": {"id": "aftTelepathicSensitivity", "type": "ancestry"}}]'),
('aftSubconsciousWarning',	'ancIktotchi',	'Subconscious Warning',	'You get flashes of danger before it happens. You gain a +2 circumstance bonus to Perception checks to avoid being surprised. If you roll initiative, you can draw a weapon as a free action.',	'{"perception": {"conditional_bonus": [{"name": "Subconscious Warning", "value": "+2 circumstance bonus to avoid being surprised.", "target": "all"}]}}',	'You get flashes of danger before it happens.',	'0',	1,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftScrapTechJuryRigger',	'ancChubbit',	'Scrap-Tech Jury-Rigger',	'You fought a war using whatever broken equipment you could scavenge, teaching you how to keep gear running with little more than wire and willpower. You can attempt to Repair an item without a repair kit. If you do so, you take a -2 circumstance penalty to the Crafting check instead of being unable to attempt it.',	NULL,	'You fought a war using whatever broken equipment you could scavenge, teaching you how to keep gear running with little more than wire and willpower.',	'0',	5,	'Chubbit',	NULL),
('aftPrecognitiveDefense',	'ancIktotchi',	'Precognitive Defense',	'Your AC increases by 1 against all attacks from creatures that you are aware of, as you instinctively move before they strike.',	NULL,	'our AC increases by 1 against all attacks from creatures that you are aware of, as you instinctively move before they strike.',	'0',	13,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftStormSurvivor',	'ancIktotchi',	'Storm Survivor',	'Your species evolved on a moon with violent winds. You treat environmental wind effects as one step less severe. You gain a +2 circumstance bonus to your Fortitude DC against being Shoved or Tripped.',	'{"saving_throw": [{"conditional_bonus": [{"name": "Storm Survivor", "value": "+2 circumstance bonus to DC against being Shoved or Tripped.", "target": "fortitude"}]}]}',	'Your species evolved on a moon with violent winds.',	'0',	1,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftCranialRam',	'ancIktotchi',	'Cranial Ram',	'Your heavy, downward-curving horns are a natural weapon. You gain a horn unarmed attack that deals 1d6 piercing damage. It has the Shove trait, allowing you to Shove enemies even if your hands are full.',	'{"weapon": [{"id": "natCranial Ram", "bulk": null, "name": "Iktotchi Horns", "type": "Melee", "group": "Brawling", "hands": "1", "traits": "Shove", "category": "Unarmed", "damagedie": "d6", "damagetype": "P", "description": "Your heavy, downward-curving horns are a natural weapon. You gain a horn unarmed attack that deals 1d6 piercing damage. It has the Shove trait, allowing you to Shove enemies even if your hands are full."}]}',	'Your heavy, downward-curving horns are a natural weapon.',	'0',	1,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftTelepathicSensitivity',	'ancIktotchi',	'Telepathic Sensitivity',	'You can sense the surface emotions of creatures within 30 feet. You gain a +1 circumstance bonus to Perception checks to Sense Motive. You can communicate telepathically with other Iktotchi within 60 feet.',	'{"sense": [{"Detect Surface Emotions": "30 feet"}]}',	'You can sense the surface emotions of creatures within 30 feet.',	'0',	1,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftUncannyAwareness',	'ancIktotchi',	'Uncanny Awareness',	'Your visions prevent you from being caught off-guard.  You cannot be made off-guard due to creatures being hidden or concealed from you, and you cannot be flanked by creatures of your level or lower.',	NULL,	'Your visions prevent you from being caught off-guard.',	'0',	9,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftGuidedPiloting',	'ancIktotchi',	'Guided Piloting',	'When you pilot a starship, your precognition guides your hand. Once per round, you can reroll a Piloting check, but you must take the second result.',	NULL,	'When you pilot a starship, your precognition guides your hand.',	'0',	9,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftVisionsOfTheFuture',	'ancIktotchi',	'Visions of the Future',	'You can spend 10 minutes in meditation to gain a vague glimpse of the future. During your meditation, ask about the results of a particular course of action.  Your vision can predict results up to 30 minutes into the future and reveal the GM''s best guess among the following outcomes: good, bad, mixed (the results will be a mix of good and bad), and nothing (there won''t be particularly good or bad results).

The GM rolls a secret DC 6 flat check. On a failure, the result is always “nothing.” This makes it impossible to tell whether a “nothing” result is accurate.',	NULL,	'You can spend 10 minutes in meditation to gain a vague glimpse of the future.',	'0',	13,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftIktotchiPilot',	'ancIktotchi',	'Iktotchi Pilot',	'You are trained in Piloting. If you would automatically become trained in Piloting, you instead become trained in a skill of your choice. You gain a +1 circumstance bonus to Initiative rolls when you are piloting a vehicle or starship.',	'{"skill": {"fixed": [{"id": "sklPiloting", "rank": "Trained"}]}}',	'You are trained in Piloting.',	'0',	1,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftStoicDemeanor',	'ancIktotchi',	'Stoic Demeanor',	'Iktotchi hide their emotions behind a mask of calm. You gain a +1 circumstance bonus to Will saves against Emotion and Fear effects. If you succeed at a save against a Fear effect, you get a critical success instead.',	'{"saving_throw": [{"conditional_bonus": [{"name": "Stoic Demeanor", "value": "+1 circumstance bonus against Emotion and Fear effects.", "target": "will"}]}]}',	'Iktotchi hide their emotions behind a mask of calm.',	'0',	1,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftSquibLore',	'ancSquib',	'Squib Lore',	'You have spent your life cataloging junk and learning who to sell it to. You become trained in Crafting and Squib Lore. If you would automatically become trained in one of these (from your background or class), you instead become trained in a skill of your choice. You also gain the Additional Lore general feat for Mercantile Lore.',	'{"feat": {"fixed": [{"id": "feaAdditionalLore", "type": "skill"}]}, "skill": {"fixed": [{"id": "sklCrafting", "rank": "Trained"}, {"id": "sklLoreSquib", "rank": "Trained"}]}}',	'You have spent your life cataloging junk and learning who to sell it to.',	'0',	1,	'Squib',	NULL),
('aftMasterNavigator',	'ancDuros',	'Master Navigator',	'Your mind processes astrogation data and spatial coordinates with the speed and accuracy of a nav-computer. You can never get lost in space or on a planet''s surface.

Additionally, once per day, you can spend 1 minute analyzing your surroundings or a star chart to determine the most direct physical route to a destination you are familiar with. For the next 8 hours, you instinctively know the direction and distance to that destination, and you gain a +4 circumstance bonus to Piloting or Survival checks made to traverse that route.',	'{"skill": {"conditional_bonus": [{"name": "Master Navigator", "value": "+4 circumstance bonus to traverse a calculated route.", "target": "sklPiloting"}, {"name": "Master Navigator", "value": "+4 circumstance bonus to traverse a calculated route.", "target": "sklSurvival"}]}}',	'Your mind processes astrogation data and spatial coordinates with the speed and accuracy of a nav-computer.',	'0',	13,	'Duros',	NULL),
('aftImprovisedWeaponFamiliarity',	'ancSquib',	'Improvised Weapon Familiarity',	'You are adept at fighting with whatever is at hand, from wrench to rock. You do not take the standard –2 item penalty to attack rolls with improvised weapons.

For the purpose of proficiency, you treat improvised weapons as Simple Weapons of their approximate shape and size (e.g., a pipe functions as a club, a jagged shard of glass functions as a dagger).

Additionally, if you use a technological item as an improvised weapon (such as a battery or a droid arm), it gains the Tech trait.',	NULL,	'You are adept at fighting with whatever is at hand, from wrench to rock.',	'0',	1,	'Squib',	NULL),
('aftClingyFur',	'ancSquib',	'Clingy Fur',	'Your fur is stiff and hooked, acting like natural gripping pads. You gain a +2 circumstance bonus to Athletics checks to Climb and Grab an Edge. If you succeed at a Climb check, you are not Flat-Footed (Off-Guard) while climbing.',	'{"skill": {"conditional_bonus": [{"name": "Clingy Fur", "value": "+2 circumstance bonus to Climb and Grab an Edge.", "target": "sklAthletics"}]}}',	'Your fur is stiff and hooked, acting like natural gripping pads.',	'0',	1,	'Squib',	NULL),
('aftTechScent',	'ancSquib',	'Tech-Scent',	'Your nose is attuned to the ozone smell of active power cells and coolant. You gain an imprecise Scent sense but it only detects distinct technological items (batteries, blasters, droids) or creatures with the Tech or Construct trait.',	'{"sense": [{"Tech-Scent": "Imprecise"}]}',	'Your nose is attuned to the ozone smell of active power cells and coolant.',	'0',	1,	'Squib',	NULL),
('aftInstinctiveAstrogation',	'ancShistavanen',	'Instinctive Astrogation',	'You don''t need a nav-computer; you can feel the hyperspace lanes. You can attempt to calculate a hyperspace jump (Astrogation) as a 1-round activity (instead of 1 minute or longer). Additionally, if you fail a Piloting check to navigate hazards or astrogate, you can reroll the check (Fortune effect). You must use the second result.',	NULL,	'You don''t need a nav-computer; you can feel the hyperspace lanes.',	'0',	9,	'Shistavanen',	'[{"skill": [{"id": "sklPiloting", "rank": "Expert"}]}]'),
('aftUnderfootScurry',	'ancSquib',	'Underfoot Scurry',	'You are accustomed to darting between the legs of larger species. You can move through the spaces of creatures of Medium size or larger. You still cannot end your turn in an occupied space. When you move through a creature’s space, you gain a +1 circumstance bonus to AC against its Reactions.',	NULL,	'You are accustomed to darting between the legs of larger species.',	'0',	1,	'Squib',	NULL),
('aftTrashTerrain',	'ancSquib',	'Trash Terrain',	'You are at home in garbage chutes and scrap yards. You ignore Difficult Terrain caused by rubble, debris, trash, or junk. If you are in such terrain, you can use the Take Cover action to gain Standard Cover (instead of Lesser Cover) even if the debris wouldn''t normally provide it.',	NULL,	'You are at home in garbage chutes and scrap yards.',	'0',	5,	'Squib',	NULL),
('aftConfidentHaggler',	'ancSquib',	'Confident Haggler',	'You have an unshakable belief in your own deal-making abilities. You are trained in the Deception skill. If you were already trained, you become trained in a skill of your choice. You can use Deception instead of Diplomacy to Make an Impression or Request, provided the interaction involves commerce, trading, or negotiation.',	'{"skill": {"fixed": [{"id": "sklDeception", "rank": "Trained"}]}}',	'You have an unshakable belief in your own deal-making abilities.',	'0',	1,	'Squib',	NULL),
('aftIKnowWhatYoureGoingToDo',	'ancIktotchi',	'I Know What You''re Going To Do',	'You read the intent of your enemies perfectly. You automatically detect the surface thoughts of any creature within 30 feet of you',	'{"sense": [{"Detect Thoughts": "30 feet"}]}',	'You read the intent of your enemies perfectly.',	'0',	17,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftApexPredatorsShot',	'ancRodian',	'Apex Predator''s Shot',	'Amateurs trade blaster fire; you wait for the heartbeat between breaths to deliver a singular, terminal shot that leaves no room for retaliation.

<div class="power-card-display">
  <header class="power-card-header">
    <div class="power-title-line">
      <h3 class="power-name">Kill Shot</h3>
      <span class="power-action-cost">[two-actions]</span>
    </div>
    <div class="power-meta-top">
      <span class="power-level">Level 17</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="power-card-traits">
    <span class="trait-tag">Rodian</span>
  </div>

  <div class="power-card-meta-grid">
    <div>
      <strong>Requirements</strong>
      <span>You are wielding a Rifle or Pistol and your target is Unaware of you or Off-Guard.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="power-card-divider" />

  <div class="power-card-description markdown-body">
    Make a ranged Strike.  On a Success, the hit resolves as if it were a Critical Success (dealing additional damage and any critical specialization effects that might apply).  On a Critical Sucess, the target deals triple damage instead of the normal double damage, and the target must make a Fortitude save against your Class DC or fall to 0 HP immediately.
  </div>
</div>',	'{"action": {"grant": [{"id": "actKillShot", "name": "Kill Shot", "traits": "Rodian", "action_cost": "[two-actions]", "description": "Make a ranged Strike.  On a Success, the hit resolves as if it were a Critical Success (dealing additional damage and any critical specialization effects that might apply).  On a Critical Sucess, the target deals triple damage instead of the normal double damage, and the target must make a Fortitude save against your Class DC or fall to 0 HP immediately.", "requirements": "You are wielding a Rifle or Pistol and your target is Unaware of you or Off-Guard."}]}}',	'Amateurs trade blaster fire; you wait for the heartbeat between breaths to deliver a singular, terminal shot that leaves no room for retaliation.',	'0',	17,	'Rodian',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftRodianWeaponFamiliarity", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftExpertScavenger',	'ancSquib',	'Expert Scavenger',	'You can find utility where others see nothing. During your daily preparations, you can produce a number of temporary consumables (grenades, meds, or ammo) equal to your Level. These items must be level 1 or lower, have a value of 10 credits or less, and are obviously cobbled together from trash. They function normally but crumble into dust if not used by your next daily preparation.',	NULL,	'You can find utility where others see nothing.',	'0',	9,	'Squib',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftSquibLore", "type": "ancestry"}], "skill": [{"id": "sklCrafting", "rank": "Master"}]}]'),
('aftSlipperyTarget',	'ancSquib',	'Slippery Target',	'Your fur and flexibility make you a nightmare to pin down. You gain a +2 circumstance bonus to Acrobatics checks to Escape. Additionally, whenever you succeed at a Reflex save against a damaging effect, you take no damage (as if you had critically succeeded).',	'{"skill": {"conditional_bonus": [{"name": "Slippery Target", "value": "+2 circumstance bonus to Escape.", "target": "sklAcrobatics"}]}}',	'Your fur and flexibility make you a nightmare to pin down.',	'0',	13,	'Squib',	NULL),
('aftImpossibleSqueeze',	'ancSquib',	'Impossible Squeeze',	'You can fit through gaps that seem physically impossible. You can Squeeze through spaces as narrow as 2 or 3 inches wide (such as ventilation grates or pipe fittings). You move at your full Speed while Squeezing.',	NULL,	'You can fit through gaps that seem physically impossible.',	'0',	13,	'Squib',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftRubberySkeleton", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftUnstoppableHunter',	'ancShistavanen',	'Unstoppable Hunter',	'Nothing keeps you from your prey. You ignore the effects of Difficult Terrain and Greater Difficult Terrain. In addition, you gain a +2 status bonus to saves against effects that would Immobilize, Slow, or Paralyze you.',	'{"saving_throw": [{"conditional_bonus": [{"name": "Unstoppable Hunter", "value": "+2 status bonus against Immobilize, Slow, or Paralyze.", "target": "all"}]}]}',	'Nothing keeps you from your prey.',	'0',	13,	'Shistavanen',	NULL),
('aftMicroTargeting',	'ancAnzellan',	'Micro-Targeting',	'You aim for the eyes, the exhaust ports, and the exposed knee-joints. Your melee attacks against creatures at least two sizes larger than you (Medium or larger) gain the Deadly d8 trait.

If the weapon already has the Deadly trait, increase the size of its deadly die by one step (e.g., d8 becomes d10) instead.',	NULL,	'You aim for the eyes, the exhaust ports, and the exposed knee-joints.',	'0',	9,	'Anzellan',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftAnzellanOptics", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftRapidTracking',	'ancShistavanen',	'Rapid Tracking',	'You can read a trail at a dead sprint. You can move at your full Speed while Tracking without taking the -5 penalty. If you are Legendary in Survival, you can Track without penalty while using a vehicle/mount at full speed.',	NULL,	'You can read a trail at a dead sprint.',	'0',	9,	'Shistavanen',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftGalacticScout", "type": "ancestry"}], "skill": [{"id": "sklSurvival", "rank": "Expert"}]}]'),
('aftOneMansTrash',	'ancSquib',	'One Man’s Trash',	'Your eye for value is supernatural. When you use the Search exploration activity, you can find items of value in completely barren locations (dust in a vent, a loose screw in a wall). Once per day, you can produce a single common item of Light Bulk up to Level 5 from your pockets or the immediate environment, claiming you "just found it."',	NULL,	'Your eye for value is supernatural.',	'0',	13,	'Squib',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftExpertScavenget", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftKingOfTheHeap',	'ancSquib',	'King of the Heap',	'You move through chaos like a fish moves through water, and you know how to make the environment turn against your foes.  You ignore difficult terrain caused by rubble, debris, trash, or crowded machinery, and any enemies within 10 feet of you treat such difficult terrain as greater difficult terrain.  You gain concealment while in such types of difficult terrain, and any attack you make while benefitting from such concealment deals an additional 2d6 precision damage.',	NULL,	'You move through chaos like a fish moves through water, and you know how to make the environment turn against your foes.',	'0',	17,	'Squib',	NULL),
('aftAdmiralsOrder',	'ancMonCalamari',	'Admiral''s Order',	'<p>You command the flow of the entire battle.</p>
<div class="power-card-display">
  <header class="power-card-header">
    <div class="power-title-line">
      <h3 class="power-name">Concentrate Fire!</h3>
      <span class="power-action-cost">[three-actions]</span>
    </div>
    <div class="power-meta-top">
      <span class="power-level">Level 17</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="power-card-traits">
    <span class="trait-tag">Mon Calamari</span>
    <span class="trait-tag">Auditory</span>
    <span class="trait-tag">Visual</span>
    <span class="trait-tag">Mental</span>
  </div>

  <div class="power-card-meta-grid">
    <div>
      <strong>Frequency</strong>
      <span>Once per minute.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="power-card-divider" />

  <div class="power-card-description markdown-body">
    You shout a command. Choose a target enemy. All allies within 60 feet who can see/hear you and have line of sight to the target can immediately use a Reaction to make a single ranged Strike against that target. These attacks are made with a -2 penalty due to the haste of the volley.<br><br><strong>Special</strong> If you have the Envoy Directives ability, you may also make a ranged Strike as a free action.
  </div>
</div>',	'{"action": {"grant": [{"id": "actConcentrateFire", "name": "Concentrate Fire!", "traits": "Mon Calamari, Auditory, Visual, Mental", "frequency": "Once per minute.", "action_cost": "[three-actions]", "description": "You shout a command. Choose a target enemy. All allies within 60 feet who can see/hear you and have line of sight to the target can immediately use a Reaction to make a single ranged Strike against that target. These attacks are made with a -2 penalty due to the haste of the volley.\n\n**Special** If you have the Envoy Directives ability, you may also make a ranged Strike as a free action."}]}}',	'You command the flow of the entire battle.',	'0',	17,	'Mon Calamari, Auditory, Visual, Mental',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftSquadCommander", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftWyrwulfMetamorphosis',	'ancCodruJi',	'Wyrwulf Metamorphosis',	'<div class="power-card-display">
  <header class="power-card-header">
    <div class="power-title-line">
      <h3 class="power-name">Wyrwulf Metamorphosis</h3>
      <span class="power-action-cost">[one-action]</span>
    </div>
    <div class="power-meta-top">
      <span class="power-level">Level 17</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="power-card-traits">
    <span class="trait-tag">Codru-Ji</span>
    <span class="trait-tag">Polymorph</span>
  </div>

  <div class="power-card-meta-grid">
    <div>
      <strong>Frequency</strong>
      <span>Once per day.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="power-card-divider" />

  <div class="power-card-description markdown-body">
    You tap into your genetic history, temporarily reverting to a hybrid Wyrwulf state. For 1 minute:<br><br>Your Speed increases by 20 feet.<br>You gain a bite attack (1d10 piercing).<br>You gain Resistance 10 to Physical damage.<br>You can Trip enemies as a Free Action when you hit them with a bite.
  </div>
</div>',	'{"action": {"grant": [{"id": "actWyrwulfMetamorphosis", "name": "Wyrwulf Metamorphosis", "traits": "Codru-Ji, Polymorph", "frequency": "Once per day.", "action_cost": "[one-action]", "description": "You tap into your genetic history, temporarily reverting to a hybrid Wyrwulf state. For 1 minute:\n\nYour Speed increases by 20 feet.\nYou gain a bite attack (1d10 piercing).\nYou gain Resistance 10 to Physical damage.\nYou can Trip enemies as a Free Action when you hit them with a bite."}]}}',	'You tap into your genetic history, temporarily reverting to a hybrid Wyrwulf state.',	'0',	17,	'Codru-Ji, Polymorph',	NULL),
('aftIndignantSpirit',	'ancAnzellan',	'Indignant Spirit',	'You are small, but your personality is massive. You gain a +1 circumstance bonus to Will saves against Fear effects. If you roll a Success on a save against Fear, you get a Critical Success instead. When you remove a Frightened condition from yourself, you can shout "Hey Hey!" to Demoralize an adjacent enemy as a free action.',	NULL,	'You are small, but your personality is massive.',	'0',	1,	'Anzellan, Emotion, Mental',	NULL),
('aftUnderfootDodger',	'ancAnzellan',	'Underfoot Dodger',	'You are used to weaving between the stomping feet of larger species. You can move through the spaces of creatures of Small size or larger. When you end your turn in the space of a creature at least one size larger than you, you gain Lesser Cover (+1 AC) against all attacks coming from outside that square.',	NULL,	'You are used to weaving between the stomping feet of larger species.',	'0',	1,	'Anzellan',	NULL),
('aftPocketStowaway',	'ancAnzellan',	'Pocket Stowaway',	'You are an expert at being carried. You can share a space with a willing ally of Medium size or larger. While occupying their space, you move with them when they move (you do not spend actions). You effectively have Standard Cover while occupying their space, but you cannot move on your own until you Dismount (1 Action).',	NULL,	'You are an expert at being carried.',	'0',	1,	'Anzellan',	NULL),
('aftVentCrawler',	'ancAnzellan',	'Vent Crawler',	'If there is airflow, there is a way in. You gain a Climb Speed equal to half your land speed. You can move at full speed while Squeezing, and you do not take the -2 penalty to AC and Reflex saves usually associated with Squeezing.',	'{"speed": [{"climb": "{((speed // 5) // 2) * 5}"}]}',	'If there is airflow, there is a way in.',	'0',	5,	'Anzellan',	NULL),
('aftDroidsmith',	'ancAnzellan',	'Droidsmith',	'You treat droids not as tools, but as cousins. You become trained in Crafting and gain the Combat Repair skill feat. You gain a +1 circumstance bonus to hecks to Repair items with the Tech trait or to Treat Wounds on creatures with the Construct trait (using Crafting instead of Medicine).',	'{"feat": {"fixed": [{"id": "feaCombatRepair", "type": "skill"}]}, "skill": [{"id": "sklCrafting", "rank": "Trained"}]}',	'You treat droids not as tools, but as cousins.',	'0',	1,	'Anzellan',	NULL),
('aftAggressiveBarter',	'ancSquib',	'Aggressive Barter',	'You can bewilder opponents with rapid-fire offers, nonsensical trades, and insults disguised as bargains. You can use Deception to Feint against a creature within 30 feet that shares a language with you.

<strong>Critical Success</strong> The target is Off-Guard against all melee attacks until the end of your next turn. Additionally, the target is Stupefied 2 for the same duration.

<strong>Success</strong> The target is Off-Guard against your next melee attack that turn. Additionally, the target is Stupefied 1 until the start of your next turn.

<strong>Critical Failure</strong> You confuse yourself with your own logic. You are Off-Guard until the start of your next turn.',	NULL,	'You can bewilder opponents with rapid-fire offers, nonsensical trades, and insults disguised as bargains.',	'0',	5,	'Auditory, Emotion, Linguistic, Mental, Squib',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftConfidentHaggler", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftStaticAdaptation',	'ancAnzellan',	'Static Adaptation',	'Generations of working on live wires have toughened your skin. You gain resistance to Electricity damage equal to half your level (minimum 1).',	'{"defense": {"resistance": [{"type": "Electricity", "amount": "{max(1, level // 2)}", "source": "Static Adaptation (Ancestry Feat)"}]}}',	'Generations of working on live wires have toughened your skin.',	'0',	1,	'Anzellan',	NULL),
('aftPrecognitiveVisions',	'ancIktotchi',	'Precognitive Visions',	'You are gifted (or cursed) with vague visions of future events.  When you make your daily preparations, you can change the subject of your visions.  Work with your GM to refine the subject of your visions if need be.

You gain the Flash of Insight reaction.

<div class="power-card-display">
  <header class="power-card-header">
    <div class="power-title-line">
      <h3 class="power-name">Precognitive Visions</h3>
      <span class="power-action-cost">[reaction]</span>
    </div>
    <div class="power-meta-top">
      <span class="power-level">Level 1</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <div class="power-card-traits">
    <span class="trait-tag">Iktotchi</span>
  </div>

  <div class="power-card-meta-grid">
    <div>
      <strong>Trigger</strong>
      <span>You are about to attempt a saving throw, Perception check, or skill check.</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <strong>Frequency</strong>
      <span>Once per hour.</span>
    </div>
    <div>
      <strong>Requirements</strong>
      <span>The pending check is related to the subject of your visions (subject to GM approval).</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="power-card-divider" />

  <div class="power-card-description markdown-body">
    You see the outcome a split second before it happens. You gain a +2 circumstance bonus to the triggering check or Saving Throw.
  </div>
</div>',	'{"action": {"grant": [{"id": "actPrecognitiveVisions", "name": "Precognitive Visions", "traits": "Iktotchi", "trigger": "You are about to attempt a saving throw, Perception check, or skill check.", "frequency": "Once per hour.", "action_cost": "[reaction]", "description": "You see the outcome a split second before it happens. You gain a +2 circumstance bonus to the triggering check or Saving Throw.", "requirements": "The pending check is related to the subject of your visions (subject to GM approval)."}]}}',	'You are gifted (or cursed) with vague visions of future events.',	'0',	1,	'Iktotchi',	NULL),
('aftQuantumTinkering',	'ancAnzellan',	'Quantum Tinkering',	'You can fix things that shouldn''t be fixable. Once per day, you can Repair 25 HP to a destroyed item or 50HP to an item that isn''t destroyed. If you use this ability on a destroyed Construct, you can revive it with 1 HP if you succeed at a Very Hard Crafting check for your level.',	NULL,	'You can fix things that shouldn''t be fixable. ',	'0',	17,	'Anzellan',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftDroidsmith", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftGrimIsolation',	'ancShistavanen',	'Grim Isolation',	'You fight best when the odds are against you. As long as you have no allies within 15 feet of you, you gain a +2 circumstance bonus to damage rolls with melee weapons and unarmed attacks. Additionally, you cannot be Flanked by creatures of your level or lower unless they are using a collaborative tactic (like the Gang Up feat).',	NULL,	'You fight best when the odds are against you.',	'0',	9,	'Shistavanen',	'[{"feat": [{"id": "aftSolitarySurvivor", "type": "ancestry"}]}]'),
('aftShistavanenClaws',	'ancShistavanen',	'Wolfman''s Claws',	'You have honed your natural weapons for combat. You gain a Claw unarmed attack that deals 1d4 Slashing damage. Your claws are in the Brawling group and have the Agile and Finesse traits.',	'{"weapon": [{"id": "natWolfmansClaws", "bulk": null, "name": "Wolfman''s Claws", "type": "Melee", "group": "Brawling", "hands": "1", "traits": "Agile, Finesse", "category": "Unarmed", "damagedie": "d4", "damagetype": "S", "description": "You have honed your natural weapons for combat. You gain a Claw unarmed attack that deals 1d4 Slashing damage. Your claws are in the Brawling group and have the Agile and Finesse traits."}]}',	'You have honed your natural weapons for combat.',	'0',	1,	'Shistavanen',	NULL),
('aftStalkersPounce',	'ancShistavanen',	'Stalker’s Pounce',	'You burst from the shadows with terrifying speed. You can Stride up to your Speed towards an enemy. If you end this movement within melee reach of the enemy, you can make a melee Strike. If this attack hits, the target is Off-Guard until the start of your next turn.

<div class="power-card-display">
  <header class="power-card-header">
    <div class="power-title-line">
      <h3 class="power-name">Stalker’s Pounce</h3>
      <span class="power-action-cost">[one-action]</span>
